const DATA = {"items":[{"id":"q001_v","conceptId":"tx_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Pulseless ventricular fibrillation/tachycardia is a shockable arrest rhythm; high-quality CPR with early defibrillation is the only intervention that restores perfusion. Drugs are secondary.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>The nurse obtains a rhythm strip on a patient who suddenly becomes unresponsive. The monitor shows a wide, bizarre, rapid waveform with no identifiable P waves, no measurable PR interval, and a chaotic baseline. The patient has no palpable pulse. What is the nurse's <strong>priority</strong> action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q001_0","text":"Administer IV amiodarone"},{"id":"q001_1","text":"Begin high-quality CPR and prepare to defibrillate"},{"id":"q001_2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q001_3","text":"Administer IV atropine"}],"correct":["q001_1"]},{"id":"q002_v","conceptId":"tx_stable_vt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> With a palpable pulse and stable vitals, ventricular tachycardia is treated with antidysrhythmics such as amiodarone. CPR/defibrillation are for pulseless patients and cardioversion for unstable ones.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>A patient with ventricular tachycardia is awake, alert, and reports palpitations. Blood pressure is 118/70 mm Hg and the patient denies chest pain or dyspnea. Which action would the nurse anticipate <strong>first</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q002_0","text":"Immediate defibrillation"},{"id":"q002_1","text":"Begin chest compressions"},{"id":"q002_2","text":"Administer antidysrhythmic medication such as amiodarone as ordered"},{"id":"q002_3","text":"Withhold all treatment and continue to monitor only"}],"correct":["q002_2"]},{"id":"q003_v","conceptId":"tx_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asystole is a non-shockable rhythm; treatment is high-quality CPR and epinephrine. Defibrillation is useless when there is no electrical activity.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>The monitor shows a flat line with no electrical activity in three leads, and the patient is unresponsive, apneic, and pulseless. Which action should the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q003_0","text":"Defibrillate immediately at 200 joules"},{"id":"q003_1","text":"Begin CPR and administer epinephrine as ordered"},{"id":"q003_2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q003_3","text":"Administer IV adenosine"}],"correct":["q003_1"]},{"id":"q004_v","conceptId":"tx_pea","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PEA is non-shockable: provide CPR and aggressively identify and treat reversible causes (the H's and T's). Shock and atropine are not indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is unresponsive and pulseless, but the monitor shows an organized rhythm at a rate of 70/min. Which action best reflects management of pulseless electrical activity (PEA)?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q004_0","text":"Defibrillate, since an organized rhythm is present"},{"id":"q004_1","text":"Begin CPR and search for reversible causes (the H's and T's)"},{"id":"q004_2","text":"Administer atropine to increase the rate"},{"id":"q004_3","text":"Withhold CPR because the rhythm is organized"}],"correct":["q004_1"]},{"id":"q005_v","conceptId":"tx_svt_stable","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> For STABLE SVT, begin with vagal maneuvers (bearing down/Valsalva); escalate to adenosine and reserve cardioversion for instability.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>A patient with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) is alert with a blood pressure of 124/78 mm Hg. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate <strong>first</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q005_0","text":"Immediate synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q005_1","text":"Vagal maneuvers such as bearing down"},{"id":"q005_2","text":"IV push of unsynchronized shock"},{"id":"q005_3","text":"Preparation for emergent pacing"}],"correct":["q005_1"]},{"id":"q006_v","conceptId":"adenosine_admin","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Adenosine has an ultra-short half-life, so it must be given as a rapid IV push over 1-2 seconds followed immediately by a fast saline flush.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The provider orders IV adenosine for a patient with stable SVT. Which technique reflects correct administration of this medication?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q006_0","text":"Slow IV infusion over 30 minutes"},{"id":"q006_1","text":"Rapid IV push over 1 to 2 seconds followed by a rapid saline flush"},{"id":"q006_2","text":"Intramuscular injection into the deltoid"},{"id":"q006_3","text":"Subcutaneous injection followed by massage"}],"correct":["q006_1"]},{"id":"q007_v","conceptId":"afib_anticoag_why","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The chief danger of atrial fibrillation is blood stasis in the atria forming a thrombus that can embolize and cause a stroke; this risk drives the plan of care.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is newly diagnosed with atrial fibrillation. Which complication is the <strong>priority</strong> concern that drives the plan of care?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q007_0","text":"Embolic stroke from atrial thrombus formation"},{"id":"q007_1","text":"Hypoglycemia"},{"id":"q007_2","text":"Hyperkalemia"},{"id":"q007_3","text":"Pressure injury"}],"correct":["q007_0"]},{"id":"q008_v","conceptId":"afib_precardiovert","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> If A-fib has lasted longer than 48 hours (or is of unknown duration), a clot may already exist. The patient must be anticoagulated (or cleared by TEE) before cardioversion to avoid dislodging an embolus.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has been in atrial fibrillation for an unknown duration that is likely greater than 48 hours. The provider is considering elective cardioversion. Which action does the nurse anticipate <strong>before</strong> cardioversion?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q008_0","text":"Withhold all anticoagulation until after the procedure"},{"id":"q008_1","text":"Ensure adequate anticoagulation (or a transesophageal echocardiogram) before cardioversion"},{"id":"q008_2","text":"Administer atropine immediately before the shock"},{"id":"q008_3","text":"Deliver an unsynchronized shock"}],"correct":["q008_1"]},{"id":"q009_v","conceptId":"tx_asym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus bradycardia is a normal, benign finding in a conditioned, asymptomatic athlete. Document and continue to monitor; no treatment is needed.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>A 20-year-old athlete has a routine ECG showing sinus bradycardia at a rate of 52/min and a blood pressure of 116/68 mm Hg. The patient denies dizziness, chest pain, or syncope. Which action would the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q009_0","text":"Administer atropine"},{"id":"q009_1","text":"Prepare for transcutaneous pacing"},{"id":"q009_2","text":"Document the finding and continue to monitor"},{"id":"q009_3","text":"Notify the provider for emergency intervention"}],"correct":["q009_2"]},{"id":"q010_v","conceptId":"tx_sym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> For symptomatic bradycardia with hypotension and dizziness, atropine is the first-line medication.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>A patient has sinus bradycardia at a rate of 38/min with a blood pressure of 84/50 mm Hg and reports dizziness and lightheadedness. Which medication should the nurse anticipate administering <strong>first</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q010_0","text":"Atropine"},{"id":"q010_1","text":"Adenosine"},{"id":"q010_2","text":"Metoprolol"},{"id":"q010_3","text":"Amiodarone"}],"correct":["q010_0"]},{"id":"q011_v","conceptId":"tx_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A consistently prolonged PR interval (>0.20 sec) in which every P wave still conducts is first-degree AV block. It is usually benign, so the nurse documents and monitors.</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>A patient has a sinus rhythm with a heart rate of 70/min. The nurse determines the PR interval is 0.24 seconds and is unchanged. The patient is asymptomatic. Which action would the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q011_0","text":"Notify the provider immediately of complete heart block"},{"id":"q011_1","text":"Document the first-degree AV block and continue to monitor the patient"},{"id":"q011_2","text":"Give atropine per protocol"},{"id":"q011_3","text":"Prepare the patient for temporary pacemaker insertion"}],"correct":["q011_1"]},{"id":"q012_v","conceptId":"tx_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Independent P waves and QRS complexes with a slow ventricular rate is third-degree (complete) heart block; with instability, the priority is transcutaneous pacing.</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>The monitor shows a rhythm in which the P waves and QRS complexes occur independently of one another, with a ventricular rate of 30/min. The patient is hypotensive and confused. Which action should the nurse prepare for?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q012_0","text":"Administer a beta-blocker to control the rate"},{"id":"q012_1","text":"Prepare for transcutaneous pacing"},{"id":"q012_2","text":"Encourage vagal maneuvers"},{"id":"q012_3","text":"Withhold treatment and continue monitoring"}],"correct":["q012_1"]},{"id":"q013_v","conceptId":"pvc_k","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Multifocal PVCs are frequently triggered by hypokalemia. A potassium of 2.8 mEq/L is the most important value to report and correct to prevent lethal dysrhythmias.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with frequent multifocal premature ventricular contractions (PVCs) has the following laboratory results. Which value is <strong>most</strong> important for the nurse to report to the provider?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q013_0","text":"Serum sodium of 138 mEq/L"},{"id":"q013_1","text":"Serum chloride of 102 mEq/L"},{"id":"q013_2","text":"Serum potassium of 2.8 mEq/L"},{"id":"q013_3","text":"Serum glucose of 110 mg/dL"}],"correct":["q013_2"]},{"id":"q014_v","conceptId":"normal_intervals","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A normal QRS is less than 0.12 second; 0.16 second is abnormally wide and requires further investigation. The other intervals listed are within normal limits.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding from a newly admitted adult patient's ECG requires <strong>further investigation</strong> by the nurse?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q014_0","text":"RR interval of 0.8 second"},{"id":"q014_1","text":"PR interval of 0.18 second"},{"id":"q014_2","text":"QT interval of 0.40 second"},{"id":"q014_3","text":"QRS interval of 0.16 second"}],"correct":["q014_3"]},{"id":"q015_v","conceptId":"pacemaker_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Avoiding raising the arm on the incision side above shoulder level prevents dislodgement of the new pacemaker lead, indicating effective teaching.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is evaluating a patient's understanding of discharge instructions after placement of a permanent pacemaker. Which statement indicates teaching was <strong>effective</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q015_0","text":"“It will be several weeks before I can return to my usual activities.”"},{"id":"q015_1","text":"“I will avoid cooking with a microwave oven.”"},{"id":"q015_2","text":"“I will not lift the arm on the incision side above my shoulder until the provider says it is okay.”"},{"id":"q015_3","text":"“I no longer need to check my pulse at home.”"}],"correct":["q015_2"]},{"id":"q016_v","conceptId":"icd_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Vigorous active range-of-motion of the affected arm can dislodge the newly placed ICD lead; encouraging it shows the nurse needs further teaching.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The charge nurse is observing care of a patient after insertion of an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD). Which action by the nurse indicates a <strong>need for further teaching</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q016_0","text":"The nurse helps the patient apply for a medical alert device"},{"id":"q016_1","text":"The nurse teaches the patient to report any device discharge to the provider"},{"id":"q016_2","text":"The nurse encourages the patient to do vigorous active range-of-motion exercises of the affected arm"},{"id":"q016_3","text":"The nurse instructs the patient to avoid strong magnetic fields"}],"correct":["q016_2"]},{"id":"q017_v","conceptId":"tx_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a prolonged QT (torsades de pointes) is treated with IV magnesium sulfate.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>A patient develops a rapid polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a twisting QRS pattern (torsades de pointes) and a prolonged QT interval. Which medication should the nurse anticipate administering?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q017_0","text":"IV magnesium sulfate"},{"id":"q017_1","text":"IV calcium gluconate"},{"id":"q017_2","text":"IV atropine"},{"id":"q017_3","text":"Oral potassium"}],"correct":["q017_0"]},{"id":"q018_v","conceptId":"tx_stach_cause","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tachycardia is usually compensatory, so the nurse treats the underlying cause (pain, hypoxia, fever, hypovolemia) rather than the rate itself.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>A patient with a myocardial infarction develops chest pain and a new heart rate of 132/min in sinus tachycardia. Which action by the nurse is <strong>most appropriate</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q018_0","text":"Treat the underlying cause, such as pain or hypoxia"},{"id":"q018_1","text":"Immediately defibrillate the patient"},{"id":"q018_2","text":"Prepare for synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q018_3","text":"Administer atropine"}],"correct":["q018_0"]},{"id":"q019_v","conceptId":"tx_st_arrest","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A pulseless patient requires CPR regardless of what the monitor shows. Treat the patient, not the monitor.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>A patient is apneic and pulseless. The monitor shows sinus tachycardia at a rate of 130/min. Which action would the nurse take <strong>next</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q019_0","text":"Give a beta-blocker to slow the rate"},{"id":"q019_1","text":"Start cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR)"},{"id":"q019_2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q019_3","text":"Apply a non-rebreather mask and reassess"}],"correct":["q019_1"]},{"id":"q020_v","conceptId":"digoxin_tox","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Classic digoxin toxicity presents with nausea, anorexia, visual disturbances (halos/yellow vision), and bradycardia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is caring for a patient receiving digoxin. Which findings would alert the nurse to possible digoxin toxicity?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q020_0","text":"Hypertension and tachycardia"},{"id":"q020_1","text":"Nausea, anorexia, visual disturbances, and bradycardia"},{"id":"q020_2","text":"Polyuria and weight gain"},{"id":"q020_3","text":"Constipation and hyperglycemia"}],"correct":["q020_1"]},{"id":"q021_v","conceptId":"cardioversion_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> An awake patient undergoing elective synchronized cardioversion should receive sedation first. The synchronization mode stays ON and the energy setting is low.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) is alert with a blood pressure of 110/66 mm Hg, and synchronized cardioversion has been ordered. Which action should the nurse anticipate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q021_0","text":"Administer sedation before the procedure"},{"id":"q021_1","text":"Ensure the synchronization mode is turned off"},{"id":"q021_2","text":"Set the energy to 360 joules for the first shock"},{"id":"q021_3","text":"Deliver the shock during the T wave"}],"correct":["q021_0"]},{"id":"q026_v","conceptId":"low_co_cues","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Cues that a dysrhythmia is dropping cardiac output include hypotension, altered level of consciousness, chest pain, cool clammy skin, and dyspnea. A normotensive, asymptomatic patient is stable.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment findings indicate that a dysrhythmia is causing decreased cardiac output and hemodynamic instability? <em>Select all that apply.</em></div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"q026_0","text":"Hypotension"},{"id":"q026_1","text":"New-onset confusion or decreased level of consciousness"},{"id":"q026_2","text":"Chest pain"},{"id":"q026_3","text":"Blood pressure of 122/78 mm Hg with no symptoms"},{"id":"q026_4","text":"Cool, clammy, diaphoretic skin"},{"id":"q026_5","text":"Shortness of breath"}],"correct":["q026_0","q026_1","q026_2","q026_3","q026_4","q026_5"]},{"id":"q027_v","conceptId":"cloze_rhythm_action","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A wide, fast, regular, pulseless rhythm is pulseless ventricular tachycardia, requiring immediate CPR and defibrillation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is interpreting a rhythm strip for an unresponsive patient. The strip shows a wide, regular, rapid waveform at a rate of 180/min with no identifiable P waves, and the patient has no pulse. The nurse identifies this rhythm as [rhythm]. Because the patient is pulseless, the priority action is to [action].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"response_rhythm","options":[{"id":"q027_rhythm_0","text":"pulseless ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"q027_rhythm_1","text":"sinus bradycardia"},{"id":"q027_rhythm_2","text":"first-degree AV block"},{"id":"q027_rhythm_3","text":"normal sinus rhythm"}],"correct":"q027_rhythm_0"},{"key":"response_action","options":[{"id":"q027_action_0","text":"begin CPR and defibrillate"},{"id":"q027_action_1","text":"administer oral metoprolol"},{"id":"q027_action_2","text":"document and reassess in 1 hour"},{"id":"q027_action_3","text":"perform a vagal maneuver"}],"correct":"q027_action_0"}]},{"id":"q030_v","conceptId":"match_rhythms","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Each rhythm is identified by its hallmark strip features (atrial activity, rate, QRS width, and P-to-QRS relationship).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each cardiac rhythm with its correct description.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"q030_l0","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"q030_l1","text":"Ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"q030_l2","text":"Sinus bradycardia"},{"id":"q030_l3","text":"Third-degree AV block"},{"id":"q030_l4","text":"Asystole"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"q030_r0","text":"Rapid, chaotic atrial activity with an irregularly irregular ventricular response"},{"id":"q030_r1","text":"Wide QRS complexes at a rate of 150-250/min, often associated with hemodynamic instability"},{"id":"q030_r2","text":"Regular rhythm under 60/min with normal P waves"},{"id":"q030_r3","text":"No relationship between P waves and QRS complexes; atria and ventricles beat independently"},{"id":"q030_r4","text":"Absence of electrical activity; flat line on the ECG"}],"pairs":[["q030_l0","q030_r0"],["q030_l1","q030_r1"],["q030_l2","q030_r2"],["q030_l3","q030_r3"],["q030_l4","q030_r4"]]},{"id":"q031_v","conceptId":"match_blocks","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The AV blocks are distinguished by PR-interval behavior and the relationship between P waves and QRS complexes.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each type of heart block with its defining characteristic.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"q031_l0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"q031_l1","text":"Second-degree AV block, Type I (Mobitz I / Wenckebach)"},{"id":"q031_l2","text":"Second-degree AV block, Type II (Mobitz II)"},{"id":"q031_l3","text":"Third-degree (complete) heart block"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"q031_r0","text":"PR interval is consistently prolonged (greater than 0.20 second), but every P wave is followed by a QRS"},{"id":"q031_r1","text":"PR interval progressively lengthens until a QRS is dropped, then the cycle repeats"},{"id":"q031_r2","text":"Some P waves are not followed by a QRS, with no progressive PR lengthening; can progress to complete block"},{"id":"q031_r3","text":"No relationship between P waves and QRS complexes"}],"pairs":[["q031_l0","q031_r0"],["q031_l1","q031_r1"],["q031_l2","q031_r2"],["q031_l3","q031_r3"]]},{"id":"q034_v","conceptId":"divert_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Diverticulitis classically produces left-lower-quadrant pain (sigmoid colon), accompanied by fever and an elevated WBC count.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is admitted with suspected diverticulitis. Which assessment finding is <strong>most consistent</strong> with this diagnosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q034_0","text":"Pain in the lower left quadrant"},{"id":"q034_1","text":"Rebound tenderness in the lower right quadrant"},{"id":"q034_2","text":"Upper abdominal pain radiating to the back"},{"id":"q034_3","text":"Hyperactive bowel sounds in all quadrants"}],"correct":["q034_0"]},{"id":"q035_v","conceptId":"divert_acute_mgmt","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acute diverticulitis is treated with bowel rest (NPO/clear liquids), IV fluids, and antibiotics. Fiber and laxatives are withheld until the inflammation resolves.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is caring for a patient admitted with acute diverticulitis. Which intervention should the nurse expect to implement during the acute phase?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q035_0","text":"Encourage a high-fiber diet to promote bowel movements"},{"id":"q035_1","text":"Maintain the patient on NPO status and administer IV fluids"},{"id":"q035_2","text":"Administer daily laxatives to promote bowel movements"},{"id":"q035_3","text":"Apply heat to the abdomen to relieve cramping"}],"correct":["q035_1"]},{"id":"q036_v","conceptId":"divert_avoid_meds","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs (and corticosteroids) raise the risk of diverticular bleeding and perforation and should be avoided.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with diverticulitis asks the nurse about preventing future episodes once the acute infection has resolved. Which medication class should this patient generally avoid?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q036_0","text":"Acetaminophen"},{"id":"q036_1","text":"Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)"},{"id":"q036_2","text":"Stool softeners"},{"id":"q036_3","text":"Antihypertensives"}],"correct":["q036_1"]},{"id":"q037_v","conceptId":"divert_perforation","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A rigid, board-like abdomen with fever and hypotension indicates perforation with peritonitis, an emergency the provider must be told about immediately.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with diverticulitis suddenly develops a rigid, board-like abdomen, severe pain, fever, and hypotension. What does the nurse recognize this finding most likely indicates?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q037_0","text":"Resolution of the infection"},{"id":"q037_1","text":"Bowel perforation with peritonitis, requiring immediate notification of the provider"},{"id":"q037_2","text":"A normal response to antibiotics"},{"id":"q037_3","text":"Mild constipation"}],"correct":["q037_1"]},{"id":"q038_v","conceptId":"divert_diet","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> After recovery, a high-fiber diet with adequate fluids prevents recurrence by softening stool and reducing colonic pressure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient recovering from acute diverticulitis is being discharged. Which dietary teaching is appropriate for long-term prevention of recurrence (once fully recovered)?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q038_0","text":"Maintain a permanent clear liquid diet"},{"id":"q038_1","text":"Follow a high-fiber diet with adequate fluid intake"},{"id":"q038_2","text":"Avoid all fruits and vegetables permanently"},{"id":"q038_3","text":"Eat a low-fiber, high-fat diet"}],"correct":["q038_1"]},{"id":"q039_v","conceptId":"uc_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The hallmark of an ulcerative colitis flare is frequent bloody diarrhea from continuous mucosal inflammation of the colon and rectum.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with ulcerative colitis is admitted with an acute flare-up. Which finding does the nurse expect upon assessment?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q039_0","text":"Frequent, bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"q039_1","text":"Constipation and bloating"},{"id":"q039_2","text":"Severe right lower quadrant pain only"},{"id":"q039_3","text":"Nausea and vomiting without diarrhea"}],"correct":["q039_0"]},{"id":"q040_v","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In suspected toxic megacolon, enemas and cathartics are contraindicated because they can precipitate perforation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with ulcerative colitis develops a distended abdomen, high fever, tachycardia, and absent bowel sounds. The nurse suspects toxic megacolon. Which intervention is <strong>contraindicated</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q040_0","text":"Keeping the patient NPO"},{"id":"q040_1","text":"Administering a cleansing enema or cathartic"},{"id":"q040_2","text":"Preparing for nasogastric decompression"},{"id":"q040_3","text":"Administering IV fluids"}],"correct":["q040_1"]},{"id":"q041_v","conceptId":"uc_anemia","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chronic blood loss from the ulcerated colonic mucosa produces the iron-deficiency anemia commonly seen in ulcerative colitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is reviewing labs for a patient with a long history of ulcerative colitis and notes a hemoglobin of 8.2 g/dL. What is the most likely explanation for this anemia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q041_0","text":"Chronic blood loss from the inflamed, ulcerated colon"},{"id":"q041_1","text":"Excessive dietary iron intake"},{"id":"q041_2","text":"Dehydration"},{"id":"q041_3","text":"Overuse of acetaminophen"}],"correct":["q041_0"]},{"id":"q042_v","conceptId":"crohn_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's disease typically causes non-bloody diarrhea (often small-bowel, transmural), in contrast to the bloody diarrhea of ulcerative colitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with Crohn's disease is admitted with severe abdominal pain and frequent diarrhea. Which clinical manifestation would the nurse expect to find?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q042_0","text":"Weight gain"},{"id":"q042_1","text":"Non-bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"q042_2","text":"Generalized edema"},{"id":"q042_3","text":"Continuous inflammation limited to the rectum"}],"correct":["q042_1"]},{"id":"q043_v","conceptId":"crohn_complication","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever with severe abdominal pain and rebound tenderness suggests perforation/peritonitis, the most concerning complication requiring immediate intervention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is caring for a patient with Crohn's disease. Which complication is <strong>most concerning</strong> and requires immediate intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q043_0","text":"Chronic diarrhea and weight loss"},{"id":"q043_1","text":"Fatigue and anemia"},{"id":"q043_2","text":"Fever, severe abdominal pain, and rebound tenderness"},{"id":"q043_3","text":"Oral ulcers and joint pain"}],"correct":["q043_2"]},{"id":"q044_v","conceptId":"ibd_plan","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Monitoring stools for blood detects worsening bleeding and anemia during an IBD flare.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which nursing action will the nurse include in the plan of care for a patient admitted with an exacerbation of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q044_0","text":"Restrict all IV fluid intake"},{"id":"q044_1","text":"Monitor stools for blood"},{"id":"q044_2","text":"Encourage a high-fiber diet during the acute flare"},{"id":"q044_3","text":"Ambulate the patient six times daily"}],"correct":["q044_1"]},{"id":"q045_v","conceptId":"crohn_avoid_med","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs aggravate GI mucosal injury and can trigger Crohn's flares, so the order should be questioned; opioids or acetaminophen are preferred for pain.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with Crohn's disease is experiencing a severe flare and is started on total parenteral nutrition (TPN). For pain management, which medication should the nurse question if ordered?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q045_0","text":"IV opioid analgesic as ordered"},{"id":"q045_1","text":"Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID)"},{"id":"q045_2","text":"Acetaminophen within safe limits"},{"id":"q045_3","text":"Antispasmodic as ordered"}],"correct":["q045_1"]},{"id":"q046_v","conceptId":"divert_sepsis_first","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> With fever, tachycardia, and hypotension (early sepsis), restoring perfusion with IV fluids is the first priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is admitted with acute diverticulitis and has a temperature of 102.2 F (39 C), heart rate 118/min, and blood pressure 88/52 mm Hg. Which action should the nurse take <strong>first</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q046_0","text":"Administer IV fluids to support perfusion"},{"id":"q046_1","text":"Educate the patient about a high-fiber diet"},{"id":"q046_2","text":"Encourage ambulation"},{"id":"q046_3","text":"Provide a regular meal tray"}],"correct":["q046_0"]},{"id":"q048_v","conceptId":"uc_vs_crohn","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's can affect anywhere from mouth to anus with patchy, transmural skip lesions (causing fistulas/strictures), while ulcerative colitis is continuous and limited to the colon and rectal mucosa.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is educating a patient about the differences between ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease. Which statements by the patient indicate correct understanding? <em>Select all that apply.</em></div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"q048_0","text":"“Crohn's disease can affect any part of the GI tract, from the mouth to the anus.”"},{"id":"q048_1","text":"“Ulcerative colitis usually affects the inner lining of the colon and rectum.”"},{"id":"q048_2","text":"“Crohn's disease can cause skip lesions, while ulcerative colitis causes continuous inflammation.”"},{"id":"q048_3","text":"“Both conditions always cause mild symptoms that need no long-term treatment.”"},{"id":"q048_4","text":"“Crohn's disease can cause fistulas and strictures because the inflammation is transmural.”"}],"correct":["q048_0","q048_1","q048_2","q048_3","q048_4"]},{"id":"q052_v","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Distension, fever, tachycardia, and absent bowel sounds indicate toxic megacolon; the nurse keeps the patient NPO with NG decompression, gives IV fluids, and monitors abdominal girth and temperature/heart rate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div><strong>BOW-TIE.</strong> A patient with ulcerative colitis develops a markedly distended, tender abdomen, a temperature of 103 F (39.4 C), a heart rate of 130/min, and absent bowel sounds.<br><br><strong>Actions to Take</strong> (select two priority actions): [action1] and [action2].<br><strong>Potential Condition:</strong> The patient is most likely developing [condition].<br><strong>Parameters to Monitor</strong> (select two): [param1] and [param2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"response_action1","options":[{"id":"q052_action1_0","text":"Keep the patient NPO and prepare for nasogastric decompression"},{"id":"q052_action1_1","text":"Administer a cleansing enema"},{"id":"q052_action1_2","text":"Encourage a high-fiber meal"},{"id":"q052_action1_3","text":"Apply heat and ambulate the patient"}],"correct":"q052_action1_0"},{"key":"response_action2","options":[{"id":"q052_action2_0","text":"Administer IV fluids and notify the provider"},{"id":"q052_action2_1","text":"Give an oral laxative"},{"id":"q052_action2_2","text":"Withhold IV access"},{"id":"q052_action2_3","text":"Delay notifying the provider until morning rounds"}],"correct":"q052_action2_0"},{"key":"response_condition","options":[{"id":"q052_condition_0","text":"toxic megacolon"},{"id":"q052_condition_1","text":"mild constipation"},{"id":"q052_condition_2","text":"gastroesophageal reflux"},{"id":"q052_condition_3","text":"lactose intolerance"}],"correct":"q052_condition_0"},{"key":"response_param1","options":[{"id":"q052_param1_0","text":"Abdominal girth and distension"},{"id":"q052_param1_1","text":"Deep tendon reflexes"},{"id":"q052_param1_2","text":"Pupil size"},{"id":"q052_param1_3","text":"Hair distribution"}],"correct":"q052_param1_0"},{"key":"response_param2","options":[{"id":"q052_param2_0","text":"Temperature and heart rate"},{"id":"q052_param2_1","text":"Visual acuity"},{"id":"q052_param2_2","text":"Capillary refill of the toes only"},{"id":"q052_param2_3","text":"Gag reflex only"}],"correct":"q052_param2_0"}]},{"id":"q053_v","conceptId":"varices_room","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Esophageal varices can rupture and cause massive hematemesis, so having suction available at the bedside protects the airway from aspiration.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is admitting a patient with advanced cirrhosis and esophageal varices. Which intervention should be the <strong>priority</strong> when preparing the patient's room?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q053_0","text":"Place a bedpan and urinal at the bedside"},{"id":"q053_1","text":"Ensure suction equipment is readily available at the bedside"},{"id":"q053_2","text":"Set up oxygen therapy in case of respiratory distress"},{"id":"q053_3","text":"Obtain an order for enteral feeding to prevent malnutrition"}],"correct":["q053_1"]},{"id":"q054_v","conceptId":"varices_bleed_first","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Active variceal hemorrhage with hypotension is a circulation emergency; restoring volume with IV fluids and blood is the first action.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a history of liver cirrhosis is admitted with hematemesis and hypotension. The nurse suspects ruptured esophageal varices. Which intervention should the nurse implement <strong>first</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q054_0","text":"Prepare the patient for surgery"},{"id":"q054_1","text":"Administer IV fluids and initiate blood transfusion as ordered"},{"id":"q054_2","text":"Insert a nasogastric (NG) tube for gastric decompression"},{"id":"q054_3","text":"Place the patient in a supine position"}],"correct":["q054_1"]},{"id":"q055_v","conceptId":"octreotide","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Octreotide reduces splanchnic blood flow and portal pressure, which slows variceal bleeding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with bleeding esophageal varices is started on an octreotide infusion. What is the primary purpose of this medication?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q055_0","text":"To reduce portal pressure and slow variceal bleeding"},{"id":"q055_1","text":"To promote clotting by replacing vitamin K"},{"id":"q055_2","text":"To treat hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"q055_3","text":"To raise the blood pressure by vasoconstricting peripheral vessels"}],"correct":["q055_0"]},{"id":"q056_v","conceptId":"propranolol_varices","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Nonselective beta-blockers such as propranolol lower portal pressure to prevent future variceal bleeding episodes.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with liver cirrhosis is prescribed propranolol after an episode of bleeding esophageal varices. What is the purpose of this medication?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q056_0","text":"To reduce the risk of future bleeding episodes by lowering portal pressure"},{"id":"q056_1","text":"To prevent infection in the varices"},{"id":"q056_2","text":"To promote clotting and stop active bleeding"},{"id":"q056_3","text":"To treat hepatic encephalopathy"}],"correct":["q056_0"]},{"id":"q057_v","conceptId":"he_cause","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hepatic encephalopathy results from the failing liver's inability to clear ammonia, which accumulates and causes confusion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is assessing a patient with liver cirrhosis who presents with confusion and drowsiness. The nurse suspects hepatic encephalopathy. Which laboratory value is the most likely cause of this condition?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q057_0","text":"Low albumin level"},{"id":"q057_1","text":"High blood ammonia level"},{"id":"q057_2","text":"Decreased bilirubin"},{"id":"q057_3","text":"Elevated blood glucose"}],"correct":["q057_1"]},{"id":"q058_v","conceptId":"lactulose_effect","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The best evidence that lactulose is effective is improved mentation (the patient becomes alert and oriented), not a single laboratory value.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding indicates to the nurse that lactulose is <strong>effective</strong> for an older adult who has advanced cirrhosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q058_0","text":"The patient is alert and oriented"},{"id":"q058_1","text":"The patient denies nausea"},{"id":"q058_2","text":"The patient's bilirubin level decreases"},{"id":"q058_3","text":"The patient reports decreased itching"}],"correct":["q058_0"]},{"id":"q059_v","conceptId":"spiro_furo_k","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> With a potassium of 3.2 mEq/L, the nurse gives the potassium-sparing spironolactone and holds the potassium-wasting furosemide, then notifies the provider.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A serum potassium level of 3.2 mEq/L is reported for a patient with cirrhosis who has scheduled doses of spironolactone and furosemide due. Which action should the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q059_0","text":"Withhold both drugs"},{"id":"q059_1","text":"Administer both drugs"},{"id":"q059_2","text":"Administer the furosemide and hold the spironolactone"},{"id":"q059_3","text":"Administer the spironolactone and hold the furosemide"}],"correct":["q059_3"]},{"id":"q060_v","conceptId":"albumin_paracentesis","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Albumin given after a large-volume paracentesis prevents paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction and acute kidney injury.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis and ascites is undergoing a large-volume paracentesis. The nurse anticipates an order for IV albumin. What is the purpose of administering albumin after this procedure?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q060_0","text":"To prevent paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction and acute kidney injury"},{"id":"q060_1","text":"To directly treat hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"q060_2","text":"To stop esophageal variceal bleeding"},{"id":"q060_3","text":"To lower the serum ammonia level"}],"correct":["q060_0"]},{"id":"q061_v","conceptId":"meld","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Of the MELD components, creatinine (renal function) is the strongest predictor of mortality.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is reviewing the components of the MELD score used to prioritize liver transplant candidates. Which value is the strongest predictor of mortality?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q061_0","text":"Creatinine"},{"id":"q061_1","text":"Hemoglobin"},{"id":"q061_2","text":"Sodium"},{"id":"q061_3","text":"Albumin"}],"correct":["q061_0"]},{"id":"q062_v","conceptId":"transplant_teach","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Immunosuppression after transplant is lifelong; stopping it leads to organ rejection, so this statement reflects a need for further teaching.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is providing discharge instructions to a patient following a liver transplant. Which statement by the patient indicates a <strong>need for further teaching</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q062_0","text":"“I will take my medications for the rest of my life to prevent rejection.”"},{"id":"q062_1","text":"“I should avoid being around people who are sick.”"},{"id":"q062_2","text":"“I can stop taking my anti-rejection medications once my liver function is normal.”"},{"id":"q062_3","text":"“I should report any signs of infection or fever to my provider.”"}],"correct":["q062_2"]},{"id":"q063_v","conceptId":"transplant_rejection","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever with new jaundice and rising liver enzymes is the classic triad of transplant rejection and must be reported immediately.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding is <strong>most important</strong> for the nurse to communicate to the provider about a patient who received a liver transplant one week ago?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q063_0","text":"Mild right upper quadrant discomfort"},{"id":"q063_1","text":"Elevated blood glucose level of 150 mg/dL"},{"id":"q063_2","text":"Temperature of 100.5 F (38.1 C) with new jaundice and rising liver enzymes"},{"id":"q063_3","text":"No bowel movement for 1 day"}],"correct":["q063_2"]},{"id":"q064_v","conceptId":"acetaminophen_liver","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acetaminophen is hepatotoxic and hidden in many combination products, so it should be limited or avoided and all OTC products reconciled.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is being treated for chronic liver disease and reports taking several over-the-counter products. Which teaching point about acetaminophen is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q064_0","text":"Acetaminophen is completely safe in any dose for liver patients"},{"id":"q064_1","text":"Acetaminophen should be limited or avoided, and many combination products contain it"},{"id":"q064_2","text":"Acetaminophen should be substituted with daily NSAIDs"},{"id":"q064_3","text":"Acetaminophen has no maximum daily limit"}],"correct":["q064_1"]},{"id":"q065_v","conceptId":"coag_bleeding","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A high INR and low platelet count create high bleeding risk, so bleeding precautions (soft toothbrush, no rectal temperatures) are the priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis has an INR of 2.4 and a platelet count of 60,000/mm3. Which nursing intervention is a <strong>priority</strong> based on these findings?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q065_0","text":"Initiate bleeding precautions, such as a soft toothbrush and no rectal temperatures"},{"id":"q065_1","text":"Encourage vigorous tooth brushing and flossing"},{"id":"q065_2","text":"Administer intramuscular injections for comfort"},{"id":"q065_3","text":"Apply minimal pressure after venipuncture"}],"correct":["q065_0"]},{"id":"q066_v","conceptId":"sbp","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever with ascites suggests spontaneous bacterial peritonitis; a diagnostic paracentesis and empiric antibiotics such as ceftriaxone are anticipated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis and ascites develops a fever of 101.3 F (38.5 C) and diffuse abdominal pain. The nurse suspects spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP). Which intervention should the nurse anticipate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q066_0","text":"A diagnostic paracentesis and administration of antibiotics such as ceftriaxone"},{"id":"q066_1","text":"Immediate discharge home with oral antacids"},{"id":"q066_2","text":"Withholding all antibiotics until cultures result in 72 hours"},{"id":"q066_3","text":"Administration of a laxative only"}],"correct":["q066_0"]},{"id":"q067_v","conceptId":"ascites_path","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Portal hypertension combined with low albumin (low oncotic pressure) shifts fluid into the peritoneal cavity and tissues, producing ascites and edema.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with end-stage liver disease asks the nurse why their abdomen is so swollen and their legs are edematous. Which physiologic explanation is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q067_0","text":"Increased portal pressure and low albumin cause fluid to shift into the abdomen and tissues"},{"id":"q067_1","text":"The liver is producing too much albumin"},{"id":"q067_2","text":"The kidneys are excreting too much sodium"},{"id":"q067_3","text":"High blood glucose is pulling fluid into the abdomen"}],"correct":["q067_0"]},{"id":"q068_v","conceptId":"liver_failure_labs","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Expected ESLD findings include asterixis, thrombocytopenia, an elevated creatinine (hepatorenal risk), a prolonged PT, and worsening confusion. A normal BUN is not an expected abnormal cue.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A 56-year-old male with cirrhosis presents with confusion, jaundice, and abdominal swelling. Labs show elevated liver enzymes, increased bilirubin, and elevated ammonia. He is diagnosed with hepatic encephalopathy and ascites related to end-stage liver failure. Which findings should the nurse expect to observe? <em>Select all that apply.</em></div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"q068_0","text":"Asterixis"},{"id":"q068_1","text":"Platelet count of 50,000/mm3"},{"id":"q068_2","text":"Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) of 12 mg/dL"},{"id":"q068_3","text":"Serum creatinine of 2.5 mg/dL"},{"id":"q068_4","text":"Prothrombin time (PT) of 25 seconds"},{"id":"q068_5","text":"Worsening confusion and lethargy"}],"correct":["q068_0","q068_1","q068_2","q068_3","q068_4","q068_5"]},{"id":"q075_v","conceptId":"cirrhosis_bowtie","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> This patient has variceal hemorrhage with hepatic encephalopathy; priorities are airway/oxygen with large-bore IV access and octreotide with urgent EGD, while monitoring MAP/heart rate and hemoglobin/level of consciousness.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div><strong>BOW-TIE.</strong> Robert, 58, with alcoholic cirrhosis and hepatitis C, arrives confused with a distended abdomen and black, tarry stools. Vitals: HR 110/min, BP 88/54 mm Hg, RR 24/min, SpO2 92%. He has asterixis and jaundice.<br><br><strong>Actions to Take</strong> (select two priority actions): [action1] and [action2].<br><strong>Potential Condition:</strong> The patient is experiencing [condition].<br><strong>Parameters to Monitor</strong> (select two): [param1] and [param2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"response_action1","options":[{"id":"q075_action1_0","text":"Apply oxygen and establish two large-bore IV lines"},{"id":"q075_action1_1","text":"Insert an NG tube before addressing the varices"},{"id":"q075_action1_2","text":"Place the patient flat and withhold fluids"},{"id":"q075_action1_3","text":"Administer an oral laxative immediately"}],"correct":"q075_action1_0"},{"key":"response_action2","options":[{"id":"q075_action2_0","text":"Prepare an octreotide infusion and notify GI for urgent EGD"},{"id":"q075_action2_1","text":"Give a high-protein meal"},{"id":"q075_action2_2","text":"Delay all labs until morning"},{"id":"q075_action2_3","text":"Apply restraints and reassess in 4 hours"}],"correct":"q075_action2_0"},{"key":"response_condition","options":[{"id":"q075_condition_0","text":"variceal hemorrhage with hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"q075_condition_1","text":"acute appendicitis"},{"id":"q075_condition_2","text":"diabetic ketoacidosis"},{"id":"q075_condition_3","text":"pulmonary embolism"}],"correct":"q075_condition_0"},{"key":"response_param1","options":[{"id":"q075_param1_0","text":"Mean arterial pressure (MAP) and heart rate"},{"id":"q075_param1_1","text":"Deep tendon reflexes"},{"id":"q075_param1_2","text":"Pupil size only"},{"id":"q075_param1_3","text":"Bowel sounds only"}],"correct":"q075_param1_0"},{"key":"response_param2","options":[{"id":"q075_param2_0","text":"Hemoglobin and level of consciousness"},{"id":"q075_param2_1","text":"Daily weight only"},{"id":"q075_param2_2","text":"Serum calcium only"},{"id":"q075_param2_3","text":"Visual acuity"}],"correct":"q075_param2_0"}]},{"id":"q077_v","conceptId":"liver_functions","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Each cue of liver failure maps to a specific failed hepatic function (excretory, detoxification, synthetic, or portal hypertension).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each cue in liver failure with the failed liver function it represents.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"q077_l0","text":"Jaundice, dark urine, pale stools"},{"id":"q077_l1","text":"Asterixis, confusion, sleep-wake reversal"},{"id":"q077_l2","text":"Easy bruising, prolonged INR"},{"id":"q077_l3","text":"Ascites, splenomegaly, varices"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"q077_r0","text":"Failure of the excretory (bile-flow) function"},{"id":"q077_r1","text":"Failure of the detoxification function (rising ammonia)"},{"id":"q077_r2","text":"Failure of the synthetic (clotting factor) function"},{"id":"q077_r3","text":"Portal hypertension"}],"pairs":[["q077_l0","q077_r0"],["q077_l1","q077_r1"],["q077_l2","q077_r2"],["q077_l3","q077_r3"]]},{"id":"q078_v","conceptId":"leuk_infection_risk","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Although the WBC count may be high in leukemia, the cells are immature blasts that cannot fight infection, leaving the patient highly susceptible to infection.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is teaching a patient newly diagnosed with leukemia. The patient asks why they are at high risk for infection even though their white blood cell count is elevated. Which response is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q078_0","text":"“The high white cells are immature and cannot fight infection effectively.”"},{"id":"q078_1","text":"“The high white cell count protects you from all infections.”"},{"id":"q078_2","text":"“Your platelets are fighting the infection instead.”"},{"id":"q078_3","text":"“The lab result is most likely an error.”"}],"correct":["q078_0"]},{"id":"q079_v","conceptId":"neutropenia_priority","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Strict hand hygiene and neutropenic precautions are the priority. Raw produce, fresh flowers, and visitors who are ill are avoided.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) is neutropenic. Which nursing intervention is the <strong>priority</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q079_0","text":"Implementing neutropenic precautions, including strict hand hygiene"},{"id":"q079_1","text":"Encouraging a diet of fresh, raw fruits and vegetables"},{"id":"q079_2","text":"Placing fresh flowers in the room to improve mood"},{"id":"q079_3","text":"Allowing all visitors regardless of symptoms"}],"correct":["q079_0"]},{"id":"q080_v","conceptId":"neutropenic_fever","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Neutropenic fever is an oncologic emergency; the nurse obtains cultures and prepares to give broad-spectrum antibiotics within one hour.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A neutropenic patient with leukemia develops a temperature of 100.8 F (38.2 C). Which action by the nurse is the <strong>priority</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q080_0","text":"Document the low-grade fever and recheck in 4 hours"},{"id":"q080_1","text":"Treat the fever as an emergency: obtain cultures and prepare to give broad-spectrum antibiotics within 1 hour"},{"id":"q080_2","text":"Administer acetaminophen and take no further action"},{"id":"q080_3","text":"Encourage oral fluids only"}],"correct":["q080_1"]},{"id":"q081_v","conceptId":"chemo_monitor","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chemotherapy causes bone marrow suppression, so the nurse prioritizes monitoring the WBC count (infection risk) and platelet count (bleeding risk).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) is receiving chemotherapy. Which laboratory results should the nurse prioritize monitoring?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q081_0","text":"Hemoglobin and hematocrit levels"},{"id":"q081_1","text":"Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) and creatinine levels"},{"id":"q081_2","text":"White blood cell (WBC) count and platelet count"},{"id":"q081_3","text":"Serum electrolytes"}],"correct":["q081_2"]},{"id":"q082_v","conceptId":"thrombocytopenia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A platelet count of 18,000/mm3 requires bleeding precautions: a soft toothbrush, no invasive procedures, and fall prevention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with leukemia has a platelet count of 18,000/mm3. Which nursing intervention is most appropriate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q082_0","text":"Implement bleeding precautions, including a soft toothbrush and avoiding invasive procedures"},{"id":"q082_1","text":"Encourage contact sports for exercise"},{"id":"q082_2","text":"Administer intramuscular injections for comfort"},{"id":"q082_3","text":"Encourage vigorous nose blowing to clear secretions"}],"correct":["q082_0"]},{"id":"q083_v","conceptId":"bmt_immunosuppress","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> After an allogeneic stem cell transplant, immunosuppressive therapy prevents the body from rejecting the donor cells.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is undergoing an allogeneic bone marrow (stem cell) transplant and asks the nurse why immunosuppressive therapy is required after the transplant. What is the best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q083_0","text":"“It is used to prevent infection during recovery.”"},{"id":"q083_1","text":"“It helps prevent your body from rejecting the donor cells.”"},{"id":"q083_2","text":"“It increases your body's ability to produce red blood cells.”"},{"id":"q083_3","text":"“It prevents blood clot formation.”"}],"correct":["q083_1"]},{"id":"q084_v","conceptId":"hiv_cd4","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A CD4 count below 200 cells/mm3 with a new respiratory infection indicates progression to AIDS and a high risk for opportunistic infections such as PCP. The patient remains infectious and ART is not stopped.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with HIV has a CD4 count of 175 cells/mm3 and is admitted with a new fever and nonproductive cough. Which conclusion by the nurse is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q084_0","text":"The patient has progressed to AIDS and is at high risk for opportunistic infections such as PCP"},{"id":"q084_1","text":"The CD4 count is within the expected range, so the cough is unrelated to the HIV"},{"id":"q084_2","text":"The HIV is well controlled, so antiretroviral therapy can be paused"},{"id":"q084_3","text":"The low CD4 count means the patient is no longer contagious"}],"correct":["q084_0"]},{"id":"q085_v","conceptId":"hiv_pcp","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, a nonproductive cough, and dyspnea with hypoxia in advanced HIV point to Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia, the most common AIDS-defining respiratory infection. CMV causes retinitis, Candida causes thrush, and Cryptococcus causes meningitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with advanced HIV develops fever, a nonproductive cough, and shortness of breath with an oxygen saturation of 88%. Which opportunistic infection should the nurse suspect <strong>first</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q085_0","text":"Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP)"},{"id":"q085_1","text":"Cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis"},{"id":"q085_2","text":"Oral candidiasis (thrush)"},{"id":"q085_3","text":"Cryptococcal meningitis"}],"correct":["q085_0"]},{"id":"q086_v","conceptId":"art_adherence","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Consistent daily adherence to antiretroviral therapy is essential; missed doses promote viral resistance. HIV is controlled, not cured, by ART.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient newly started on antiretroviral therapy (ART) for HIV asks the nurse about taking the medications. Which teaching point is most important?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q086_0","text":"“Stop the medication once you feel better to avoid side effects.”"},{"id":"q086_1","text":"“Take the medications consistently every day; skipping doses can lead to drug resistance.”"},{"id":"q086_2","text":"“The medications cure HIV after a few weeks.”"},{"id":"q086_3","text":"“You only need the medication when you have symptoms.”"}],"correct":["q086_1"]},{"id":"q087_v","conceptId":"leuk_report","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Patients with leukemia should immediately report a fever of 100.4 F (38 C) or higher, new bleeding or bruising, and respiratory symptoms, which may signal life-threatening infection or hemorrhage.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is educating a patient with leukemia about signs and symptoms to report immediately to the provider. Which should be included? <em>Select all that apply.</em></div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"q087_0","text":"Fever of 100.4 F (38 C) or higher"},{"id":"q087_1","text":"New-onset bleeding gums or easy bruising"},{"id":"q087_2","text":"Fatigue and mild pallor"},{"id":"q087_3","text":"Shortness of breath and persistent cough"},{"id":"q087_4","text":"A small papercut that has stopped bleeding"}],"correct":["q087_0","q087_1","q087_2","q087_3","q087_4"]},{"id":"q090_v","conceptId":"match_leukemia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> ALL is most common in children; AML occurs in adults with rapid onset; CLL is indolent and seen in older adults; CML is associated with the Philadelphia chromosome.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each type of leukemia with its corresponding characteristic or population.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"q090_l0","text":"Acute lymphocytic leukemia (ALL)"},{"id":"q090_l1","text":"Acute myeloid leukemia (AML)"},{"id":"q090_l2","text":"Chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL)"},{"id":"q090_l3","text":"Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"q090_r0","text":"Common in children; rapid onset and progression"},{"id":"q090_r1","text":"Common in adults; rapid onset with poor prognosis if untreated"},{"id":"q090_r2","text":"Slow onset, often seen in older adults; may be asymptomatic"},{"id":"q090_r3","text":"Associated with the Philadelphia chromosome; treated with tyrosine-kinase inhibitors"}],"pairs":[["q090_l0","q090_r0"],["q090_l1","q090_r1"],["q090_l2","q090_r2"],["q090_l3","q090_r3"]]},{"id":"q091_v","conceptId":"match_hiv_oi","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Each opportunistic infection is matched to its hallmark presentation: PCP (respiratory), CMV (retinitis), Cryptococcus (meningitis), and Candida (oral thrush).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each HIV-related opportunistic infection or finding with its primary clinical feature.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"q091_l0","text":"Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP)"},{"id":"q091_l1","text":"Cytomegalovirus (CMV)"},{"id":"q091_l2","text":"Cryptococcus"},{"id":"q091_l3","text":"Candida albicans"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"q091_r0","text":"Fever, nonproductive cough, and shortness of breath"},{"id":"q091_r1","text":"Retinitis leading to vision changes"},{"id":"q091_r2","text":"Meningitis with headache and altered mental status"},{"id":"q091_r3","text":"Oral thrush (white plaques in the mouth)"}],"pairs":[["q091_l0","q091_r0"],["q091_l1","q091_r1"],["q091_l2","q091_r2"],["q091_l3","q091_r3"]]},{"id":"q092_v","conceptId":"dmards","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> DMARDs (such as methotrexate) slow disease progression and prevent joint destruction in rheumatoid arthritis. NSAIDs, corticosteroids, and opioids relieve symptoms but do not modify the disease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is reviewing the medication list of a patient newly diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis. Which class of medication is prescribed specifically to <strong>slow the progression</strong> of the disease and prevent joint destruction, rather than only relieve symptoms?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q092_0","text":"Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)"},{"id":"q092_1","text":"Disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs)"},{"id":"q092_2","text":"Corticosteroids"},{"id":"q092_3","text":"Opioid analgesics"}],"correct":["q092_1"]},{"id":"q093_v","conceptId":"mtx_teach","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Starting DMARD therapy early limits irreversible joint damage, making this the most important teaching point for a patient refusing methotrexate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>When the nurse brings medications to a patient with rheumatoid arthritis, the patient refuses the prescribed methotrexate, saying, “My arthritis isn't that bad yet. The side effects are worse than the disease.” Which information would be <strong>most</strong> important for the nurse to provide?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q093_0","text":"“Methotrexate is less expensive than some of the newer drugs.”"},{"id":"q093_1","text":"“It will take 4 to 6 weeks to see the therapeutic effects of methotrexate.”"},{"id":"q093_2","text":"“It is important to start methotrexate early to decrease the extent of joint damage.”"},{"id":"q093_3","text":"“Methotrexate has fewer side effects than the other drugs.”"}],"correct":["q093_2"]},{"id":"q094_v","conceptId":"ra_septic_joint","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A single hot, red, swollen joint with limited motion may indicate septic arthritis, an emergency requiring immediate evaluation, unlike the symmetric stiffness typical of rheumatoid arthritis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is assessing a patient with rheumatoid arthritis (RA). Which finding is <strong>most concerning</strong> and requires immediate intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q094_0","text":"Joint stiffness and swelling in the hands and wrists"},{"id":"q094_1","text":"Low-grade fever and fatigue"},{"id":"q094_2","text":"Pain, redness, and warmth in one knee with limited range of motion"},{"id":"q094_3","text":"Symmetric joint pain that improves with movement"}],"correct":["q094_2"]},{"id":"q095_v","conceptId":"ana","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A positive ANA supports a diagnosis of SLE but is sensitive rather than specific; it can be positive in other conditions, so it does not confirm lupus by itself.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with suspected systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) has a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and asks the nurse what it means. Which response is <strong>most accurate</strong>?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q095_0","text":"“A positive ANA supports the diagnosis, but it is not specific to lupus and can occur in other conditions.”"},{"id":"q095_1","text":"“A positive ANA confirms that you definitely have lupus.”"},{"id":"q095_2","text":"“A positive ANA measures how well your kidneys are working.”"},{"id":"q095_3","text":"“A positive ANA means your lupus is currently in remission.”"}],"correct":["q095_0"]},{"id":"q096_v","conceptId":"lupus_nephritis","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> New bilateral lower-extremity edema in SLE suggests lupus nephritis (renal involvement), the most serious, organ-threatening complication.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) presents with joint pain, fatigue, and new-onset swelling in both legs. Which complication is the nurse <strong>most concerned</strong> about?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q096_0","text":"Lupus nephritis"},{"id":"q096_1","text":"Osteoarthritis"},{"id":"q096_2","text":"Deep vein thrombosis (DVT)"},{"id":"q096_3","text":"Peripheral neuropathy"}],"correct":["q096_0"]},{"id":"q097_v","conceptId":"crp_prednisone","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> C-reactive protein is an inflammatory marker; a downward trend indicates that corticosteroids are reducing inflammation in rheumatoid arthritis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which laboratory result would the nurse monitor to determine if prednisone has been effective for a patient who has an acute exacerbation of rheumatoid arthritis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q097_0","text":"Blood glucose"},{"id":"q097_1","text":"C-reactive protein (CRP)"},{"id":"q097_2","text":"Serum electrolytes"},{"id":"q097_3","text":"Liver function tests"}],"correct":["q097_1"]},{"id":"q098_v","conceptId":"post_op_shock","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hypotension with tachycardia and pale, diaphoretic skin signals shock; the nurse activates the Rapid Response Team immediately.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse notices that a postoperative patient's blood pressure is 82/50 mm Hg, heart rate is 122/min, and the patient is diaphoretic and pale. What is the nurse's immediate action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q098_0","text":"Administer prescribed antihypertensive medications"},{"id":"q098_1","text":"Recheck vital signs in 30 minutes"},{"id":"q098_2","text":"Elevate the head of the bed and reassess in 10 minutes"},{"id":"q098_3","text":"Call the Rapid Response Team (RRT)"}],"correct":["q098_3"]},{"id":"q099_v","conceptId":"gi_bleed_escalate","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A repeat blood pressure that continues to fall despite ongoing resuscitation is the clearest evidence of continued hemorrhage and decompensation, requiring immediate escalation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A 64-year-old with portal hypertension is admitted for coffee-ground emesis. After 1 L of crystalloid and starting octreotide and ceftriaxone, vital signs are: BP 92/58 mm Hg, HR 126/min, RR 22/min, mentation intact, urine output 25 mL over 2 hours. Which measurement <strong>best</strong> indicates the patient is worsening and requires immediate escalation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q099_0","text":"A repeat blood pressure of 88/52 mm Hg 10 minutes later despite ongoing resuscitation"},{"id":"q099_1","text":"Heart rate of 126/min"},{"id":"q099_2","text":"Capillary refill of 3 seconds at the fingertips"},{"id":"q099_3","text":"Urine output of 12.5 mL/hr over 2 hours"}],"correct":["q099_0"]},{"id":"q100_v","conceptId":"rrt_criteria","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The Rapid Response Team is activated for symptomatic bradycardia, chest pain with dyspnea, new-onset confusion, and acute hypotension, but not for a stable low-grade fever or mild incisional pain.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which situations would warrant activation of the Rapid Response Team (RRT)? <em>Select all that apply.</em></div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"q100_0","text":"A patient with a heart rate of 45/min who reports dizziness"},{"id":"q100_1","text":"A patient with sudden chest pain and shortness of breath"},{"id":"q100_2","text":"A patient with a low-grade fever of 100.4 F after surgery who is otherwise stable"},{"id":"q100_3","text":"A patient with new-onset confusion and restlessness"},{"id":"q100_4","text":"A patient with a sudden drop in blood pressure to 78/40 mm Hg"},{"id":"q100_5","text":"A patient reporting mild incisional pain relieved by repositioning"}],"correct":["q100_0","q100_1","q100_2","q100_3","q100_4","q100_5"]},{"id":"q101_v","conceptId":"id_afib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows atrial fibrillation (irregularly irregular rhythm, no P waves, fibrillatory baseline). Blood stasis in the fibrillating atria can form a thrombus that embolizes and causes a stroke, so anticoagulation is central to the plan of care.</p>","imageRhythm":"afib","stem":"<div>The nurse observes the rhythm shown on a patient's monitor. The ventricular response is irregularly irregular with no identifiable P waves. Which complication is the <strong>priority</strong> concern for this patient?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/afib.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q101_0","text":"Embolic stroke from atrial thrombus formation"},{"id":"q101_1","text":"Hypoglycemia"},{"id":"q101_2","text":"Respiratory alkalosis"},{"id":"q101_3","text":"Hypercalcemia"}],"correct":["q101_0"]},{"id":"q102_v","conceptId":"id_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows ventricular fibrillation — chaotic, disorganized activity with no true QRS complexes. Pulseless VF is a shockable arrest rhythm requiring immediate high-quality CPR and early defibrillation.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>A patient suddenly collapses and the monitor displays the rhythm shown. The patient is unresponsive, apneic, and pulseless. What is the nurse's <strong>priority</strong> action?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/vfib.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q102_0","text":"Begin high-quality CPR and prepare to defibrillate"},{"id":"q102_1","text":"Administer IV adenosine"},{"id":"q102_2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q102_3","text":"Administer IV atropine"}],"correct":["q102_0"]},{"id":"q103_v","conceptId":"id_vtach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows monomorphic ventricular tachycardia (wide, regular, rapid complexes). Because the patient has a pulse and is hemodynamically stable, the anticipated treatment is an antidysrhythmic such as amiodarone; defibrillation/CPR are reserved for the pulseless patient and cardioversion for instability.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>The rhythm shown appears in a patient who is awake and alert, with a blood pressure of 130/78 mm Hg, reporting only palpitations. Which treatment should the nurse anticipate?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/vtach.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q103_0","text":"Immediate defibrillation"},{"id":"q103_1","text":"Begin chest compressions"},{"id":"q103_2","text":"Administer an antidysrhythmic such as amiodarone as ordered"},{"id":"q103_3","text":"No treatment is ever needed for this rhythm"}],"correct":["q103_2"]},{"id":"q104_v","conceptId":"id_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows third-degree (complete) AV block — atria and ventricles beat independently with a slow ventricular escape rate. A symptomatic, hypotensive patient requires transcutaneous pacing (atropine is often ineffective in complete block).</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>The monitor shows the rhythm below, in which the P waves and QRS complexes occur independently of one another at a ventricular rate of 38/min. The patient is dizzy and hypotensive. What is the nurse's <strong>priority</strong>?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/third_degree.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q104_0","text":"Prepare for transcutaneous pacing"},{"id":"q104_1","text":"Administer a beta-blocker"},{"id":"q104_2","text":"Encourage vagal maneuvers"},{"id":"q104_3","text":"Continue to monitor only"}],"correct":["q104_0"]},{"id":"q105_v","conceptId":"id_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows asystole (a flat line with no electrical activity). Asystole is non-shockable; treatment is high-quality CPR and epinephrine. Defibrillation is not indicated because there is no electrical activity to convert.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>A patient is unresponsive, apneic, and pulseless. The monitor shows the rhythm below. Which action should the nurse take?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/asystole.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q105_0","text":"Defibrillate immediately at 200 joules"},{"id":"q105_1","text":"Begin CPR and administer epinephrine as ordered"},{"id":"q105_2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q105_3","text":"Administer IV adenosine"}],"correct":["q105_1"]},{"id":"q106_v","conceptId":"id_sbrady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows sinus bradycardia (regular, normal complexes at a slow rate). Because this patient is symptomatic (hypotensive and lightheaded), atropine is the first-line medication.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>The rhythm below is seen in a patient who reports lightheadedness, with a heart rate of 45/min and a blood pressure of 84/50 mm Hg. Which medication should the nurse anticipate administering <strong>first</strong>?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/sinus_brady.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q106_0","text":"Atropine"},{"id":"q106_1","text":"Adenosine"},{"id":"q106_2","text":"Metoprolol"},{"id":"q106_3","text":"Amiodarone"}],"correct":["q106_0"]},{"id":"q107_v","conceptId":"id_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows supraventricular tachycardia (narrow QRS, very fast, regular, no discernible P waves). For a stable patient, the first intervention is a vagal maneuver, followed by adenosine if needed; cardioversion is reserved for instability.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>A patient is alert with a blood pressure of 118/72 mm Hg, and the monitor shows the narrow-complex tachycardia below at a rate of about 190/min. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate <strong>first</strong>?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/svt.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q107_0","text":"Vagal maneuvers such as bearing down"},{"id":"q107_1","text":"Immediate defibrillation"},{"id":"q107_2","text":"Synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q107_3","text":"Begin chest compressions"}],"correct":["q107_0"]},{"id":"q108_v","conceptId":"id_stach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows sinus tachycardia (regular, normal complexes with P waves at a fast rate). Sinus tachycardia is usually compensatory, so the nurse treats the underlying cause (pain, fever, hypovolemia) rather than the rate itself.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>The rhythm below is seen in a postoperative patient who is febrile and reports pain, with a heart rate of 130/min. Which action by the nurse is <strong>most appropriate</strong>?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/sinus_tach.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q108_0","text":"Treat the underlying cause, such as pain, fever, or hypovolemia"},{"id":"q108_1","text":"Immediately defibrillate the patient"},{"id":"q108_2","text":"Prepare for synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"q108_3","text":"Administer atropine"}],"correct":["q108_0"]},{"id":"q109_v","conceptId":"id_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows first-degree AV block — a consistently prolonged PR interval (>0.20 second) with every P wave still conducting to a QRS. It is usually benign in an asymptomatic patient, so the nurse documents and monitors.</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>The nurse measures a consistently prolonged PR interval of 0.34 second on the rhythm below, with a heart rate of 70/min. The patient is asymptomatic. Which action would the nurse take?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/first_degree.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q109_0","text":"Document the first-degree AV block and continue to monitor"},{"id":"q109_1","text":"Notify the provider for emergency pacing"},{"id":"q109_2","text":"Administer atropine immediately"},{"id":"q109_3","text":"Prepare for synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":["q109_0"]},{"id":"q110_v","conceptId":"id_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The strip shows torsades de pointes — polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a twisting, waxing-and-waning amplitude, associated with a prolonged QT. The treatment of choice is IV magnesium sulfate.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>A patient with a prolonged QT interval develops the polymorphic, twisting rhythm shown below. Which medication should the nurse anticipate administering?<p><img src=\"$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/web_resources/torsades.png\" alt=\"ECG rhythm strip\" width=\"640\"/></p></div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"q110_0","text":"IV magnesium sulfate"},{"id":"q110_1","text":"IV calcium gluconate"},{"id":"q110_2","text":"IV atropine"},{"id":"q110_3","text":"Oral potassium chloride"}],"correct":["q110_0"]},{"id":"varices_room_g0","conceptId":"varices_room","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Varices can rupture and bleed massively into the airway. Functioning suction to clear blood and protect the airway is the priority bedside setup.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with decompensated cirrhosis and known esophageal varices is being admitted. Which item is the priority to have ready at the bedside?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Wall suction set up and functioning"},{"id":"o1","text":"A bedside commode"},{"id":"o2","text":"An incentive spirometer"},{"id":"o3","text":"A high-protein meal tray"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_room_g1","conceptId":"varices_room","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The catastrophic risk is hemorrhage. Suction (airway) plus large-bore IV access (volume resuscitation) directly address it.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is preparing a room for a patient with bleeding-risk esophageal varices. Which combination best reflects readiness for the most life-threatening complication?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Suction and large-bore IV access"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sequential compression devices and a walker"},{"id":"o2","text":"An overbed table and a urinal"},{"id":"o3","text":"A glucometer and lancets"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_room_g2","conceptId":"varices_room","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Suction protects the airway if varices rupture; blood in the oropharynx is an aspiration and obstruction risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with grade III esophageal varices asks why suction is set up in the room. What is the nurse's best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"If the varices bleed, we may need to quickly clear blood from your mouth and airway.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"It is used to deliver your tube feeding.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It will help you cough up mucus from pneumonia.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It is a routine item in every room and not specific to you.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_room_g3","conceptId":"varices_room","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hematemesis signals active variceal bleeding; suction is critical to clear the airway of blood.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding in a patient with esophageal varices would make immediate bedside suction availability most critical?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sudden hematemesis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild ankle edema"},{"id":"o2","text":"Reported pruritus"},{"id":"o3","text":"Spider angiomata on the chest"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_room_g4","conceptId":"varices_room","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Of the listed items, only suction addresses the airway threat from a possible variceal bleed and must be in place first.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is setting up for a patient with varices. Which item, if missing, should the nurse obtain first before the patient arrives?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Functioning suction equipment"},{"id":"o1","text":"Extra pillows"},{"id":"o2","text":"A bedside fan"},{"id":"o3","text":"A whiteboard marker"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_bleed_first_g0","conceptId":"varices_bleed_first","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> After airway/oxygen, hemodynamic resuscitation with volume and blood is the priority in hypotensive variceal bleeding to restore perfusion before definitive endoscopic therapy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis is admitted with hematemesis and a BP of 84/50 mm Hg. After ensuring airway and applying oxygen, which action should the nurse take first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Establish large-bore IV access and begin fluid/blood resuscitation as ordered"},{"id":"o1","text":"Insert an NG tube for decompression"},{"id":"o2","text":"Place the patient flat and supine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Transport immediately to the OR"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_bleed_first_g1","conceptId":"varices_bleed_first","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Active hemorrhage with hypotension requires immediate IV volume and blood. Beta-blockers are for prophylaxis, not active bleeding, and would worsen the compensatory tachycardia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient with ruptured varices has HR 124/min, BP 86/52 mm Hg, and ongoing hematemesis. Which is the priority intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Volume resuscitation with crystalloid and blood products"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administration of an oral beta-blocker"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encouraging oral fluids"},{"id":"o3","text":"Placing the patient in Trendelenburg and waiting"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_bleed_first_g2","conceptId":"varices_bleed_first","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hypotension with poor perfusion indicates hemorrhagic shock requiring immediate resuscitation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment finding indicates a patient with bleeding esophageal varices needs immediate fluid and blood resuscitation rather than continued monitoring?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"BP 82/48 mm Hg with cool, mottled skin"},{"id":"o1","text":"BP 118/72 mm Hg, warm skin"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hemoglobin 13 g/dL"},{"id":"o3","text":"Heart rate 78/min"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_bleed_first_g3","conceptId":"varices_bleed_first","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Endoscopy is definitive, but the patient must be hemodynamically supported with volume/blood first so they can tolerate the procedure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with ruptured varices is hypotensive. The provider plans urgent endoscopy. What is the nurse's priority while preparing for the procedure?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Resuscitate with IV fluids and blood to stabilize perfusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"Keep the patient NPO and take no other action"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer lactulose for encephalopathy"},{"id":"o3","text":"Apply a warm compress to the abdomen"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"varices_bleed_first_g4","conceptId":"varices_bleed_first","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> With active hemorrhage and the access in place, transfusing to restore oxygen-carrying capacity and perfusion is the immediate priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient with active variceal bleeding has two large-bore IVs placed. Which order should the nurse implement first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Transfuse packed red blood cells per protocol"},{"id":"o1","text":"Schedule a dietary consult"},{"id":"o2","text":"Obtain a standing weight"},{"id":"o3","text":"Apply antiembolism stockings"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"octreotide_g0","conceptId":"octreotide","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Octreotide reduces splanchnic blood flow and portal pressure, decreasing variceal bleeding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with bleeding esophageal varices is started on an octreotide infusion. Which statement best describes its action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It causes splanchnic vasoconstriction, lowering portal pressure and bleeding"},{"id":"o1","text":"It replaces clotting factors directly"},{"id":"o2","text":"It neutralizes gastric acid"},{"id":"o3","text":"It sedates the patient for endoscopy"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"octreotide_g1","conceptId":"octreotide","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Octreotide's therapeutic goal is reduction of portal pressure to control variceal hemorrhage.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse is teaching a new graduate about octreotide for variceal bleeding. Which goal reflects its purpose?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Reduce portal venous pressure"},{"id":"o1","text":"Raise the systemic blood pressure to hypertensive levels"},{"id":"o2","text":"Increase urine output via diuresis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Lower the serum ammonia"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"octreotide_g2","conceptId":"octreotide","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Octreotide works hemodynamically by reducing portal/splanchnic pressure, not by altering coagulation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient asks why octreotide was ordered for their bleeding varices instead of a clotting medication. What is the nurse's best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"It lowers the pressure in the veins feeding the varices to slow the bleeding.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"It dissolves the clot that is blocking your liver.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It replaces the vitamin K your liver cannot make.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It treats the confusion caused by your liver disease.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"octreotide_g3","conceptId":"octreotide","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Effective octreotide therapy is reflected by slowed bleeding and hemodynamic stabilization from reduced portal pressure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which outcome indicates octreotide is having its intended effect in a patient with variceal bleeding?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Decreased active bleeding and stabilizing vital signs"},{"id":"o1","text":"Increased serum ammonia"},{"id":"o2","text":"A rise in INR"},{"id":"o3","text":"Increased abdominal girth"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"octreotide_g4","conceptId":"octreotide","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Octreotide is a somatostatin analog that reduces splanchnic blood flow and portal pressure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An octreotide infusion is running for a patient with esophageal varices. Which class of medication does octreotide belong to?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Somatostatin analog"},{"id":"o1","text":"Proton pump inhibitor"},{"id":"o2","text":"Beta-lactam antibiotic"},{"id":"o3","text":"Loop diuretic"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"propranolol_varices_g0","conceptId":"propranolol_varices","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Nonselective beta-blockers like propranolol provide secondary prophylaxis by lowering portal pressure, reducing rebleeding risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient who recovered from a variceal bleed is discharged on propranolol. What is the purpose of this medication?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"To lower portal pressure and reduce the risk of future bleeding"},{"id":"o1","text":"To stop active bleeding immediately"},{"id":"o2","text":"To treat existing hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"o3","text":"To prevent infection of the varices"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"propranolol_varices_g1","conceptId":"propranolol_varices","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Propranolol is preventive, taken consistently, and should not be stopped abruptly. It lowers portal pressure to reduce rebleeding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which teaching point should the nurse include for a cirrhotic patient starting propranolol for variceal prophylaxis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"This lowers the pressure in your veins to help prevent future bleeds; do not stop it abruptly.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Take this only when you notice bleeding.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"This medication cures your cirrhosis.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Double the dose if your heart rate feels fast.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"propranolol_varices_g2","conceptId":"propranolol_varices","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Beta-blockade lowers heart rate and portal pressure; the goal is no recurrent variceal bleeding with adequate rate control.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse evaluates the effectiveness of propranolol prescribed for variceal prophylaxis. Which assessment best reflects the intended therapeutic effect?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A controlled resting heart rate without recurrent bleeding"},{"id":"o1","text":"A rising heart rate over time"},{"id":"o2","text":"Increasing abdominal girth"},{"id":"o3","text":"Worsening jaundice"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"propranolol_varices_g3","conceptId":"propranolol_varices","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Nonselective blockade (beta-1 and beta-2) lowers cardiac output and produces splanchnic vasoconstriction, both reducing portal inflow and pressure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is a nonselective beta-blocker such as propranolol preferred over a selective agent for variceal prophylaxis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Beta-2 blockade adds splanchnic vasoconstriction that further lowers portal pressure"},{"id":"o1","text":"It has no effect on heart rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"It selectively dilates the portal vein"},{"id":"o3","text":"It replaces albumin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"propranolol_varices_g4","conceptId":"propranolol_varices","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Propranolol is a long-term prophylactic therapy; stopping it raises the risk of recurrent variceal bleeding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient on propranolol for varices asks when they can stop taking it. What is the nurse's best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"It is usually continued long-term to keep your bleeding risk low.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"You can stop once you feel well for a week.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Stop it the day after your endoscopy.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It is only needed during active bleeding.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"he_cause_g0","conceptId":"he_cause","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hepatic encephalopathy is driven by accumulation of ammonia and other nitrogenous toxins the failing liver cannot clear.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient is increasingly confused and drowsy. Which lab value most directly explains hepatic encephalopathy?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Elevated serum ammonia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Low serum sodium"},{"id":"o2","text":"Elevated bilirubin"},{"id":"o3","text":"Low hemoglobin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"he_cause_g1","conceptId":"he_cause","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A failing liver cannot detoxify ammonia into urea; rising ammonia crosses the blood-brain barrier and causes encephalopathy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse correlates a patient's worsening mentation with which pathophysiologic process in liver failure?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The liver cannot convert ammonia to urea, so ammonia accumulates and affects the brain"},{"id":"o1","text":"The liver overproduces albumin"},{"id":"o2","text":"Excess bilirubin is excreted in urine"},{"id":"o3","text":"The kidneys retain too much potassium"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"he_cause_g2","conceptId":"he_cause","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asterixis (flapping tremor) plus elevated ammonia is characteristic of hepatic encephalopathy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding supports a diagnosis of hepatic encephalopathy in a patient with cirrhosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Asterixis with an elevated ammonia level"},{"id":"o1","text":"A normal ammonia with brisk reflexes"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hyperglycemia with thirst"},{"id":"o3","text":"Low bilirubin with clear mentation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"he_cause_g3","conceptId":"he_cause","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Encephalopathy results from accumulation of gut-derived nitrogenous toxins (chiefly ammonia) that the diseased liver fails to clear.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is teaching a family why their cirrhotic relative is confused. Which explanation is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Toxins like ammonia build up because the liver cannot filter them, affecting the brain.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"The brain is bleeding from low platelets.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"High blood sugar is causing the confusion.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"The confusion is unrelated to the liver.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"he_cause_g4","conceptId":"he_cause","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Protein breakdown (including blood from a GI bleed) increases ammonia generation by gut bacteria, worsening encephalopathy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which dietary factor can precipitate or worsen hepatic encephalopathy by increasing ammonia production?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A large protein load, especially with GI bleeding"},{"id":"o1","text":"Increased water intake"},{"id":"o2","text":"A low-sodium diet"},{"id":"o3","text":"Vitamin C supplementation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lactulose_effect_g0","conceptId":"lactulose_effect","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Lactulose lowers ammonia by trapping it in the gut for excretion; effectiveness is shown by improved mentation. Stools should increase, not decrease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with hepatic encephalopathy is receiving lactulose. Which finding best indicates the drug is effective?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Improved level of consciousness and orientation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Decreased number of stools"},{"id":"o2","text":"A rise in serum ammonia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Decreased bilirubin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lactulose_effect_g1","conceptId":"lactulose_effect","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Lactulose acidifies the colon and produces soft stools that carry ammonia out; 2-3 stools/day with improving mentation indicates effectiveness.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse evaluates lactulose therapy. Which result reflects the expected therapeutic mechanism?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Two to three soft stools per day with clearing confusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"Constipation with formed stools"},{"id":"o2","text":"Decreased urine output"},{"id":"o3","text":"Increased serum potassium"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lactulose_effect_g2","conceptId":"lactulose_effect","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> No stooling and persistent lethargy suggest inadequate effect; lactulose must produce stools to remove ammonia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A confused cirrhotic patient has received lactulose for 24 hours. Which assessment finding would concern the nurse that the dose may need adjustment for under-treatment?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Persistent lethargy with no bowel movement"},{"id":"o1","text":"Three soft stools and improved orientation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild abdominal cramping with stooling"},{"id":"o3","text":"Patient now able to state the date"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lactulose_effect_g3","conceptId":"lactulose_effect","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Several soft stools per day is the therapeutic target, not an adverse effect to stop. It clears ammonia and is taken regularly.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which teaching point about lactulose should the nurse give the patient and family?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"The goal is a few soft stools daily; that is how it removes the toxins.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Call us if you have any diarrhea so we can stop it right away.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"This medication thins the blood.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Take it only when you feel confused.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lactulose_effect_g4","conceptId":"lactulose_effect","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> While soft stools are the goal, excessive watery stools risk dehydration and electrolyte loss, indicating the dose is too high and needs titration.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient on lactulose develops excessive watery stools and signs of dehydration. What does this indicate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The dose may be excessive and needs adjustment to avoid fluid/electrolyte loss"},{"id":"o1","text":"The drug is not working"},{"id":"o2","text":"The patient should double the dose"},{"id":"o3","text":"Lactulose should be replaced with a constipating agent permanently"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"spiro_furo_k_g0","conceptId":"spiro_furo_k","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> With hypokalemia, hold the potassium-wasting loop diuretic (furosemide) and give the potassium-sparing spironolactone. Notify the provider.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient on spironolactone and furosemide has a serum potassium of 3.1 mEq/L. Both doses are due. Which action is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Give the spironolactone and hold the furosemide"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give both as scheduled"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hold both medications"},{"id":"o3","text":"Give the furosemide and hold the spironolactone"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"spiro_furo_k_g1","conceptId":"spiro_furo_k","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Spironolactone spares potassium and is appropriate with hypokalemia; furosemide wastes potassium and should be held with provider notification.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with ascites is on combined spironolactone/furosemide therapy. Labs show K 3.3 mEq/L. What is the nurse's best action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administer spironolactone, hold furosemide, and notify the provider"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer furosemide, hold spironolactone"},{"id":"o2","text":"Give both and recheck in the morning"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hold both and give a potassium binder"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"spiro_furo_k_g2","conceptId":"spiro_furo_k","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Cirrhosis causes secondary hyperaldosteronism driving sodium/water retention; spironolactone (an aldosterone antagonist) targets this and spares potassium.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is spironolactone the preferred first-line diuretic in cirrhotic ascites?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It counters the secondary hyperaldosteronism of cirrhosis and spares potassium"},{"id":"o1","text":"It works faster than all loop diuretics"},{"id":"o2","text":"It directly lowers ammonia"},{"id":"o3","text":"It replaces albumin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"spiro_furo_k_g3","conceptId":"spiro_furo_k","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Spironolactone is potassium-sparing; with hyperkalemia it should be held and the provider notified. (Contrast with hypokalemia, where furosemide is held.)</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient's potassium is 5.6 mEq/L while on spironolactone and furosemide. Which action should the nurse anticipate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Holding the spironolactone and notifying the provider"},{"id":"o1","text":"Holding the furosemide only"},{"id":"o2","text":"Giving both medications"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administering additional potassium"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"spiro_furo_k_g4","conceptId":"spiro_furo_k","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Holding furosemide (wasting) and giving spironolactone (sparing) is the correct response to hypokalemia in this regimen.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse reviews diuretic doses for a patient with ascites and K 3.2 mEq/L. Which statement reflects correct clinical reasoning?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"I'll give the potassium-sparing drug and hold the potassium-wasting one.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"I'll give the loop diuretic to pull off more fluid.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Potassium does not affect which diuretic I give.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"I'll hold the spironolactone to raise the potassium.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"albumin_paracentesis_g0","conceptId":"albumin_paracentesis","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Removing large volumes of ascitic fluid causes fluid shifts; albumin maintains intravascular volume, preventing circulatory dysfunction and AKI.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Following a large-volume paracentesis, the nurse anticipates IV albumin. What is its purpose?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"To prevent post-paracentesis circulatory dysfunction and acute kidney injury"},{"id":"o1","text":"To treat hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"o2","text":"To stop variceal bleeding"},{"id":"o3","text":"To lower serum ammonia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"albumin_paracentesis_g1","conceptId":"albumin_paracentesis","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Large-volume removal risks paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction; albumin supports plasma oncotic pressure and intravascular volume.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is to have 6 liters of ascitic fluid removed. Why does the protocol include IV albumin?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The large fluid shift can drop intravascular volume; albumin maintains it"},{"id":"o1","text":"Albumin replaces clotting factors"},{"id":"o2","text":"Albumin treats the underlying cirrhosis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Albumin prevents infection of the puncture site"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"albumin_paracentesis_g2","conceptId":"albumin_paracentesis","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Albumin preserves intravascular volume after large-volume paracentesis, protecting blood pressure and renal perfusion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse explains to a patient why albumin is given after draining ascites. Which response is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"It keeps fluid in your bloodstream so your blood pressure and kidneys stay stable.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"It cures the liver scarring.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It is an antibiotic for the procedure.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It lowers the ammonia causing your confusion.\""}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"albumin_paracentesis_g3","conceptId":"albumin_paracentesis","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Omitting albumin after large-volume paracentesis raises the risk of paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction and AKI.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>After a large-volume paracentesis without albumin replacement, which complication is the patient at greatest risk for?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Acute kidney injury from circulatory dysfunction"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hyperkalemia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hepatic encephalopathy resolution"},{"id":"o3","text":"Polycythemia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"albumin_paracentesis_g4","conceptId":"albumin_paracentesis","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Albumin is indicated for large-volume paracentesis to prevent circulatory dysfunction; small diagnostic taps generally do not require it.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>For which paracentesis scenario is IV albumin most clearly indicated?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Removal of a large volume (e.g., > 5 L) of ascitic fluid"},{"id":"o1","text":"A small diagnostic tap of 30 mL"},{"id":"o2","text":"Any paracentesis regardless of volume, to treat encephalopathy"},{"id":"o3","text":"Only when the fluid is bloody"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"meld_g0","conceptId":"meld","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Among MELD components (bilirubin, INR, creatinine, +/- sodium), creatinine (renal function) is the strongest mortality predictor.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Reviewing MELD score components, which value is the strongest predictor of mortality in liver transplant prioritization?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Creatinine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sodium"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hemoglobin"},{"id":"o3","text":"Albumin"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"meld_g1","conceptId":"meld","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Creatinine reflects renal function; renal impairment in liver disease (e.g., hepatorenal syndrome) strongly predicts mortality.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The MELD score uses bilirubin, INR, and creatinine. Which body system does the creatinine component reflect, marking it a powerful mortality predictor?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Renal function"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hepatic synthetic function"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hematologic function"},{"id":"o3","text":"Pulmonary function"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"meld_g2","conceptId":"meld","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> MELD predicts 90-day mortality; higher scores indicate sicker patients with greater transplant priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse explains MELD-based transplant prioritization to a patient. Which statement is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"A higher MELD score means higher short-term mortality risk and higher transplant priority.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"A lower MELD means you are sicker.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"MELD is based mainly on your weight.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"MELD measures how long you have had cirrhosis.\""}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"meld_g3","conceptId":"meld","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The classic MELD score is calculated from bilirubin, INR, and creatinine (with sodium added in MELD-Na).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which set of laboratory values are the core components of the MELD score?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Bilirubin, INR, and creatinine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sodium, potassium, and chloride"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hemoglobin, hematocrit, and platelets"},{"id":"o3","text":"Albumin, total protein, and glucose"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"meld_g4","conceptId":"meld","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A rising creatinine raises MELD and signals deteriorating renal function with higher mortality risk and greater transplant urgency.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A transplant candidate's MELD score rises sharply, driven mainly by an increasing creatinine. How should the nurse interpret this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Worsening renal function signals higher mortality risk and increased priority"},{"id":"o1","text":"Improving liver function"},{"id":"o2","text":"Lower transplant priority"},{"id":"o3","text":"A laboratory error that can be ignored"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"transplant_teach_g0","conceptId":"transplant_teach","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Immunosuppression is lifelong; stopping it leads to rejection. This statement is incorrect and requires correction.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement by a post-liver-transplant patient indicates a need for further teaching?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Once my liver function is normal, I can stop my anti-rejection drugs.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"I will take immunosuppressants for life.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"I will avoid crowds and sick contacts.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"I will report any fever to my provider.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_teach_g1","conceptId":"transplant_teach","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Immunosuppressants must be taken consistently; skipping doses risks rejection. This statement needs correction.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is reinforcing discharge teaching after liver transplant. Which patient statement requires correction?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"I can skip a dose of tacrolimus if I feel fine.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"I will wash my hands frequently.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"I will keep all my lab appointments.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"I will report decreased urine output or fever.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_teach_g2","conceptId":"transplant_teach","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Correct understanding: lifelong daily immunosuppression that suppresses (not boosts) the immune system to prevent rejection.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement shows a post-transplant patient correctly understands their medication regimen?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"I must take my immunosuppressants every day for the rest of my life.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"I can stop these medications after one year.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"These medications boost my immune system.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"I only need them when I feel sick.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_teach_g3","conceptId":"transplant_teach","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> This reflects accurate understanding: immunosuppressants increase infection susceptibility, so avoiding sick contacts is appropriate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A liver transplant recipient says, \"I should avoid people who are sick because my medications lower my immunity.\" How should the nurse respond?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"That's correct; immunosuppression raises your infection risk, so avoiding sick contacts is important.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"That's incorrect; your medications boost immunity.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"You only need precautions for the first week.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"You can resume normal contact once you feel well.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_teach_g4","conceptId":"transplant_teach","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Immunosuppressed patients can deteriorate quickly and may have blunted signs; prompt reporting of fever/infection is essential.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which post-transplant teaching point about infection is most important to emphasize?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Report fever or signs of infection promptly because immunosuppression masks and worsens infection"},{"id":"o1","text":"Infections are no longer a concern after transplant"},{"id":"o2","text":"Stop immunosuppressants at the first sign of a cold"},{"id":"o3","text":"Antibiotics can replace anti-rejection drugs"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_rejection_g0","conceptId":"transplant_rejection","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, new jaundice, and rising liver enzymes suggest acute rejection or infection and require urgent evaluation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>One week after liver transplant, which finding is most important to report to the provider?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Temperature 100.6 F with new jaundice and rising liver enzymes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild incisional tenderness"},{"id":"o2","text":"Blood glucose 148 mg/dL"},{"id":"o3","text":"One day without a bowel movement"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_rejection_g1","conceptId":"transplant_rejection","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, RUQ pain, and rising bilirubin point to possible rejection or biliary complication and must be reported promptly.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse assesses a liver transplant recipient on postoperative day 8. Which cluster of findings warrants immediate provider notification?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fever, right upper quadrant pain, and increasing bilirubin"},{"id":"o1","text":"Appetite returning and ambulating in halls"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild fatigue that improves with rest"},{"id":"o3","text":"Surgical staples intact and dry"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_rejection_g2","conceptId":"transplant_rejection","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Increasing transaminases and bilirubin indicate graft dysfunction and possible rejection.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which laboratory trend in a recent liver transplant patient most strongly suggests rejection?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rising AST, ALT, and bilirubin"},{"id":"o1","text":"Decreasing AST and ALT toward normal"},{"id":"o2","text":"Stable, normal liver enzymes"},{"id":"o3","text":"A mild rise in glucose only"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_rejection_g3","conceptId":"transplant_rejection","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever with new jaundice signals possible rejection/infection; prompt notification and workup are the priority. (Acetaminophen is also hepatotoxic and inappropriate here.)</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A liver transplant patient develops fever and new-onset jaundice. What is the nurse's priority action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Notify the provider promptly and prepare for possible rejection workup"},{"id":"o1","text":"Document and reassess at the next shift"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage fluids and recheck in the morning"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer acetaminophen and take no other action"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"transplant_rejection_g4","conceptId":"transplant_rejection","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Because immunosuppression masks typical signs, even a low-grade fever can indicate significant rejection or infection and must be evaluated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is even a low-grade fever significant in a patient one week post-liver transplant?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Immunosuppression blunts immune response, so fever may signal serious rejection or infection"},{"id":"o1","text":"Fever after transplant is always benign"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fever indicates the graft is functioning normally"},{"id":"o3","text":"Low-grade fever rules out rejection"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"acetaminophen_liver_g0","conceptId":"acetaminophen_liver","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acetaminophen is hepatotoxic and hidden in many OTC combination products; it should be limited/avoided with careful product reconciliation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which teaching point about acetaminophen is correct for a patient with chronic liver disease?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Limit or avoid it, and check combination products that hide acetaminophen"},{"id":"o1","text":"It is safe at any dose for liver patients"},{"id":"o2","text":"Replace it with daily NSAIDs"},{"id":"o3","text":"There is no maximum daily limit"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"acetaminophen_liver_g1","conceptId":"acetaminophen_liver","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acetaminophen requires a reduced ceiling in liver disease; NSAIDs carry bleeding/renal risks in cirrhosis. Hidden sources must be avoided.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis asks about safe pain relief. Which response reflects correct teaching?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Acetaminophen should be limited; we will set a low daily ceiling and avoid hidden sources.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Take as much acetaminophen as you want.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Use ibuprofen every day instead.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"All pain relievers are equally safe for you.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"acetaminophen_liver_g2","conceptId":"acetaminophen_liver","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Combination products frequently contain acetaminophen; unrecognized sources can push patients over a safe cumulative dose.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why must patients with liver disease scrutinize OTC combination cold and pain products?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Many contain acetaminophen, risking cumulative hepatotoxic doses"},{"id":"o1","text":"They all contain NSAIDs that are safe"},{"id":"o2","text":"They contain lactulose"},{"id":"o3","text":"They raise serum albumin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"acetaminophen_liver_g3","conceptId":"acetaminophen_liver","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Stacking products can exceed safe acetaminophen limits; reconciliation to total the daily acetaminophen is the priority in liver disease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient reports taking a nighttime cold medicine plus acetaminophen tablets daily. What is the nurse's priority teaching?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Reconcile all products for total acetaminophen content to avoid exceeding a safe limit"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage adding ibuprofen for better relief"},{"id":"o2","text":"Reassure that combining products is fine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Recommend doubling the dose for adequate effect"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"acetaminophen_liver_g4","conceptId":"acetaminophen_liver","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs risk variceal/GI bleeding and renal injury in cirrhosis; carefully dose-limited acetaminophen is generally preferred for analgesia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which analgesic consideration is correct for a patient with advanced cirrhosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Acetaminophen at a reduced daily limit is generally preferred over NSAIDs"},{"id":"o1","text":"NSAIDs are the safest option in cirrhosis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Aspirin should be taken daily for pain"},{"id":"o3","text":"No analgesic is ever safe"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"coag_bleeding_g0","conceptId":"coag_bleeding","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Coagulopathy from impaired synthetic function plus thrombocytopenia greatly increases bleeding risk; bleeding precautions are the priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient has an INR of 2.6 and platelets of 55,000/mm3. Which intervention is the priority?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Institute bleeding precautions (soft toothbrush, no rectal temps, minimal needlesticks)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage vigorous flossing"},{"id":"o2","text":"Give IM injections for comfort"},{"id":"o3","text":"Apply only brief pressure after venipuncture"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"coag_bleeding_g1","conceptId":"coag_bleeding","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Prolonged pressure and avoiding IM injections reduce bleeding risk; firm brushing, aspirin, and contact sports increase it.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which nursing action is appropriate for a patient with cirrhosis-related coagulopathy?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hold prolonged pressure after any venipuncture and avoid IM injections"},{"id":"o1","text":"Use a firm-bristle toothbrush"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer aspirin for comfort"},{"id":"o3","text":"Encourage contact sports"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"coag_bleeding_g2","conceptId":"coag_bleeding","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Melena and mucosal bleeding indicate active hemorrhage in a coagulopathic patient and require immediate reporting.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis is at high bleeding risk. Which assessment finding should the nurse report immediately?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Melena and bleeding gums"},{"id":"o1","text":"One soft-formed stool"},{"id":"o2","text":"Clear urine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Stable hemoglobin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"coag_bleeding_g3","conceptId":"coag_bleeding","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Reduced synthesis of clotting factors plus splenic sequestration of platelets (from portal hypertension) produce a bleeding tendency.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why does the failing liver in cirrhosis increase bleeding risk?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It cannot synthesize adequate clotting factors, and portal hypertension lowers platelets"},{"id":"o1","text":"It produces too many clotting factors"},{"id":"o2","text":"It increases vitamin K absorption"},{"id":"o3","text":"It raises the platelet count"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"coag_bleeding_g4","conceptId":"coag_bleeding","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> IM injections risk hematoma and bleeding in a coagulopathic, thrombocytopenic patient and should be questioned.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which order should the nurse question for a cirrhotic patient with INR 2.8 and platelets 48,000/mm3?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"An intramuscular injection of a PRN medication"},{"id":"o1","text":"A soft mechanical diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"An oral stool softener"},{"id":"o3","text":"A subcutaneous low-dose order the provider has reviewed"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"sbp_g0","conceptId":"sbp","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> SBP is diagnosed by diagnostic paracentesis (ascitic neutrophil count/culture) and treated promptly with empiric IV antibiotics.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis and ascites develops fever and diffuse abdominal pain. The nurse suspects spontaneous bacterial peritonitis. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Diagnostic paracentesis and IV antibiotics such as ceftriaxone"},{"id":"o1","text":"Discharge home with antacids"},{"id":"o2","text":"Withholding antibiotics until cultures result in 72 hours"},{"id":"o3","text":"A laxative only"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"sbp_g1","conceptId":"sbp","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> SBP often presents with fever, abdominal pain/tenderness, and may worsen encephalopathy; it requires prompt diagnosis and treatment.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment findings in a patient with ascites should prompt the nurse to suspect spontaneous bacterial peritonitis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fever, abdominal pain or tenderness, and worsening encephalopathy"},{"id":"o1","text":"Weight loss and increased appetite"},{"id":"o2","text":"Clear lungs and normal temperature"},{"id":"o3","text":"Bradycardia and hypertension"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"sbp_g2","conceptId":"sbp","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Suspected SBP requires prompt provider notification, diagnostic paracentesis, and empiric antibiotics; delay increases mortality.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient with ascites has a temperature of 101.5 F and abdominal tenderness. What is the priority nursing action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Notify the provider and prepare for diagnostic paracentesis and antibiotics"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer an enema"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage a high-sodium meal"},{"id":"o3","text":"Reassess temperature in 8 hours"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"sbp_g3","conceptId":"sbp","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Empiric IV antibiotics begin promptly after the diagnostic paracentesis because delays raise mortality; therapy is later tailored to cultures.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why should empiric antibiotics not be delayed for culture results in suspected SBP?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"SBP carries high mortality, so prompt empiric treatment is started after the diagnostic tap"},{"id":"o1","text":"Antibiotics are only given after positive cultures"},{"id":"o2","text":"SBP resolves without treatment"},{"id":"o3","text":"Cultures are unnecessary"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"sbp_g4","conceptId":"sbp","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> An elevated ascitic PMN count (>=250 cells/mm3) confirms SBP and warrants antibiotic therapy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A diagnostic paracentesis in a febrile cirrhotic patient shows an elevated ascitic neutrophil (PMN) count. Which condition does this confirm?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"o2","text":"Variceal bleeding"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hepatorenal syndrome"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"ascites_path_g0","conceptId":"ascites_path","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Ascites/edema arise from portal hypertension plus low oncotic pressure (low albumin), driving fluid out of the vasculature.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with end-stage liver disease asks why their abdomen is swollen and legs are edematous. Which explanation is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Portal hypertension and low albumin shift fluid into the abdomen and tissues"},{"id":"o1","text":"The liver makes too much albumin"},{"id":"o2","text":"The kidneys excrete excessive sodium"},{"id":"o3","text":"High blood glucose pulls fluid into the abdomen"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ascites_path_g1","conceptId":"ascites_path","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Increased portal venous pressure and decreased plasma oncotic pressure (low albumin) are the central drivers of ascites.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which two factors primarily cause ascites in cirrhosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Portal hypertension and hypoalbuminemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hyperalbuminemia and low portal pressure"},{"id":"o2","text":"High oncotic pressure and dehydration"},{"id":"o3","text":"Polycythemia and hypertension"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ascites_path_g2","conceptId":"ascites_path","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Reduced hepatic albumin synthesis lowers plasma oncotic pressure, allowing fluid to leak into tissues and the peritoneum.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse explains the role of albumin in a cirrhotic patient's edema. Which statement is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Your liver makes less albumin, so fluid leaks out of the blood vessels.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Too much albumin is pulling fluid into your legs.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Albumin has no role in swelling.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Albumin raises your blood sugar.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ascites_path_g3","conceptId":"ascites_path","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Splanchnic vasodilation reduces effective circulating volume, activating RAAS and ADH, which retain sodium and water and worsen ascites.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which mechanism explains the sodium and water retention contributing to ascites in cirrhosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Reduced effective circulating volume activates RAAS, causing sodium and water retention"},{"id":"o1","text":"The kidneys actively waste sodium"},{"id":"o2","text":"Aldosterone levels fall in cirrhosis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Antidiuretic hormone is suppressed"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ascites_path_g4","conceptId":"ascites_path","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Because RAAS-driven sodium retention drives ascites, sodium restriction is a cornerstone of management.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A cirrhotic patient with new ascites should receive which dietary teaching aligned with its pathophysiology?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Restrict dietary sodium to reduce fluid retention"},{"id":"o1","text":"Increase sodium to replace losses"},{"id":"o2","text":"Restrict all protein permanently"},{"id":"o3","text":"Eliminate all fluids"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"liver_failure_labs_g0","conceptId":"liver_failure_labs","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> End-stage liver disease produces asterixis, thrombocytopenia, renal impairment (hepatorenal), prolonged PT, and worsening encephalopathy. A high hemoglobin is not expected (anemia is typical).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with end-stage cirrhosis has hepatic encephalopathy and ascites. Which findings are expected? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Asterixis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Platelet count of 50,000/mm3"},{"id":"o2","text":"Serum creatinine of 2.5 mg/dL"},{"id":"o3","text":"Prothrombin time of 25 seconds"},{"id":"o4","text":"Worsening confusion"},{"id":"o5","text":"Hemoglobin of 17 g/dL"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3","o4"]},{"id":"liver_failure_labs_g1","conceptId":"liver_failure_labs","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Decompensated cirrhosis shows elevated ammonia and bilirubin, prolonged INR, low albumin, and low platelets. The last option is a distractor that misframes renal risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which laboratory and assessment findings are consistent with decompensated cirrhosis? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Elevated ammonia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Prolonged INR"},{"id":"o2","text":"Low albumin"},{"id":"o3","text":"Elevated bilirubin"},{"id":"o4","text":"Thrombocytopenia"},{"id":"o5","text":"Low BUN with normal kidneys ruling out hepatorenal risk"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3","o4"]},{"id":"liver_failure_labs_g2","conceptId":"liver_failure_labs","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Synthetic failure prolongs PT/INR and lowers albumin and fibrinogen. Elevated H/H is not a feature; anemia is more typical.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse reviews labs for a patient in liver failure. Which results support impaired hepatic synthetic function? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Prolonged prothrombin time"},{"id":"o1","text":"Low serum albumin"},{"id":"o2","text":"Elevated INR"},{"id":"o3","text":"Low fibrinogen"},{"id":"o4","text":"Elevated hemoglobin and hematocrit"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"liver_failure_labs_g3","conceptId":"liver_failure_labs","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Worsening encephalopathy presents with asterixis, lethargy, confusion, disorientation, and elevated ammonia. Improved coordination is not expected.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which clinical findings would the nurse expect in a patient with worsening hepatic encephalopathy? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Asterixis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Increasing lethargy and confusion"},{"id":"o2","text":"Elevated serum ammonia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Disorientation to time and place"},{"id":"o4","text":"Sharp improvement in fine motor coordination"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"liver_failure_labs_g4","conceptId":"liver_failure_labs","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hepatorenal syndrome features rising creatinine, oliguria, azotemia, and low effective circulating volume. Brisk dilute diuresis is the opposite.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with cirrhosis is at risk for hepatorenal syndrome. Which findings support this complication? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rising serum creatinine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Decreasing urine output"},{"id":"o2","text":"Azotemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hypotension/low effective circulating volume"},{"id":"o4","text":"Brisk diuresis with dilute urine"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"liver_functions_g0","conceptId":"liver_functions","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Jaundice/pale stools = impaired bile excretion; high ammonia = impaired detoxification; prolonged INR = impaired synthesis of clotting factors; varices/ascites = portal hypertension.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each cue in liver failure with the failed liver function it represents.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Jaundice and clay-colored stools"},{"id":"l1","text":"Rising ammonia with confusion"},{"id":"l2","text":"Prolonged INR and easy bruising"},{"id":"l3","text":"Esophageal varices and ascites"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Failure of the excretory (bile-flow) function"},{"id":"r1","text":"Failure of the detoxification function"},{"id":"r2","text":"Failure of the synthetic (clotting-factor) function"},{"id":"r3","text":"Portal hypertension"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"liver_functions_g1","conceptId":"liver_functions","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Low albumin and clotting factors reflect synthetic failure; elevated bilirubin reflects excretory failure; high ammonia reflects detox failure; splenomegaly/thrombocytopenia reflect portal hypertension.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each laboratory or clinical finding to the liver function it reflects.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Low serum albumin"},{"id":"l1","text":"Elevated serum bilirubin"},{"id":"l2","text":"Elevated blood ammonia"},{"id":"l3","text":"Splenomegaly with low platelets"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Failure of synthetic function"},{"id":"r1","text":"Failure of excretory function"},{"id":"r2","text":"Failure of detoxification function"},{"id":"r3","text":"Portal hypertension"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"liver_functions_g2","conceptId":"liver_functions","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PT prolongation = synthetic failure; encephalopathy = detox failure; dark urine/pruritus = excretory (bilirubin) failure; caput medusae = portal hypertension collaterals.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each manifestation of cirrhosis to the underlying failed hepatic role.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Bleeding gums and prolonged PT"},{"id":"l1","text":"Hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"l2","text":"Dark urine and pruritus"},{"id":"l3","text":"Caput medusae"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Synthetic (clotting factors)"},{"id":"r1","text":"Detoxification (ammonia clearance)"},{"id":"r2","text":"Excretory (bilirubin/bile)"},{"id":"r3","text":"Portal hypertension"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"liver_functions_g3","conceptId":"liver_functions","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Low albumin (synthetic) causes edema; ammonia accumulation (detox) causes asterixis; bilirubin retention (excretory) causes scleral icterus; collateral varices reflect portal hypertension.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse teaches about liver functions lost in cirrhosis. Match the patient finding to the lost function.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Edema from low oncotic pressure"},{"id":"l1","text":"Asterixis and lethargy"},{"id":"l2","text":"Yellow sclera"},{"id":"l3","text":"Hemorrhoids and esophageal varices"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Synthetic function (albumin)"},{"id":"r1","text":"Detoxification function"},{"id":"r2","text":"Excretory function"},{"id":"r3","text":"Portal hypertension"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"liver_functions_g4","conceptId":"liver_functions","domain":"Liver","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Elevated INR/bleeding = synthetic failure; ammonia-related confusion responsive to lactulose = detox failure; clay stool = impaired bile excretion; ascites = portal hypertension plus hypoalbuminemia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each cue to the hepatic function whose failure best explains it.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"INR 2.5 with mucosal bleeding"},{"id":"l1","text":"Confusion improving with lactulose"},{"id":"l2","text":"Clay-colored stool"},{"id":"l3","text":"Massive ascites"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Synthetic function"},{"id":"r1","text":"Detoxification function"},{"id":"r2","text":"Excretory function"},{"id":"r3","text":"Portal hypertension and low albumin"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"cirrhosis_bowtie_g0","conceptId":"cirrhosis_bowtie","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Tarry stools + hypotension + cirrhosis = variceal/GI hemorrhage; confusion + asterixis = encephalopathy. Priority is airway/oxygen and volume access. Monitor perfusion (MAP/HR) and neuro status (LOC).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>BOW-TIE. Robert, 58, with alcoholic cirrhosis arrives confused with a distended abdomen and black, tarry stools. HR 110, BP 88/54, RR 24, SpO2 92%, asterixis and jaundice. The nurse identifies the condition as [b0], takes priority action [b1], and monitors [b2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"variceal hemorrhage with hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"o1","text":"acute appendicitis"},{"id":"o2","text":"diabetic ketoacidosis"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"apply oxygen and establish two large-bore IVs"},{"id":"o1","text":"give a high-protein meal"},{"id":"o2","text":"place flat and withhold fluids"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"mean arterial pressure, heart rate, and level of consciousness"},{"id":"o1","text":"pupil size only"},{"id":"o2","text":"deep tendon reflexes only"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"cirrhosis_bowtie_g1","conceptId":"cirrhosis_bowtie","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hematemesis with hypotension in cirrhosis indicates variceal bleeding. Octreotide lowers portal pressure acutely; urgent EGD with banding is definitive. Propranolol is for prophylaxis, not active bleeding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>BOW-TIE. A cirrhotic patient has hematemesis and BP 86/50. The nurse anticipates the condition [b0], prepares the medication [b1], and arranges the definitive procedure [b2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"bleeding esophageal varices"},{"id":"o1","text":"spontaneous bacterial peritonitis"},{"id":"o2","text":"hepatorenal syndrome"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"octreotide infusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"oral propranolol now"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV potassium"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"urgent endoscopy (EGD) with banding"},{"id":"o1","text":"outpatient colonoscopy next week"},{"id":"o2","text":"abdominal ultrasound only"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"cirrhosis_bowtie_g2","conceptId":"cirrhosis_bowtie","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever and abdominal pain with ascites suggests SBP. Diagnostic paracentesis confirms it (PMN count/culture); prompt empiric IV antibiotics are the treatment.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>BOW-TIE. A cirrhotic patient with ascites has fever 101.4 F and diffuse abdominal pain. The nurse suspects [b0], anticipates the diagnostic test [b1], and expects treatment with [b2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"spontaneous bacterial peritonitis"},{"id":"o1","text":"variceal bleeding"},{"id":"o2","text":"hepatic encephalopathy"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"diagnostic paracentesis"},{"id":"o1","text":"upper endoscopy"},{"id":"o2","text":"lumbar puncture"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV antibiotics such as ceftriaxone"},{"id":"o1","text":"lactulose alone"},{"id":"o2","text":"an oral laxative only"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"cirrhosis_bowtie_g3","conceptId":"cirrhosis_bowtie","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Elevated ammonia + confusion (precipitated by GI bleeding) = hepatic encephalopathy. Lactulose traps and excretes ammonia; effectiveness is shown by improving mentation with several soft stools daily.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>BOW-TIE. A confused cirrhotic patient has an ammonia of 110 mcg/dL and recent GI bleeding. The nurse identifies the complication [b0], anticipates the medication [b1], and evaluates effectiveness by [b2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"o1","text":"spontaneous bacterial peritonitis"},{"id":"o2","text":"hepatorenal syndrome"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"lactulose"},{"id":"o1","text":"propranolol"},{"id":"o2","text":"albumin only"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"improved level of consciousness with soft stools"},{"id":"o1","text":"decreased stool frequency"},{"id":"o2","text":"a fall in serum albumin"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"cirrhosis_bowtie_g4","conceptId":"cirrhosis_bowtie","domain":"Liver","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Large-volume paracentesis can cause circulatory dysfunction and AKI; IV albumin supports intravascular volume. Monitor BP and renal parameters (urine output/creatinine).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>BOW-TIE. A cirrhotic patient post large-volume paracentesis becomes hypotensive with rising creatinine. The nurse identifies the risk [b0], anticipates the intervention [b1], and monitors [b2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"paracentesis-induced circulatory dysfunction/AKI"},{"id":"o1","text":"hepatic encephalopathy"},{"id":"o2","text":"variceal bleeding"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV albumin"},{"id":"o1","text":"oral lactulose"},{"id":"o2","text":"a beta-blocker"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"blood pressure and urine output/creatinine"},{"id":"o1","text":"ammonia level only"},{"id":"o2","text":"INR only"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"tx_vfib_g0","conceptId":"tx_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Pulseless VF is a shockable arrest rhythm; immediate CPR with early defibrillation is the only intervention that restores perfusion. Drugs (including amiodarone) are secondary to shock and compressions.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient on telemetry suddenly becomes unresponsive; the monitor shows ventricular fibrillation and there is no pulse. What is the nurse's priority action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin high-quality CPR and prepare for immediate defibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer IV amiodarone"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Give IV atropine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_vfib_g1","conceptId":"tx_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> VF has no R wave to synchronize to, so the shock must be unsynchronized (defibrillation). CPR resumes immediately after the shock without a prolonged pulse check.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>During a code, a patient is in VF. The defibrillator is charged. Which action is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Deliver an unsynchronized shock, then immediately resume CPR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Deliver a synchronized shock on the R wave"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hold the shock until amiodarone is given"},{"id":"o3","text":"Check a 12-lead ECG before shocking"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_vfib_g2","conceptId":"tx_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> VF management is CPR, defibrillation, and epinephrine with minimal compression interruptions. Synchronized cardioversion is impossible and inappropriate in VF because there is no organized QRS.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is in pulseless ventricular fibrillation. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Start high-quality chest compressions"},{"id":"o1","text":"Defibrillate as soon as the device is ready"},{"id":"o2","text":"Give epinephrine per ACLS"},{"id":"o3","text":"Minimize interruptions in compressions"},{"id":"o4","text":"Attempt synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_vfib_g3","conceptId":"tx_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Synchronization requires an R wave to time the shock; VF has none, so the defibrillator delivers an unsynchronized shock to depolarize the myocardium and allow an organized rhythm to resume.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement explains why defibrillation rather than synchronized cardioversion is used for ventricular fibrillation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"VF has no organized QRS to synchronize to, so an unsynchronized shock is required"},{"id":"o1","text":"Cardioversion uses too much energy for VF"},{"id":"o2","text":"VF responds only to medication"},{"id":"o3","text":"Synchronized shocks cannot treat ventricular rhythms"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_vfib_g4","conceptId":"tx_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Refractory VF is managed with continued CPR, repeated defibrillation, epinephrine, and consideration of an antiarrhythmic such as amiodarone. Adenosine has no role in VF.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in VF has received one shock and CPR is ongoing. The rhythm remains VF at the next check. Which is the appropriate next step?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Resume CPR, deliver another shock at the next analysis, and give epinephrine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Stop the code"},{"id":"o2","text":"Switch to synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer IV adenosine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_stable_vt_g0","conceptId":"tx_stable_vt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Stable VT with a pulse is treated with an IV antiarrhythmic (amiodarone or procainamide) first; electrical therapy is reserved for instability or drug failure. CPR/defibrillation are for pulseless VT.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in monomorphic ventricular tachycardia is awake and alert with a BP of 122/74 mm Hg and no chest pain. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV antiarrhythmic such as amiodarone"},{"id":"o1","text":"Immediate unsynchronized defibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Begin chest compressions"},{"id":"o3","text":"IV atropine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_stable_vt_g1","conceptId":"tx_stable_vt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> For stable VT, drugs are tried first; synchronized cardioversion is escalated to when antiarrhythmics fail or the patient deteriorates.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A hemodynamically stable patient with a regular, monomorphic wide-complex tachycardia is being managed. The provider may choose synchronized cardioversion if:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Antiarrhythmic therapy fails or the patient becomes unstable"},{"id":"o1","text":"The patient is comfortable and stable"},{"id":"o2","text":"The QRS narrows"},{"id":"o3","text":"The heart rate falls below 100/min"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_stable_vt_g2","conceptId":"tx_stable_vt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Stable VT warrants IV access, ECG, antiarrhythmic therapy, reversible-cause correction, and standby defibrillation. Compressions are only for a pulseless patient.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with stable monomorphic VT (pulse present, BP 118/70) is being treated. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Obtain IV access and a 12-lead ECG"},{"id":"o1","text":"Prepare an antiarrhythmic infusion (amiodarone)"},{"id":"o2","text":"Identify and correct reversible causes"},{"id":"o3","text":"Have the defibrillator available in case of deterioration"},{"id":"o4","text":"Begin chest compressions now"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_stable_vt_g3","conceptId":"tx_stable_vt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Because the stable patient is still perfusing, there is time to attempt pharmacologic conversion, avoiding procedural sedation and an electrical shock. Cardioversion remains the backup if the patient destabilizes.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is an antiarrhythmic, rather than immediate cardioversion, generally preferred for a stable patient with monomorphic VT?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The patient is perfusing, so a pharmacologic attempt avoids the need for sedation and a shock"},{"id":"o1","text":"Cardioversion is contraindicated in all VT"},{"id":"o2","text":"Antiarrhythmics work faster than electricity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Cardioversion converts VT to VF"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_stable_vt_g4","conceptId":"tx_stable_vt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Once the patient becomes pulseless, VT is treated as a shockable arrest rhythm: CPR and defibrillation, not synchronized cardioversion or continued drug-only therapy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with stable VT suddenly loses consciousness and has no pulse. The nurse should now:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin CPR and prepare for immediate defibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Continue the amiodarone infusion only"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer atropine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_asystole_g0","conceptId":"tx_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asystole is non-shockable; treatment is high-quality CPR and epinephrine while searching for reversible causes. Defibrillation is useless when there is no electrical activity.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is unresponsive, apneic, and pulseless with asystole confirmed in two leads. Which action should the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin high-quality CPR and administer epinephrine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Defibrillate at 200 J"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer adenosine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_asystole_g1","conceptId":"tx_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Defibrillation works by depolarizing myocardium so a normal pacemaker can resume; in asystole there is no electrical activity to reorganize, so a shock provides no benefit.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is defibrillation not used for asystole?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"There is no electrical activity for a shock to reorganize"},{"id":"o1","text":"The energy required is too high"},{"id":"o2","text":"Asystole always converts on its own"},{"id":"o3","text":"A shock would cause VF"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_asystole_g2","conceptId":"tx_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asystole care is CPR, epinephrine, reversible-cause correction, and rhythm confirmation. It is never defibrillated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which interventions are appropriate for a patient in asystole? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"High-quality CPR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Epinephrine per ACLS"},{"id":"o2","text":"Identify and treat reversible causes (H's and T's)"},{"id":"o3","text":"Confirm asystole in a second lead"},{"id":"o4","text":"Immediate defibrillation"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_asystole_g3","conceptId":"tx_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The H's and T's (e.g., hypoxia, hypovolemia, hyperkalemia, hypothermia, toxins, tamponade, tension pneumothorax, thrombosis) are reversible causes that must be sought and treated in asystole and PEA.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>During an asystole code, identifying reversible causes is emphasized. Which is an example of a reversible cause the team should rule out?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypoxia"},{"id":"o1","text":"A prolonged PR interval"},{"id":"o2","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus arrhythmia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_asystole_g4","conceptId":"tx_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Persistent asystole is managed with continued CPR, repeat epinephrine every 3-5 minutes, and aggressive treatment of reversible causes. Shocking asystole is not indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in asystole has received CPR and one dose of epinephrine. The rhythm remains asystole. The nurse should:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Continue CPR, repeat epinephrine per protocol, and keep searching for reversible causes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Defibrillate immediately"},{"id":"o2","text":"Switch to synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer amiodarone as the priority"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_pea_g0","conceptId":"tx_pea","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PEA is a non-shockable arrest: an organized rhythm without a pulse. Treatment is CPR plus epinephrine while identifying and correcting the underlying reversible cause.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A pulseless patient has an organized rhythm at 64/min on the monitor. Which action best reflects management of pulseless electrical activity (PEA)?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin CPR and search for reversible causes (the H's and T's)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Defibrillate because a rhythm is present"},{"id":"o2","text":"Withhold CPR because the rhythm is organized"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer atropine to raise the rate"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_pea_g1","conceptId":"tx_pea","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In PEA the electrical rhythm is organized but the heart is not generating perfusion; shocking an organized rhythm is inappropriate. CPR and reversible-cause correction are key.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is PEA never treated with defibrillation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"PEA is non-shockable; the problem is mechanical/perfusion failure, not a disorganized electrical rhythm"},{"id":"o1","text":"The rhythm is too fast to shock"},{"id":"o2","text":"Defibrillation would slow the rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"PEA always resolves spontaneously"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_pea_g2","conceptId":"tx_pea","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PEA care is CPR, epinephrine, and reversible-cause correction. It is non-shockable, so defibrillation is not indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is in PEA. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Start high-quality CPR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give epinephrine"},{"id":"o2","text":"Aggressively look for and treat reversible causes"},{"id":"o3","text":"Assess for hypovolemia and hypoxia"},{"id":"o4","text":"Deliver an unsynchronized shock"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_pea_g3","conceptId":"tx_pea","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Given massive hemorrhage, hypovolemia is the most likely reversible cause and should be addressed with volume/blood resuscitation alongside CPR and epinephrine.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in PEA was found after massive GI bleeding. Which reversible cause should the team prioritize correcting?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypovolemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypothermia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hyperkalemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Tension pneumothorax"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_pea_g4","conceptId":"tx_pea","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Both are non-shockable arrest rhythms, but PEA displays organized electrical activity without a pulse, whereas asystole is the absence of electrical activity altogether.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement distinguishes PEA from asystole?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"PEA shows an organized rhythm without a pulse; asystole shows no electrical activity"},{"id":"o1","text":"PEA is shockable; asystole is not"},{"id":"o2","text":"PEA always has a pulse"},{"id":"o3","text":"Asystole shows an organized rhythm"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_st_arrest_g0","conceptId":"tx_st_arrest","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A monitored rhythm means nothing without a pulse. A pulseless patient with any organized rhythm (here sinus tach) is in PEA — start CPR; do not treat the rate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is apneic and pulseless. The monitor shows sinus tachycardia at 128/min. Which action should the nurse take next?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Start cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give a beta-blocker to slow the rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Apply oxygen via non-rebreather and reassess"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_st_arrest_g1","conceptId":"tx_st_arrest","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Electrical activity on the monitor does not guarantee perfusion. Pulselessness with an organized rhythm defines PEA, and CPR is the priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why would the nurse begin CPR on a pulseless patient whose monitor shows sinus tachycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"An organized rhythm without a pulse is PEA, a cardiac arrest requiring CPR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sinus tachycardia is always lethal"},{"id":"o2","text":"The monitor is malfunctioning"},{"id":"o3","text":"The rate must be slowed first"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_st_arrest_g2","conceptId":"tx_st_arrest","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> This is PEA: CPR, epinephrine, reversible-cause correction, and pulse confirmation. Rate-controlling drugs are inappropriate in arrest.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A pulseless patient shows sinus tachycardia on the monitor. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin CPR immediately"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give epinephrine per ACLS"},{"id":"o2","text":"Search for reversible causes"},{"id":"o3","text":"Confirm pulselessness"},{"id":"o4","text":"Treat the tachycardia with a beta-blocker"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_st_arrest_g3","conceptId":"tx_st_arrest","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The teaching point is to treat the patient (pulselessness) rather than the number on the screen; PEA requires CPR and ACLS, not rate control.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nursing student asks why the team is not 'fixing the fast rate' in a pulseless patient with sinus tach on the monitor. The best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"In cardiac arrest we treat the patient, not the monitor — the priority is CPR"},{"id":"o1","text":"The rate will correct itself once oxygen is applied"},{"id":"o2","text":"We must cardiovert first"},{"id":"o3","text":"The monitor reading is wrong"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_st_arrest_g4","conceptId":"tx_st_arrest","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tach in PEA often reflects a reversible cause (e.g., hypovolemia, hypoxia, PE) that is preventing the organized rhythm from producing a pulse; finding and treating it is essential.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A pulseless patient in PEA with sinus tachycardia is most likely experiencing which underlying problem?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A reversible cause such as hypovolemia or hypoxia preventing effective perfusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"A primary electrical conduction block"},{"id":"o2","text":"An overdose of a rate-control drug"},{"id":"o3","text":"A normal physiologic response that needs no action"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_svt_stable_g0","conceptId":"tx_svt_stable","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> For stable SVT, vagal maneuvers (Valsalva, bearing down) are attempted first; adenosine follows if they fail. Cardioversion is reserved for instability.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with stable SVT (alert, BP 124/78) does not respond to coaching. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Vagal maneuvers such as bearing down"},{"id":"o1","text":"Immediate synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV amiodarone bolus"},{"id":"o3","text":"Unsynchronized defibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_svt_stable_g1","conceptId":"tx_svt_stable","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> When vagal maneuvers do not terminate stable SVT, adenosine is the first-line drug. Atropine raises rate (used in bradycardia), and epinephrine is not used in stable SVT.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Vagal maneuvers fail to convert a stable patient's SVT. Which medication should the nurse anticipate next?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV adenosine by rapid push"},{"id":"o1","text":"IV atropine"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV epinephrine"},{"id":"o3","text":"IV magnesium"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_svt_stable_g2","conceptId":"tx_svt_stable","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Stable SVT: vagal maneuvers, then adenosine, with cardioversion on standby for instability, plus oxygen and ECG. Atropine is for bradycardia, not SVT.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with stable SVT (HR 190, BP 118/72) is being managed. Which interventions should the nurse anticipate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Attempt vagal maneuvers first"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer IV adenosine if vagal maneuvers fail"},{"id":"o2","text":"Prepare for synchronized cardioversion if the patient becomes unstable"},{"id":"o3","text":"Apply oxygen and obtain a 12-lead ECG"},{"id":"o4","text":"Administer IV atropine"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_svt_stable_g3","conceptId":"tx_svt_stable","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Stable SVT is managed least-to-most invasive: vagal maneuvers, then adenosine, escalating to synchronized cardioversion only if the patient becomes unstable.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which describes the correct escalation order for a STABLE patient with SVT?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Vagal maneuvers → adenosine → synchronized cardioversion if unstable"},{"id":"o1","text":"Adenosine → vagal maneuvers → defibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Synchronized cardioversion first → then vagal maneuvers"},{"id":"o3","text":"Defibrillation → adenosine → atropine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_svt_stable_g4","conceptId":"tx_svt_stable","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Unstable SVT (hypotension, chest pain, altered perfusion) requires synchronized cardioversion rather than continued vagal/pharmacologic attempts.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with SVT becomes hypotensive, diaphoretic, and develops chest pain. The nurse should now anticipate:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o1","text":"Continued vagal maneuvers"},{"id":"o2","text":"Oral beta-blocker"},{"id":"o3","text":"Watchful waiting"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"adenosine_admin_g0","conceptId":"adenosine_admin","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Adenosine has an extremely short half-life, so it must be given as a rapid IV push followed immediately by a fast saline flush, ideally through a proximal port, to reach the AV node before it degrades.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The provider orders IV adenosine for stable SVT. Which administration technique is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rapid IV push over 1-2 seconds followed immediately by a fast saline flush"},{"id":"o1","text":"Slow IV push over 60 seconds"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV infusion over 30 minutes"},{"id":"o3","text":"Subcutaneous injection"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"adenosine_admin_g1","conceptId":"adenosine_admin","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A proximal port speeds delivery before adenosine breaks down. Patients commonly feel transient flushing, chest pressure, and a brief asystolic pause, which the nurse should explain in advance.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which port should be used and what should the nurse tell the patient before adenosine administration?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Use the port closest to the patient and warn about a brief feeling of chest pressure/flushing and a transient pause"},{"id":"o1","text":"Use the most distal port and warn of permanent palpitations"},{"id":"o2","text":"Use a slow drip and tell the patient nothing will be felt"},{"id":"o3","text":"Use an IM site to avoid sensations"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"adenosine_admin_g2","conceptId":"adenosine_admin","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Adenosine is a rapid push + fast flush via a proximal port with continuous monitoring and resuscitation equipment available, because of its short half-life and the transient pause it produces.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which actions reflect correct adenosine administration? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Push rapidly over 1-2 seconds"},{"id":"o1","text":"Follow immediately with a rapid saline flush"},{"id":"o2","text":"Have the patient on a cardiac monitor and a code cart nearby"},{"id":"o3","text":"Use a port close to the heart"},{"id":"o4","text":"Dilute and infuse slowly over 20 minutes"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"adenosine_admin_g3","conceptId":"adenosine_admin","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A brief sinus pause/transient asystole after adenosine is expected as it transiently blocks the AV node; the rhythm typically resumes within seconds. Continuous monitoring is essential.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>After a rapid adenosine push, the monitor briefly shows a few seconds of asystole before sinus rhythm returns. The nurse recognizes this as:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"An expected transient effect of adenosine"},{"id":"o1","text":"A medication error requiring CPR"},{"id":"o2","text":"An allergic reaction"},{"id":"o3","text":"A sign the drug failed"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"adenosine_admin_g4","conceptId":"adenosine_admin","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> If the initial 6 mg dose fails, a 12 mg rapid push (with flush) is the standard next step. Atropine and defibrillation are not part of stable SVT management.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>If the first 6 mg dose of adenosine fails to convert stable SVT, the nurse anticipates:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A 12 mg rapid IV push as the next dose"},{"id":"o1","text":"Repeating the same 6 mg dose three more times"},{"id":"o2","text":"Switching to IV atropine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Immediate defibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cardioversion_svt_g0","conceptId":"cardioversion_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Synchronized cardioversion times the shock to the R wave to avoid the vulnerable T-wave period; sync mode must be ON. A stable, awake patient should receive sedation first, and energy is far lower than 360 J.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Synchronized cardioversion has been ordered for a stable patient with SVT. Which action should the nurse anticipate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administer sedation and ensure the synchronization (sync) mode is ON before the shock"},{"id":"o1","text":"Set the defibrillator to deliver an unsynchronized shock"},{"id":"o2","text":"Deactivate sync mode before shocking"},{"id":"o3","text":"Set the energy to 360 J"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cardioversion_svt_g1","conceptId":"cardioversion_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Delivering energy during the T wave (the vulnerable period) can induce VF. Synchronization ensures the shock lands on the R wave, making cardioversion safer than an unsynchronized shock for an organized rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why must the synchronization mode be activated for cardioversion of SVT?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"To deliver the shock on the R wave and avoid the T wave, preventing induction of VF"},{"id":"o1","text":"To increase the energy delivered"},{"id":"o2","text":"To allow a slower shock"},{"id":"o3","text":"To bypass the need for sedation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cardioversion_svt_g2","conceptId":"cardioversion_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Cardioversion requires sync ON, sedation for the awake patient, lower energy than defibrillation, and a clearly tracked R wave. A 360 J unsynchronized shock describes defibrillation, not cardioversion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which actions are appropriate when preparing a stable, awake patient for synchronized cardioversion of SVT? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Confirm sync mode is ON"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer procedural sedation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Use a lower energy setting than for defibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Ensure the patient is on a monitor with a clear R wave"},{"id":"o4","text":"Set energy to 360 J unsynchronized"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cardioversion_svt_g3","conceptId":"cardioversion_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> If a stable patient does not convert, the team verifies sync is engaged and escalates energy for another synchronized attempt. Compressions are only for pulselessness.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Immediately after a synchronized shock fails to convert SVT and the patient remains stable, the nurse anticipates:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Re-checking sync mode and escalating energy per protocol for a repeat synchronized attempt"},{"id":"o1","text":"Switching to an unsynchronized shock"},{"id":"o2","text":"Starting chest compressions"},{"id":"o3","text":"Giving atropine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cardioversion_svt_g4","conceptId":"cardioversion_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Cardioversion uses lower energy synchronized to the R wave for organized rhythms with a pulse; defibrillation uses higher energy delivered without synchronization for pulseless VF/VT.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A key safety difference between synchronized cardioversion and defibrillation is that cardioversion:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Delivers a lower-energy shock timed to the R wave"},{"id":"o1","text":"Delivers a higher-energy shock at a random point"},{"id":"o2","text":"Is used only for pulseless rhythms"},{"id":"o3","text":"Never requires patient sedation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_sym_brady_g0","conceptId":"tx_sym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Symptomatic bradycardia (hypotension, dizziness, altered mentation) is treated first with atropine. Adenosine and beta-blockers slow the heart further; amiodarone is not indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has sinus bradycardia at 38/min with a BP of 82/48 mm Hg and reports dizziness and confusion. Which medication should the nurse anticipate administering first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV atropine"},{"id":"o1","text":"IV adenosine"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV metoprolol"},{"id":"o3","text":"IV amiodarone"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_sym_brady_g1","conceptId":"tx_sym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> When atropine fails in symptomatic bradycardia, transcutaneous pacing or a chronotropic infusion (dopamine, epinephrine) is the next step. Rate-slowing drugs and cardioversion are inappropriate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A symptomatic bradycardic patient does not respond to atropine. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate next?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Transcutaneous pacing (and/or a dopamine or epinephrine infusion)"},{"id":"o1","text":"A second beta-blocker dose"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV adenosine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_sym_brady_g2","conceptId":"tx_sym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Symptomatic bradycardia is treated with atropine, pacing readiness, oxygen/IV access, and reversible-cause search. A beta-blocker would worsen the bradycardia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with symptomatic bradycardia (HR 40, BP 80/50, lightheaded) is being managed. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administer IV atropine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Apply transcutaneous pacing pads and prepare to pace"},{"id":"o2","text":"Establish IV access and apply oxygen"},{"id":"o3","text":"Identify reversible causes"},{"id":"o4","text":"Administer a beta-blocker to stabilize the rhythm"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"tx_sym_brady_g3","conceptId":"tx_sym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Treatment is driven by symptoms of poor perfusion (hypotension, altered mentation, chest pain). A slow but asymptomatic rate, especially in an athlete or during sleep, does not require atropine.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment finding converts asymptomatic bradycardia into a situation requiring atropine?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypotension with dizziness and confusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"A resting heart rate of 55/min in an athlete"},{"id":"o2","text":"An incidental rate of 58/min while asleep"},{"id":"o3","text":"A normal blood pressure with no symptoms"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_sym_brady_g4","conceptId":"tx_sym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Atropine is an anticholinergic that reduces vagal influence on the SA and AV nodes, raising the heart rate — the desired effect in symptomatic bradycardia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is atropine the first-line drug for symptomatic bradycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It blocks vagal (parasympathetic) tone, increasing the heart rate"},{"id":"o1","text":"It directly paces the ventricle"},{"id":"o2","text":"It vasodilates to lower afterload"},{"id":"o3","text":"It blocks the AV node to slow conduction"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_3avb_g0","conceptId":"tx_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Symptomatic complete heart block requires pacing (transcutaneous as a bridge to transvenous/permanent). Atropine is often ineffective in complete block; cardioversion/defibrillation and adenosine are not indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in third-degree AV block has a ventricular rate of 30/min, BP 78/46, and is confused and diaphoretic. Which intervention should the nurse prepare for?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Transcutaneous pacing"},{"id":"o1","text":"Synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o2","text":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"IV adenosine"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_3avb_g1","conceptId":"tx_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In complete block the escape rhythm often originates below the AV node, where vagolytic atropine has limited effect; pacing is the definitive bridge.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is atropine frequently ineffective in symptomatic third-degree AV block?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The block is below the AV node, where atropine has little effect on the escape pacemaker"},{"id":"o1","text":"Atropine slows the heart"},{"id":"o2","text":"The patient is already tachycardic"},{"id":"o3","text":"Atropine only works in atrial fibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_3avb_g2","conceptId":"tx_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Symptomatic complete block: pacing readiness, oxygen/IV access, anticipation of definitive pacing, and continuous monitoring. A beta-blocker would further suppress the escape rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A symptomatic patient in complete heart block (HR 32, BP 80/48, confused) is being managed. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Prepare for transcutaneous pacing"},{"id":"o1","text":"Apply oxygen and establish IV access"},{"id":"o2","text":"Anticipate possible transvenous or permanent pacing"},{"id":"o3","text":"Continuously monitor the rhythm and perfusion"},{"id":"o4","text":"Administer a beta-blocker"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"tx_3avb_g3","conceptId":"tx_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The ventricular escape pacemaker in complete block is slow and unreliable, so standby pacing is kept ready in case the rate or perfusion drops abruptly.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with new complete heart block is stable now but the nurse keeps pacing pads attached. The rationale is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The escape rhythm is unreliable and the patient can deteriorate suddenly"},{"id":"o1","text":"Pacing pads treat the underlying ischemia"},{"id":"o2","text":"The pads will convert the block to sinus rhythm on their own"},{"id":"o3","text":"Pads prevent the need for a permanent pacemaker"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_3avb_g4","conceptId":"tx_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A permanent pacemaker is the definitive treatment for persistent symptomatic complete heart block; transcutaneous/transvenous pacing serves as a temporary bridge.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which is the definitive long-term treatment for persistent symptomatic third-degree AV block?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Permanent pacemaker implantation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Lifelong atropine"},{"id":"o2","text":"Daily adenosine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Beta-blocker therapy"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_1avb_g0","conceptId":"tx_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asymptomatic first-degree AV block (fixed prolonged PR, 1:1 conduction) is benign and requires only documentation and monitoring. No medication or pacing is indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has sinus rhythm at 70/min with a fixed PR interval of 0.26 seconds and is asymptomatic. Which action would the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Document the finding and continue to monitor"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer atropine"},{"id":"o2","text":"Prepare for a temporary pacemaker"},{"id":"o3","text":"Notify the provider for emergency intervention"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_1avb_g1","conceptId":"tx_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In first-degree block conduction is merely delayed, not interrupted; every P wave still produces a QRS, so perfusion is maintained and no acute treatment is needed in an asymptomatic patient.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why does asymptomatic first-degree AV block generally not require treatment?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Every impulse still conducts to the ventricles, so cardiac output is preserved"},{"id":"o1","text":"It always resolves within hours"},{"id":"o2","text":"It cannot progress to other blocks"},{"id":"o3","text":"Atropine is contraindicated"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_1avb_g2","conceptId":"tx_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asymptomatic first-degree block calls for documentation, monitoring, medication review (e.g., AV-nodal agents), and reassessment if symptoms appear. Immediate pacing is unnecessary.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has an incidental fixed PR of 0.24 s with 1:1 conduction and no symptoms. Which nursing actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Document the rhythm"},{"id":"o1","text":"Continue routine monitoring"},{"id":"o2","text":"Review medications that prolong AV conduction"},{"id":"o3","text":"Reassess if symptoms develop"},{"id":"o4","text":"Prepare for immediate pacing"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"tx_1avb_g3","conceptId":"tx_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Progression to dropped beats (higher-degree block) or symptoms of decreased perfusion is significant and warrants provider notification; a stable prolonged PR alone does not.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which new finding in a patient with known first-degree AV block would prompt the nurse to notify the provider?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Development of dropped QRS complexes or symptoms of poor perfusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"An unchanged prolonged PR interval"},{"id":"o2","text":"A heart rate of 72/min"},{"id":"o3","text":"A normal blood pressure"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_1avb_g4","conceptId":"tx_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Patient teaching should reflect that first-degree block is a benign conduction delay with preserved 1:1 conduction, requiring observation rather than intervention when asymptomatic.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient asks why no medication is being given for their 'heart block.' The nurse's best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'Your type of block only delays the signal slightly; every beat still gets through, so we just watch it.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'You will need a pacemaker today.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'We will start atropine to fix it.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'It is an emergency and the provider is on the way.'"},{"id":"o4","text":"'It means your heart has stopped conducting.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_torsades_g0","conceptId":"tx_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> IV magnesium sulfate is the first-line treatment for torsades de pointes. Adenosine, atropine, and calcium channel blockers are not used; if the patient becomes pulseless, defibrillation is required.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a prolonged QT develops torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT) but still has a pulse. Which medication should the nurse anticipate administering?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV magnesium sulfate"},{"id":"o1","text":"IV adenosine"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV atropine"},{"id":"o3","text":"IV diltiazem"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_torsades_g1","conceptId":"tx_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Beyond magnesium, repleting potassium and discontinuing QT-prolonging medications address the underlying cause and reduce recurrence of torsades.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>In addition to magnesium, which intervention helps prevent recurrence of torsades de pointes?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Correcting hypokalemia and stopping QT-prolonging drugs"},{"id":"o1","text":"Starting a QT-prolonging antiarrhythmic"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administering atropine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Restricting all IV fluids"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_torsades_g2","conceptId":"tx_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Torsades management is magnesium, electrolyte correction, removal of QT-prolonging drugs, and defibrillation readiness for pulseless deterioration. Rate-control CCBs are not used.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with torsades de pointes and a pulse is being treated. Which interventions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administer IV magnesium sulfate"},{"id":"o1","text":"Correct hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Review and stop QT-prolonging medications"},{"id":"o3","text":"Be prepared to defibrillate if the patient loses a pulse"},{"id":"o4","text":"Administer IV diltiazem to control the rate"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_torsades_g3","conceptId":"tx_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Pulseless torsades/polymorphic VT is treated as a shockable arrest: CPR and defibrillation. Synchronization is often not feasible with the constantly changing QRS of polymorphic VT.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in torsades de pointes becomes pulseless. The nurse should now:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin CPR and defibrillate (treat as a shockable arrest)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give a second dose of diltiazem"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion only"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer adenosine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_torsades_g4","conceptId":"tx_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Magnesium stabilizes the myocardial membrane and suppresses the triggered activity (early afterdepolarizations) responsible for torsades, even when serum magnesium is normal.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is magnesium effective in torsades de pointes?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It stabilizes the cardiac membrane and suppresses the early afterdepolarizations that trigger the rhythm"},{"id":"o1","text":"It speeds AV conduction"},{"id":"o2","text":"It increases the QT interval"},{"id":"o3","text":"It directly paces the heart"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"tx_stach_cause_g0","conceptId":"tx_stach_cause","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tachycardia is a compensatory response, not a primary dysrhythmia. Managing the underlying causes (here, treating pain and fever) addresses the rate. Adenosine/cardioversion target reentrant rhythms, not sinus tach.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A postoperative patient who is febrile and reports pain has sinus tachycardia at 130/min. Which action by the nurse is most appropriate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Treat the underlying causes — pain and fever"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer adenosine"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perform synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Prepare for defibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_stach_cause_g1","conceptId":"tx_stach_cause","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In sinus tachycardia the priority is correcting the driving cause (ischemic pain, anxiety). Adenosine and cardioversion are not used for sinus tachycardia, and atropine would raise the rate further.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a myocardial infarction develops chest pain and sinus tachycardia at 132/min. Which intervention is most appropriate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Treat the ischemia/pain and reassess the rate"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give IV adenosine"},{"id":"o2","text":"Cardiovert the patient"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer atropine"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_stach_cause_g2","conceptId":"tx_stach_cause","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tachycardia stems from physiologic stressors: fever, pain, hypovolemia, anxiety, hypoxia. A reentrant AV nodal circuit produces SVT, a different rhythm with different management.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has sinus tachycardia at 128/min. Which causes should the nurse assess for and address? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fever"},{"id":"o1","text":"Pain"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hypovolemia/dehydration"},{"id":"o3","text":"Anxiety"},{"id":"o4","text":"A reentrant AV nodal circuit"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"tx_stach_cause_g3","conceptId":"tx_stach_cause","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In hypovolemia the tachycardia maintains cardiac output; blunting it pharmacologically before restoring volume can precipitate hemodynamic collapse. Treat the cause (give volume) first.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is it inappropriate to give a rate-controlling drug as the first response to sinus tachycardia in a hypovolemic patient?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The fast rate is compensating for low volume; slowing it could reduce cardiac output dangerously"},{"id":"o1","text":"Rate-control drugs do not work on the SA node"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sinus tachycardia is not affected by volume"},{"id":"o3","text":"The patient needs cardioversion first"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_stach_cause_g4","conceptId":"tx_stach_cause","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tachycardia reflects a physiologic response and is treated by addressing its cause, whereas SVT is a primary reentrant rhythm treated with vagal maneuvers, adenosine, or cardioversion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse explains to a student why sinus tachycardia is managed differently from SVT. The key distinction is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sinus tachycardia is a symptom of an underlying cause; SVT is a primary reentrant dysrhythmia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sinus tachycardia is always more dangerous"},{"id":"o2","text":"SVT is treated by fixing fever and pain"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus tachycardia requires immediate cardioversion"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_anticoag_why_g0","conceptId":"afib_anticoag_why","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In afib the atria quiver rather than contract, allowing blood to pool and clot; embolization of an atrial thrombus can cause a stroke. This risk drives anticoagulation therapy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is newly diagnosed with atrial fibrillation. Which complication is the priority concern that drives the plan of care?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Embolic stroke from atrial thrombus formation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypoglycemia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Pulmonary fibrosis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hypocalcemia"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_anticoag_why_g1","conceptId":"afib_anticoag_why","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Warfarin is an anticoagulant prescribed to prevent thromboembolic stroke in afib. It does not control rate or convert the rhythm — those require other agents.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with atrial fibrillation is discharged on warfarin. Which statement indicates correct understanding of why it was prescribed?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'This medication lowers my risk of a stroke from a clot.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'This medication converts my heart back to a normal rhythm.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'This medication slows my heart rate directly.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'This medication treats my blood pressure.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_anticoag_why_g2","conceptId":"afib_anticoag_why","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Afib teaching: stroke is the priority risk, anticoagulation lowers it, rate-control drugs slow the ventricular response, and lost atrial kick reduces output. Anticoagulants prevent clots; they do not convert the rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with new atrial fibrillation is being taught about the condition. Which statements are accurate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The main long-term risk is stroke from clot formation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Anticoagulation reduces stroke risk"},{"id":"o2","text":"Rate-control medications (e.g., metoprolol, diltiazem) slow the ventricular response"},{"id":"o3","text":"Loss of the atrial kick can reduce cardiac output"},{"id":"o4","text":"Anticoagulants will restore normal sinus rhythm"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"afib_anticoag_why_g3","conceptId":"afib_anticoag_why","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Metoprolol (a beta-blocker) provides rate control; warfarin (an anticoagulant) provides stroke prevention. The two drugs address different problems in afib management.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with afib asks why they take both metoprolol and warfarin. The nurse's best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'Metoprolol controls your heart rate, and warfarin prevents blood clots.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'Metoprolol prevents clots, and warfarin controls your rate.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'Both convert your rhythm to normal.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'Both lower your blood pressure only.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_anticoag_why_g4","conceptId":"afib_anticoag_why","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Without organized atrial contraction, blood stagnates (notably in the left atrial appendage) and can form thrombi that embolize to the brain — the basis for anticoagulation in afib.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which physiologic change in atrial fibrillation explains the elevated stroke risk?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Ineffective atrial contraction causes blood to stagnate and form clots, especially in the left atrial appendage"},{"id":"o1","text":"The ventricles stop contracting"},{"id":"o2","text":"The SA node fires too slowly"},{"id":"o3","text":"The QT interval shortens"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_precardiovert_g0","conceptId":"afib_precardiovert","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> If afib has lasted >48 hours (or unknown duration), the patient must be anticoagulated for several weeks or undergo a transesophageal echo to rule out atrial thrombus before cardioversion, to avoid dislodging a clot.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has been in atrial fibrillation for an unknown duration likely exceeding 48 hours. Elective cardioversion is being considered. Which action does the nurse anticipate before cardioversion?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Several weeks of anticoagulation (or a TEE to exclude atrial thrombus) before the procedure"},{"id":"o1","text":"Immediate cardioversion without any preparation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Discontinuing all anticoagulants first"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administering atropine"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_precardiovert_g1","conceptId":"afib_precardiovert","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Restoring organized atrial contraction can propel a pre-existing thrombus into the circulation; ensuring the atrium is clot-free (via weeks of anticoagulation or TEE) prevents cardioversion-related stroke.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is anticoagulation or a TEE required before cardioverting afib of >48 hours' duration?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Cardioversion can dislodge an existing atrial clot and cause an embolic stroke"},{"id":"o1","text":"Anticoagulation makes the shock more effective"},{"id":"o2","text":"It lowers the energy needed"},{"id":"o3","text":"It prevents the rhythm from recurring"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_precardiovert_g2","conceptId":"afib_precardiovert","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Pre-cardioversion afib care includes confirming anticoagulation/TEE, consent and sedation, sync mode, and continued post-procedure anticoagulation. Anticoagulation is not stopped just before the shock.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with afib of unknown duration is scheduled for elective cardioversion. Which actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Confirm adequate anticoagulation or a TEE before the procedure"},{"id":"o1","text":"Ensure informed consent and sedation are arranged"},{"id":"o2","text":"Verify the synchronization mode will be on"},{"id":"o3","text":"Continue anticoagulation after cardioversion"},{"id":"o4","text":"Stop anticoagulation immediately before the shock"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"afib_precardiovert_g3","conceptId":"afib_precardiovert","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> When afib onset is clearly under 48 hours, the clot-formation window is short and cardioversion may proceed more promptly per protocol, though anticoagulation decisions still follow risk assessment.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with new afib that began clearly less than 48 hours ago needs cardioversion. Compared with afib of unknown duration, this patient:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Has a lower thromboembolic risk, so cardioversion may proceed with less delay (per protocol)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Must wait several weeks regardless"},{"id":"o2","text":"Cannot be cardioverted at all"},{"id":"o3","text":"Requires no anticoagulation ever"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"afib_precardiovert_g4","conceptId":"afib_precardiovert","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Atrial mechanical function and stroke risk do not normalize instantly after cardioversion, so anticoagulation is continued for a defined period afterward.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>After successful cardioversion of afib, the nurse anticipates that anticoagulation will be:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Continued for a period afterward because clot risk persists"},{"id":"o1","text":"Stopped immediately since the rhythm is normal"},{"id":"o2","text":"Replaced with atropine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Never needed again"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"low_co_cues_g0","conceptId":"low_co_cues","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Signs of decreased cardiac output from a dysrhythmia include hypotension, altered mentation, chest pain, and poor peripheral perfusion. Warm extremities with normal mentation indicate adequate perfusion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment findings indicate that a dysrhythmia is causing decreased cardiac output and hemodynamic instability? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypotension"},{"id":"o1","text":"Altered mental status/confusion"},{"id":"o2","text":"Chest pain"},{"id":"o3","text":"Cool, clammy skin and weak pulses"},{"id":"o4","text":"Warm, well-perfused extremities with normal mentation"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"low_co_cues_g1","conceptId":"low_co_cues","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Instability is defined by signs of inadequate perfusion — hypotension, ischemic chest pain, altered mentation, signs of shock — not by heart rate alone.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a new tachydysrhythmia is most clearly 'unstable' when which finding is present?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypotension with chest pain and confusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"A rapid heart rate alone"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild anxiety"},{"id":"o3","text":"A palpable regular pulse"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"low_co_cues_g2","conceptId":"low_co_cues","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> New altered mentation with hypotension signals the dysrhythmia is compromising perfusion and demands urgent intervention, unlike an isolated mild tachycardia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding in a patient with a dysrhythmia should prompt the most urgent intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"New-onset confusion with a BP of 80/48"},{"id":"o1","text":"A heart rate of 110/min with normal BP"},{"id":"o2","text":"Occasional palpitations"},{"id":"o3","text":"A regular pulse and clear speech"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"low_co_cues_g3","conceptId":"low_co_cues","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Syncope, dyspnea/heart-failure signs, cool diaphoretic skin, and falling urine output indicate poor perfusion. A normal blood pressure with clear mentation suggests the patient is tolerating the rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is evaluating whether a patient's dysrhythmia is symptomatic. Which findings reflect inadequate perfusion? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Syncope or near-syncope"},{"id":"o1","text":"Dyspnea and signs of heart failure"},{"id":"o2","text":"Diaphoresis with cool skin"},{"id":"o3","text":"Decreased urine output"},{"id":"o4","text":"A blood pressure of 128/76 with clear mentation"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"low_co_cues_g4","conceptId":"low_co_cues","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The same rhythm can be tolerated or life-threatening depending on perfusion; clinical instability (not the rate alone) drives how aggressively the dysrhythmia is treated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why does the nurse assess perfusion (mentation, BP, skin, urine output) rather than the heart rate number alone when deciding how urgently to treat a dysrhythmia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Treatment urgency depends on whether the rhythm is producing symptoms of decreased cardiac output"},{"id":"o1","text":"The heart rate is unreliable on a monitor"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perfusion signs change the rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"The number always determines the drug"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_assess_g0","conceptId":"divert_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Diverticulitis most often affects the sigmoid colon, producing left lower quadrant pain. RLQ pain suggests appendicitis; epigastric pain radiating to the back suggests pancreatitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is admitted with suspected diverticulitis. Which assessment finding is most consistent with this diagnosis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Left lower quadrant pain"},{"id":"o1","text":"Right lower quadrant rebound tenderness"},{"id":"o2","text":"Upper abdominal pain radiating to the back"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hyperactive bowel sounds in all quadrants"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_assess_g1","conceptId":"divert_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acute diverticulitis classically presents with LLQ pain, fever, and an elevated WBC. The other clusters describe biliary disease, appendicitis, and peptic ulcer disease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which cluster of findings best supports a diagnosis of acute diverticulitis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"LLQ pain, fever, and leukocytosis"},{"id":"o1","text":"RUQ pain and jaundice"},{"id":"o2","text":"Periumbilical pain migrating to the RLQ"},{"id":"o3","text":"Burning epigastric pain relieved by food"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_assess_g2","conceptId":"divert_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Diverticulitis presents with LLQ pain, fever, leukocytosis, and altered bowel habits. RUQ pain with jaundice points to biliary/hepatic disease, not diverticulitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which findings would the nurse expect in a patient with acute diverticulitis? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Left lower quadrant pain"},{"id":"o1","text":"Fever"},{"id":"o2","text":"Elevated white blood cell count"},{"id":"o3","text":"Change in bowel habits"},{"id":"o4","text":"Right upper quadrant pain with jaundice"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"divert_assess_g3","conceptId":"divert_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> LLQ pain with fever and altered bowel habits fits diverticulitis (sigmoid colon). Cholecystitis is RUQ, gastritis is epigastric, and appendicitis is classically RLQ.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient reports steady left lower quadrant pain, low-grade fever, and constipation. The nurse recognizes these findings are most consistent with:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Diverticulitis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Cholecystitis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Gastritis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Appendicitis"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_assess_g4","conceptId":"divert_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Diverticula are most prevalent in the sigmoid colon, which lies in the left lower quadrant, so inflammation there localizes pain to the LLQ.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why does diverticulitis typically produce left lower quadrant pain?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Diverticula most commonly form in the sigmoid colon on the left side"},{"id":"o1","text":"The appendix is on the left"},{"id":"o2","text":"The gallbladder refers pain to the LLQ"},{"id":"o3","text":"The stomach lies in the LLQ"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_diet_g0","conceptId":"divert_diet","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Once the acute infection resolves, a high-fiber diet with adequate fluids helps prevent recurrence by promoting soft, bulky stools. A low-fiber/clear-liquid diet is used only during the acute phase.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient recovering from acute diverticulitis is being discharged. Which long-term dietary teaching is appropriate once fully recovered?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Gradually increase dietary fiber and fluids to prevent recurrence"},{"id":"o1","text":"Follow a permanent clear-liquid diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"Avoid all fruits and vegetables for life"},{"id":"o3","text":"Eat a low-fiber diet indefinitely"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_diet_g1","conceptId":"divert_diet","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The acute phase calls for bowel rest with low-fiber/clear liquids; high fiber is reintroduced gradually after recovery for long-term prevention. Distinguishing the two phases is the key teaching point.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>During the ACUTE phase of diverticulitis, which diet is appropriate, in contrast to the long-term plan?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Low-fiber or clear liquids to rest the bowel"},{"id":"o1","text":"High-fiber foods immediately"},{"id":"o2","text":"A regular full diet"},{"id":"o3","text":"Daily bran and raw vegetables"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_diet_g2","conceptId":"divert_diet","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Long-term prevention emphasizes gradual fiber increase, hydration, and regular soft stools. Lifelong avoidance of whole grains is not recommended; older seed/nut restrictions are no longer supported.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which dietary teaching points are appropriate for long-term prevention of diverticulitis recurrence? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Increase fiber gradually"},{"id":"o1","text":"Drink adequate fluids"},{"id":"o2","text":"Aim for regular soft, bulky stools"},{"id":"o3","text":"Resume a balanced high-fiber diet after recovery"},{"id":"o4","text":"Permanently avoid all whole grains"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"divert_diet_g3","conceptId":"divert_diet","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Routine avoidance of seeds, nuts, and popcorn is no longer evidence-based. The emphasis for prevention is a high-fiber diet with adequate fluid intake.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient recovering from diverticulitis asks if seeds and nuts must be avoided forever. The nurse's best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'Current evidence does not support routinely avoiding seeds and nuts; focus on overall high fiber and fluids.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'You must avoid all seeds and nuts permanently.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'A low-fiber diet for life is safest.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'You should avoid fruits and vegetables.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_diet_g4","conceptId":"divert_diet","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Adequate fiber produces softer, bulkier stool and reduces intraluminal colonic pressure, decreasing the likelihood of recurrent diverticular inflammation. It is introduced after, not during, the acute phase.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is a high-fiber diet recommended once a patient recovers from diverticulitis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fiber softens and adds bulk to stool, lowering colonic pressure and recurrence risk"},{"id":"o1","text":"Fiber sterilizes the diverticula"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fiber replaces the need for antibiotics"},{"id":"o3","text":"Fiber should be started during the acute infection"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_assess_g0","conceptId":"uc_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Ulcerative colitis characteristically causes frequent bloody, mucus-containing diarrhea with urgency. Constipation and isolated RLQ pain are not typical of a UC flare.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with ulcerative colitis is admitted with an acute flare. Which finding does the nurse expect?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Frequent bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"o1","text":"Constipation and bloating"},{"id":"o2","text":"Severe right lower quadrant pain"},{"id":"o3","text":"Vomiting without diarrhea"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_assess_g1","conceptId":"uc_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> UC flares produce bloody, urgent diarrhea with cramping due to continuous mucosal inflammation of the colon and rectum.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which symptom pattern is most characteristic of an ulcerative colitis exacerbation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Bloody diarrhea with urgency and lower abdominal cramping"},{"id":"o1","text":"Greasy, foul-smelling stools"},{"id":"o2","text":"Painless rectal bleeding without diarrhea"},{"id":"o3","text":"Alternating constipation and diarrhea without blood"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_assess_g2","conceptId":"uc_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> UC flares cause bloody diarrhea, cramping, urgency, and frequent stools. Weight loss — not gain — is typical due to malabsorption and decreased intake.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which findings should the nurse expect in a patient with an ulcerative colitis flare? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"o1","text":"Abdominal cramping"},{"id":"o2","text":"Urgency to defecate"},{"id":"o3","text":"Increased stool frequency"},{"id":"o4","text":"Weight gain"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"uc_assess_g3","conceptId":"uc_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Frequent bloody diarrhea in UC leads to fluid/electrolyte loss and blood loss, so the nurse monitors for dehydration, electrolyte derangement, and anemia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with UC reports 10-15 bloody stools per day with urgency. The nurse anticipates monitoring for which complication?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Dehydration, electrolyte imbalance, and anemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypercoagulable polycythemia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hyperkalemia from constipation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Weight gain from fluid retention"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_assess_g4","conceptId":"uc_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> UC produces continuous, superficial (mucosal) inflammation confined to the colon and rectum — distinguishing it from Crohn's transmural, skip-lesion pattern.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement about ulcerative colitis inflammation is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It is continuous and limited to the mucosa of the colon and rectum"},{"id":"o1","text":"It causes skip lesions throughout the GI tract"},{"id":"o2","text":"It affects the full thickness of the bowel wall from mouth to anus"},{"id":"o3","text":"It spares the rectum entirely"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_anemia_g0","conceptId":"uc_anemia","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Ongoing bloody diarrhea from ulcerated colonic mucosa causes chronic iron-deficiency anemia in UC. Dehydration would raise, not lower, the hemoglobin concentration.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a long history of ulcerative colitis has a hemoglobin of 8.2 g/dL. What is the most likely explanation for this anemia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Chronic blood loss from inflamed, ulcerated colonic mucosa"},{"id":"o1","text":"Acute hemolysis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Vitamin B12 deficiency from gastrectomy"},{"id":"o3","text":"Dehydration causing hemoconcentration"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_anemia_g1","conceptId":"uc_anemia","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chronic intestinal blood loss in UC depletes iron stores, producing iron-deficiency (microcytic) anemia over time.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which type of anemia is most commonly associated with chronic ulcerative colitis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Iron-deficiency anemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Folate-induced macrocytosis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sickle cell anemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Aplastic anemia"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_anemia_g2","conceptId":"uc_anemia","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chronic GI blood loss produces low H&H, fatigue/pallor, a history of bloody stools, and low iron stores (ferritin). Dehydration does not raise reticulocytes.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with chronic UC and anemia is being assessed. Which findings support iron-deficiency anemia from chronic GI blood loss? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Low hemoglobin and hematocrit"},{"id":"o1","text":"Fatigue and pallor"},{"id":"o2","text":"History of frequent bloody stools"},{"id":"o3","text":"Low ferritin"},{"id":"o4","text":"Elevated reticulocyte count due to dehydration"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"uc_anemia_g3","conceptId":"uc_anemia","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Correcting iron-deficiency anemia in UC requires iron replacement and control of the colonic inflammation driving the blood loss; severe cases may need transfusion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse anticipates which intervention for a UC patient with iron-deficiency anemia from chronic blood loss?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Iron supplementation and treatment of the underlying colitis"},{"id":"o1","text":"High-dose vitamin C only"},{"id":"o2","text":"Permanent fluid restriction"},{"id":"o3","text":"Daily laxatives"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_anemia_g4","conceptId":"uc_anemia","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A severe UC flare can produce substantial colonic bleeding, so serial H&H monitoring detects worsening anemia and guides transfusion decisions.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why does the nurse monitor hemoglobin and hematocrit closely in a patient hospitalized with a severe UC flare?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Ongoing colonic bleeding can cause significant, sometimes rapid, blood loss"},{"id":"o1","text":"UC raises hemoglobin"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fluid overload falsely lowers H&H"},{"id":"o3","text":"The values are unrelated to UC"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_assess_g0","conceptId":"crohn_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's typically causes non-bloody diarrhea, crampy RLQ pain, and weight loss. Bloody diarrhea is more characteristic of ulcerative colitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with Crohn's disease is admitted with severe abdominal pain and frequent diarrhea. Which clinical manifestation would the nurse expect?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Non-bloody diarrhea with right lower quadrant pain"},{"id":"o1","text":"Significant weight gain"},{"id":"o2","text":"Generalized edema"},{"id":"o3","text":"Continuous rectal bleeding with every stool"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_assess_g1","conceptId":"crohn_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's produces discontinuous skip lesions, can involve any part of the GI tract, and is transmural. UC is continuous, mucosal, and limited to the colon and rectum.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which feature distinguishes Crohn's disease from ulcerative colitis on assessment?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Skip lesions that can occur anywhere from mouth to anus, with transmural involvement"},{"id":"o1","text":"Continuous inflammation limited to the colon and rectum"},{"id":"o2","text":"Inflammation confined to the mucosa only"},{"id":"o3","text":"Always bloody diarrhea"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_assess_g2","conceptId":"crohn_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's features non-bloody diarrhea, RLQ pain, weight loss, and complications like fistulas/strictures from transmural disease. Continuous mucosal rectal inflammation describes UC.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which manifestations are characteristic of Crohn's disease? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Non-bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"o1","text":"Right lower quadrant pain"},{"id":"o2","text":"Weight loss and malnutrition"},{"id":"o3","text":"Risk of fistula and stricture formation"},{"id":"o4","text":"Continuous mucosal-only inflammation of the rectum"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"crohn_assess_g3","conceptId":"crohn_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Transmural inflammation in Crohn's can erode through the bowel wall, creating fistulas, abscesses, and strictures — complications less common in mucosal-only UC.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with Crohn's disease is at risk for fistula formation primarily because the inflammation:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Extends through the entire thickness of the bowel wall (transmural)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Is limited to the mucosal surface"},{"id":"o2","text":"Affects only the rectum"},{"id":"o3","text":"Never causes structural damage"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_assess_g4","conceptId":"crohn_assess","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's frequently involves the small intestine, impairing nutrient absorption and causing deficiencies (e.g., B12, fat-soluble vitamins) and weight loss.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which long-term complication is the patient with Crohn's disease at increased risk for due to chronic small-bowel involvement?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Malabsorption and nutritional deficiencies"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypertension"},{"id":"o2","text":"Polycythemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hyperkalemia from constipation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_vs_crohn_g0","conceptId":"uc_vs_crohn","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Correct: Crohn's can affect the whole GI tract with transmural skip lesions; UC is continuous and limited to colon/rectum. Both are chronic and require ongoing management, so the last statement is wrong.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is teaching about the differences between ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease. Which patient statements indicate correct understanding? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'Crohn's can affect any part of the GI tract from mouth to anus.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'Ulcerative colitis affects only the colon and rectum.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'Crohn's causes skip lesions, while UC has continuous inflammation.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'Crohn's involves the full thickness of the bowel wall.'"},{"id":"o4","text":"'Both diseases are mild and never need long-term treatment.'"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"uc_vs_crohn_g1","conceptId":"uc_vs_crohn","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> UC: continuous, mucosal inflammation of the colon/rectum with bloody diarrhea. Crohn's: transmural inflammation with skip lesions anywhere in the GI tract.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Ulcerative colitis is characterized by [b0] inflammation limited to the colon and rectum and typically causes [b1]. In contrast, Crohn's disease causes [b2] inflammation with skip lesions.</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"continuous"},{"id":"o1","text":"patchy"},{"id":"o2","text":"transmural"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"o1","text":"greasy stools"},{"id":"o2","text":"constipation"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"transmural"},{"id":"o1","text":"mucosal-only"},{"id":"o2","text":"rectal-only"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"uc_vs_crohn_g2","conceptId":"uc_vs_crohn","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> UC is continuous mucosal inflammation of the colon/rectum; Crohn's is discontinuous, transmural, and can occur anywhere in the GI tract.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement correctly contrasts the two forms of inflammatory bowel disease?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"UC is continuous and mucosal; Crohn's is patchy (skip lesions) and transmural"},{"id":"o1","text":"UC affects mouth to anus; Crohn's affects only the rectum"},{"id":"o2","text":"Both cause exclusively bloody diarrhea"},{"id":"o3","text":"Crohn's is limited to the mucosa; UC is transmural"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"uc_vs_crohn_g3","conceptId":"uc_vs_crohn","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's features skip lesions, transmural involvement, small-bowel disease, and fistula/stricture risk. Confinement to the rectum and colon describes UC.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which characteristics belong to Crohn's disease (rather than ulcerative colitis)? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Skip lesions"},{"id":"o1","text":"Transmural inflammation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Can involve the small intestine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Increased risk of fistulas and strictures"},{"id":"o4","text":"Inflammation always confined to the rectum and colon"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"uc_vs_crohn_g4","conceptId":"uc_vs_crohn","domain":"GI","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Crohn's frequently involves the nutrient-absorbing small intestine, causing malabsorption, whereas UC is confined to the colon and rectum, which is not a primary site of nutrient absorption.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient asks why their Crohn's disease causes nutritional problems that their friend's ulcerative colitis does not. The best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'Crohn's often involves the small intestine where nutrients are absorbed, while UC is limited to the large bowel.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'UC affects the whole GI tract and Crohn's only the colon.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'Both diseases affect the same areas equally.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'Crohn's only affects the rectum.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_acute_mgmt_g0","conceptId":"divert_acute_mgmt","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The acute phase of diverticulitis is managed with bowel rest (NPO), IV fluids, and IV antibiotics. High fiber and laxatives are avoided acutely; they are part of long-term prevention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is caring for a patient with acute diverticulitis. Which intervention should the nurse expect during the acute phase?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Maintain NPO status and administer IV fluids"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage a high-fiber diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer daily laxatives"},{"id":"o3","text":"Insert an NG tube for routine feeding"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_acute_mgmt_g1","conceptId":"divert_acute_mgmt","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acute diverticulitis is treated with bowel rest, IV fluids, IV antibiotics, and analgesia. Fiber is reintroduced only after the acute infection resolves.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which interventions should the nurse expect during the acute phase of diverticulitis? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"NPO or clear liquids for bowel rest"},{"id":"o1","text":"IV fluids"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV antibiotics"},{"id":"o3","text":"Pain management"},{"id":"o4","text":"A high-fiber diet immediately"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"divert_acute_mgmt_g2","conceptId":"divert_acute_mgmt","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The first priority in acute diverticulitis is supportive treatment of the infection — IV access for fluids and antibiotics — before education and activity, and the patient is kept NPO, not fed.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Place in priority order: a patient with acute diverticulitis needs all of the following. Which should the nurse do FIRST?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Establish IV access and begin prescribed IV fluids and antibiotics"},{"id":"o1","text":"Educate about a low-fiber diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"Provide a regular meal tray"},{"id":"o3","text":"Encourage ambulation around the unit"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_acute_mgmt_g3","conceptId":"divert_acute_mgmt","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Bowel rest decreases colonic motility and secretions, allowing the inflamed diverticula to heal while antibiotics treat the infection. Diet advances gradually as symptoms improve.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is the patient with acute diverticulitis kept NPO during the acute phase?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"To rest the bowel and reduce colonic activity while the infection is treated"},{"id":"o1","text":"To prepare for immediate surgery in all cases"},{"id":"o2","text":"To prevent aspiration from the colon"},{"id":"o3","text":"To force weight loss"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_acute_mgmt_g4","conceptId":"divert_acute_mgmt","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> As acute diverticulitis resolves, the diet advances stepwise from clear liquids to low-fiber and eventually to high-fiber for long-term prevention once fully recovered.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with acute diverticulitis improves after several days of treatment. The nurse anticipates the diet will be advanced:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Gradually from clear liquids to low-fiber, then to high-fiber after full recovery"},{"id":"o1","text":"Immediately to a high-fiber diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"To a permanent clear-liquid diet"},{"id":"o3","text":"Directly to a regular diet with bran"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_avoid_meds_g0","conceptId":"divert_avoid_meds","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs (and corticosteroids) increase the risk of diverticular bleeding and perforation and are generally avoided. Acetaminophen and stool softeners are acceptable.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient asks how to prevent future diverticulitis episodes once recovered. Which medication class should this patient generally avoid?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Acetaminophen"},{"id":"o2","text":"Stool softeners"},{"id":"o3","text":"Antihypertensives"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_avoid_meds_g1","conceptId":"divert_avoid_meds","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs impair mucosal protection and are associated with increased diverticular bleeding and perforation, so they are generally avoided in diverticular disease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why are NSAIDs generally discouraged in patients with diverticular disease?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"They raise the risk of diverticular bleeding and perforation"},{"id":"o1","text":"They cause constipation that ruptures diverticula"},{"id":"o2","text":"They have no effect on the GI tract"},{"id":"o3","text":"They are too weak for pain control"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_avoid_meds_g2","conceptId":"divert_avoid_meds","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs and corticosteroids raise bleeding/perforation risk, and constipating opioids should be used cautiously. Acetaminophen and stool softeners are acceptable and may be helpful.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which agents are generally best avoided in a patient with a history of diverticulitis? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"NSAIDs"},{"id":"o1","text":"Corticosteroids (when avoidable)"},{"id":"o2","text":"Opioids that promote constipation (use cautiously)"},{"id":"o3","text":"Acetaminophen"},{"id":"o4","text":"Prescribed stool softeners"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2"]},{"id":"divert_avoid_meds_g3","conceptId":"divert_avoid_meds","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acetaminophen is preferred for mild pain because the NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen, high-dose aspirin) increase diverticular bleeding and perforation risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with diverticular disease needs an analgesic. Which is the safer choice for routine mild pain?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Acetaminophen within recommended limits"},{"id":"o1","text":"Ibuprofen around the clock"},{"id":"o2","text":"Naproxen twice daily"},{"id":"o3","text":"Aspirin at high doses"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_avoid_meds_g4","conceptId":"divert_avoid_meds","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chronic NSAID use elevates diverticular bleeding and perforation risk; the nurse should raise this with the patient and recommend the provider review safer analgesic options.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient recovering from diverticulitis takes daily ibuprofen for knee arthritis. The nurse should:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Discuss the increased GI bleeding/perforation risk and suggest reviewing alternatives with the provider"},{"id":"o1","text":"Tell the patient ibuprofen is completely safe"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage doubling the ibuprofen dose"},{"id":"o3","text":"Advise switching to a high-dose aspirin regimen"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_perforation_g0","conceptId":"divert_perforation","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A rigid, board-like abdomen with severe pain, fever, and hypotension signals perforation and peritonitis — a surgical emergency requiring immediate intervention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with diverticulitis suddenly develops a rigid, board-like abdomen, severe pain, fever, and hypotension. The nurse recognizes this most likely indicates:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Perforation with peritonitis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild constipation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Resolving inflammation"},{"id":"o3","text":"A normal response to antibiotics"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_perforation_g1","conceptId":"divert_perforation","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> These findings indicate perforation/peritonitis. The nurse must escalate immediately, keep the patient NPO, and prepare for urgent surgical management; enemas are contraindicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A diverticulitis patient develops sudden severe abdominal pain with rebound tenderness and a rigid abdomen. The nurse's priority action is to:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Notify the provider immediately and prepare for emergency evaluation/surgery"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer a cleansing enema"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage oral fluids"},{"id":"o3","text":"Reassure the patient and recheck in an hour"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_perforation_g2","conceptId":"divert_perforation","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Perforation/peritonitis produces a rigid abdomen, rebound tenderness, fever, and signs of sepsis. A soft, nontender abdomen with normal vitals does not.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which findings suggest a diverticular perforation with peritonitis? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rigid, board-like abdomen"},{"id":"o1","text":"Rebound tenderness"},{"id":"o2","text":"High fever"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hypotension and tachycardia (signs of sepsis/shock)"},{"id":"o4","text":"Soft, nontender abdomen with normal vitals"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"divert_perforation_g3","conceptId":"divert_perforation","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Perforation releases fecal/bacterial contents into the sterile peritoneal cavity, producing peritonitis and risk of life-threatening sepsis, which requires urgent surgical control.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is a perforated diverticulum considered a surgical emergency?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Bowel contents spill into the peritoneal cavity, causing peritonitis and possible sepsis"},{"id":"o1","text":"It always resolves with oral antibiotics"},{"id":"o2","text":"Perforation only causes mild discomfort"},{"id":"o3","text":"The colon heals itself within hours"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_perforation_g4","conceptId":"divert_perforation","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Enemas are contraindicated with suspected perforation because increased intraluminal pressure can worsen the perforation and peritoneal contamination. IV fluids, antibiotics, and monitoring are appropriate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with suspected diverticular perforation is NPO and being prepared for surgery. Which intervention is contraindicated?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administering a cleansing enema"},{"id":"o1","text":"Establishing IV access for fluids"},{"id":"o2","text":"Giving prescribed IV antibiotics"},{"id":"o3","text":"Monitoring vital signs for sepsis"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_sepsis_first_g0","conceptId":"divert_sepsis_first","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, tachycardia, and hypotension indicate early sepsis. Restoring perfusion with IV fluids is the first priority, along with antibiotics; education and activity are not the immediate concern.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with acute diverticulitis has a temperature of 102.2°F, HR 118, and BP 88/52. Which action should the nurse take first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administer IV fluids to support perfusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"Educate the patient about a high-fiber diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage ambulation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Provide a regular meal tray"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_sepsis_first_g1","conceptId":"divert_sepsis_first","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Early antibiotic administration is critical in sepsis from diverticulitis. Fluids restore perfusion and timely antibiotics treat the source; teaching and activity come later.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A diverticulitis patient with signs of sepsis (fever, tachycardia, hypotension) needs prompt care. After IV fluids, which intervention is the priority?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administer prescribed IV antibiotics promptly"},{"id":"o1","text":"Provide diet teaching"},{"id":"o2","text":"Ambulate the patient"},{"id":"o3","text":"Remove the IV line"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_sepsis_first_g2","conceptId":"divert_sepsis_first","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Early sepsis care includes fluids, antibiotics, cultures/lactate, and perfusion monitoring. Feeding a high-fiber meal is inappropriate during the acute septic phase (patient is kept NPO).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with diverticulitis shows fever 102.2°F, HR 118, BP 88/52. Which interventions are appropriate now? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Begin IV fluid resuscitation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer prescribed IV antibiotics"},{"id":"o2","text":"Obtain blood cultures and lactate as ordered"},{"id":"o3","text":"Monitor urine output and mental status"},{"id":"o4","text":"Provide a high-fiber meal"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"divert_sepsis_first_g3","conceptId":"divert_sepsis_first","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The combination of hypotension, tachycardia, and fever signals systemic infection/sepsis, prompting immediate fluid and antibiotic intervention, unlike isolated mild findings.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment finding in a diverticulitis patient most strongly indicates progression to sepsis requiring rapid intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypotension with tachycardia and fever"},{"id":"o1","text":"A single temperature of 99.8°F"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild LLQ tenderness with normal vitals"},{"id":"o3","text":"Constipation without other symptoms"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"divert_sepsis_first_g4","conceptId":"divert_sepsis_first","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In sepsis, timely fluid resuscitation and antibiotics restore perfusion and control the infection source, reducing the risk of progression to septic shock and organ failure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is rapid fluid and antibiotic administration emphasized when a diverticulitis patient becomes septic?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Early intervention improves perfusion and outcomes and limits progression to septic shock"},{"id":"o1","text":"Antibiotics are optional in sepsis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fluids worsen hypotension"},{"id":"o3","text":"Delaying treatment is preferred to observe the trend"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_g0","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In toxic megacolon, enemas and cathartics are contraindicated because they can precipitate perforation. Care includes NPO status, NG decompression, IV fluids, and possible surgery.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with ulcerative colitis develops a distended abdomen, high fever, tachycardia, and absent bowel sounds. The nurse suspects toxic megacolon. Which intervention is contraindicated?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Administering a cleansing enema or cathartic"},{"id":"o1","text":"Keeping the patient NPO"},{"id":"o2","text":"Preparing for nasogastric decompression"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administering IV fluids"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_g1","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Toxic megacolon care is bowel rest (NPO), NG decompression, IV fluids/electrolytes, and close monitoring for perforation. Laxatives/enemas are contraindicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with UC is suspected of developing toxic megacolon. Which nursing actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Keep the patient NPO"},{"id":"o1","text":"Prepare for nasogastric decompression"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer IV fluids and electrolytes"},{"id":"o3","text":"Notify the provider and monitor for perforation"},{"id":"o4","text":"Give a stimulant laxative to relieve distension"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_g2","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Toxic megacolon presents with massive colonic dilation, systemic toxicity (fever, tachycardia), and absent bowel sounds — a life-threatening emergency.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which set of findings should make the nurse suspect toxic megacolon in a patient with ulcerative colitis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Marked abdominal distension, high fever, tachycardia, and absent bowel sounds"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild cramping with normal vital signs"},{"id":"o2","text":"Constipation with active bowel sounds"},{"id":"o3","text":"Isolated low-grade fever with no distension"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_g3","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The colon in toxic megacolon is massively dilated and fragile; agents that increase motility or pressure can precipitate perforation and peritonitis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why are cathartics and enemas dangerous in suspected toxic megacolon?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"They increase intraluminal pressure in an already dilated, friable colon and can cause perforation"},{"id":"o1","text":"They relieve the distension safely"},{"id":"o2","text":"They have no effect on the colon"},{"id":"o3","text":"They are the first-line treatment"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_g4","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sudden severe pain, abdominal rigidity, and hemodynamic deterioration suggest perforation, a catastrophic complication requiring emergency surgery. Improvement and normalizing vitals are reassuring.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with toxic megacolon is being monitored. Which new finding indicates a possible perforation and requires immediate escalation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sudden severe abdominal pain with rigidity and worsening hypotension"},{"id":"o1","text":"Gradual improvement in distension"},{"id":"o2","text":"Return of normal bowel sounds"},{"id":"o3","text":"A decreasing temperature toward normal"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_complication_g0","conceptId":"crohn_complication","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, severe pain, and rebound tenderness suggest perforation, abscess, or obstruction — acute complications of transmural Crohn's disease that demand immediate intervention. The other findings are chronic and less urgent.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is caring for a patient with Crohn's disease. Which complication is most concerning and requires immediate intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fever, severe abdominal pain, and rebound tenderness"},{"id":"o1","text":"Chronic diarrhea and weight loss"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fatigue and mild anemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Oral ulcers and joint pain"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_complication_g1","conceptId":"crohn_complication","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Peritoneal signs, fever with severe pain, obstruction signs, and hemodynamic instability indicate acute Crohn's complications. Mild fatigue with stable vitals is not an emergency.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which findings in a patient with Crohn's disease warrant immediate provider notification? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rebound tenderness and rigidity"},{"id":"o1","text":"High fever with severe abdominal pain"},{"id":"o2","text":"Signs of bowel obstruction (distension, vomiting, no flatus)"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sudden drop in blood pressure with tachycardia"},{"id":"o4","text":"Mild fatigue with normal vital signs"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"crohn_complication_g2","conceptId":"crohn_complication","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Strictures from transmural Crohn's inflammation can cause bowel obstruction, presenting with distension, vomiting, and absent flatus — requiring prompt evaluation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with Crohn's disease develops abdominal distension, vomiting, and absence of flatus. The nurse suspects:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Bowel obstruction from a stricture"},{"id":"o1","text":"Resolution of the flare"},{"id":"o2","text":"Simple constipation needing fiber"},{"id":"o3","text":"Improved nutritional status"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_complication_g3","conceptId":"crohn_complication","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Transmural (full-thickness) inflammation in Crohn's can penetrate the bowel wall, forming fistulas and abscesses — complications uncommon in the mucosal-only inflammation of UC.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is the patient with Crohn's disease at higher risk for fistulas and abscesses than the patient with ulcerative colitis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Crohn's inflammation is transmural and can erode through the bowel wall"},{"id":"o1","text":"Crohn's affects only the mucosa"},{"id":"o2","text":"Crohn's is limited to the rectum"},{"id":"o3","text":"Crohn's never causes structural complications"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_complication_g4","conceptId":"crohn_complication","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> These findings suggest perforation/peritonitis. The priority is NPO status, immediate provider notification, and surgical preparation — not feeding, enemas, or ambulation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A Crohn's patient reports sudden severe abdominal pain and has a rigid abdomen and a temperature of 102°F. The nurse's priority is to:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Keep the patient NPO, notify the provider, and prepare for possible surgery"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage a high-fiber meal"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer an enema"},{"id":"o3","text":"Ambulate the patient to relieve gas"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ibd_plan_g0","conceptId":"ibd_plan","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Monitoring stools for blood tracks disease severity and bleeding in an IBD flare. Fluids are not restricted (losses are high), high fiber is avoided acutely, and rigid ambulation goals are not indicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which nursing action will the nurse include in the plan of care for a patient admitted with an IBD exacerbation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Monitor stools for blood"},{"id":"o1","text":"Restrict IV fluid intake"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage a high-fiber diet during the flare"},{"id":"o3","text":"Ambulate the patient six times daily"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ibd_plan_g1","conceptId":"ibd_plan","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acute IBD care includes stool monitoring, fluid/electrolyte maintenance, bowel rest, and watching for dehydration/anemia. High-fiber diets are avoided during active flares.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which interventions are appropriate in the plan of care for an acute IBD exacerbation? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Monitor stool frequency and for blood"},{"id":"o1","text":"Maintain fluid and electrolyte balance"},{"id":"o2","text":"Provide bowel rest as ordered"},{"id":"o3","text":"Monitor for signs of dehydration and anemia"},{"id":"o4","text":"Encourage a high-residue, high-fiber diet during the flare"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"ibd_plan_g2","conceptId":"ibd_plan","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Frequent diarrhea causes significant fluid and electrolyte loss, so monitoring volume status and electrolytes is a priority. Fluids are replaced, not restricted, during a flare.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with an IBD flare is having frequent diarrhea. Which is a priority nursing assessment?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fluid volume status and electrolytes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Daily weight gain goals"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encouraging high-fiber intake"},{"id":"o3","text":"Limiting fluid intake to reduce stools"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ibd_plan_g3","conceptId":"ibd_plan","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Resting the bowel decreases mechanical and secretory activity in inflamed intestine, helping reduce diarrhea and pain during the acute phase; nutrition may be provided parenterally if needed.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is bowel rest often part of the plan of care during an acute IBD flare?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It reduces stimulation of the inflamed bowel and helps control symptoms"},{"id":"o1","text":"It promotes immediate weight gain"},{"id":"o2","text":"It permanently cures the disease"},{"id":"o3","text":"It allows a high-fiber diet to be tolerated"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ibd_plan_g4","conceptId":"ibd_plan","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Increasing distension with fever and tachycardia may signal toxic megacolon or perforation and must be reported promptly. The other findings are not acutely alarming.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with an IBD flare has had 12 stools today, several bloody. Which finding should the nurse report promptly?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Increasing abdominal distension with fever and tachycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"A single soft stool overnight"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild fatigue that improves with rest"},{"id":"o3","text":"A stable hemoglobin from yesterday"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_avoid_med_g0","conceptId":"crohn_avoid_med","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs aggravate GI mucosal injury and can trigger or worsen Crohn's flares, so the order should be questioned. Opioids and acetaminophen are generally preferred for pain in IBD.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with Crohn's disease in a severe flare on TPN has these analgesic orders. Which should the nurse question?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID)"},{"id":"o1","text":"An IV opioid as ordered"},{"id":"o2","text":"Acetaminophen within safe limits"},{"id":"o3","text":"A prescribed antispasmodic"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_avoid_med_g1","conceptId":"crohn_avoid_med","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs impair protective prostaglandins and injure the GI mucosa, which can exacerbate IBD inflammation and bleeding, so their use is questioned in active disease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why should NSAIDs be questioned in a patient with active inflammatory bowel disease?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"They damage the GI mucosa and can precipitate or worsen flares"},{"id":"o1","text":"They are too weak to relieve pain"},{"id":"o2","text":"They cause excessive sedation"},{"id":"o3","text":"They have no effect on the GI tract"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_avoid_med_g2","conceptId":"crohn_avoid_med","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs can worsen mucosal injury, and anti-motility/strongly constipating agents can precipitate toxic megacolon in severe colitis. Acetaminophen and indicated corticosteroids are appropriate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which medications should the nurse question or use cautiously in a patient with an active IBD flare? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"NSAIDs"},{"id":"o1","text":"Antidiarrheals/anti-motility agents in severe colitis (risk of toxic megacolon)"},{"id":"o2","text":"Acetaminophen at safe doses"},{"id":"o3","text":"Opioids that significantly slow the gut (cautious use)"},{"id":"o4","text":"Prescribed corticosteroids for the flare"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o3"]},{"id":"crohn_avoid_med_g3","conceptId":"crohn_avoid_med","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In severe active colitis, slowing gut motility can lead to colonic dilation and toxic megacolon, so anti-motility/antidiarrheal agents are used cautiously or avoided and the order should be clarified.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with severe ulcerative colitis is prescribed an antidiarrheal agent. The nurse recognizes this order is concerning because:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Anti-motility agents can precipitate toxic megacolon in severe colitis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Antidiarrheals always cure colitis"},{"id":"o2","text":"They are the safest first-line therapy"},{"id":"o3","text":"They prevent all complications"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crohn_avoid_med_g4","conceptId":"crohn_avoid_med","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Because NSAIDs can aggravate IBD, acetaminophen or carefully selected opioids are preferred for pain control in active disease.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which analgesic is generally preferred for pain management in a patient with active inflammatory bowel disease?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Acetaminophen or an opioid as indicated, rather than an NSAID"},{"id":"o1","text":"High-dose ibuprofen"},{"id":"o2","text":"Around-the-clock naproxen"},{"id":"o3","text":"Daily aspirin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie_g0","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Distension, fever, tachycardia, and absent bowel sounds in UC point to toxic megacolon. Priorities are bowel rest (NPO), provider notification, and NG decompression; enemas/laxatives are contraindicated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with UC develops a distended, tender abdomen, fever 103°F, HR 130, and absent bowel sounds. Two priority actions are [b0] and [b1]. The condition the nurse is most concerned about is [b2].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"keep the patient NPO"},{"id":"o1","text":"give a cleansing enema"},{"id":"o2","text":"encourage high-fiber meals"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"notify the provider and prepare for NG decompression"},{"id":"o1","text":"administer a laxative"},{"id":"o2","text":"ambulate the patient"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b2","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"toxic megacolon with possible perforation"},{"id":"o1","text":"simple constipation"},{"id":"o2","text":"dehydration only"}],"correct":"o0"}]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie_g1","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sudden severe pain with rigidity plus hemodynamic deterioration indicates perforation. Improving distension, returning bowel sounds, and stable vitals are reassuring signs.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with suspected toxic megacolon is deteriorating. Which two findings together most strongly indicate perforation? (Select the best single option.)</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sudden severe pain with abdominal rigidity and worsening hypotension"},{"id":"o1","text":"Improving distension and normalizing temperature"},{"id":"o2","text":"Return of bowel sounds and decreased pain"},{"id":"o3","text":"Stable vitals with mild tenderness"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie_g2","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Monitoring includes abdominal girth, vital signs, bowel sounds, and perforation signs. The patient is NPO, so tracking high-fiber intake is irrelevant.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>For a patient with toxic megacolon, which parameters should the nurse monitor closely? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Abdominal girth/distension"},{"id":"o1","text":"Vital signs for sepsis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Bowel sounds"},{"id":"o3","text":"Signs of perforation (sudden severe pain, rigidity)"},{"id":"o4","text":"Daily caloric intake of a high-fiber diet"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie_g3","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NG decompression removes gas and secretions to reduce intraluminal pressure in the dilated colon, lowering perforation risk. It is not used for feeding or cleansing in this setting.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with toxic megacolon is NPO with an NG tube. The primary purpose of the NG tube is to:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Decompress the dilated bowel and reduce pressure"},{"id":"o1","text":"Provide enteral nutrition"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer oral medications"},{"id":"o3","text":"Deliver a cleansing solution"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie_g4","conceptId":"toxic_megacolon_bowtie","domain":"GI","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Untreated toxic megacolon can perforate, spilling colonic contents into the peritoneum and causing peritonitis and septic shock — the most dangerous outcome requiring emergency surgery.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which condition, if untreated, is the most life-threatening progression of toxic megacolon?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Colonic perforation with peritonitis and septic shock"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild dehydration"},{"id":"o2","text":"Iron-deficiency anemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Transient constipation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"leuk_infection_risk_g0","conceptId":"leuk_infection_risk","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In leukemia the proliferating WBCs are immature, nonfunctional blasts. A high count does not equal functional immunity, so infection risk is high.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A newly diagnosed leukemia patient asks why infection risk is high when the WBC count is elevated. Best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"The white cells are immature and abnormal, so they can't fight infection effectively.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"A high white count fully protects you from infection.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Your platelets fight infection instead.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"The lab value is probably an error.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"leuk_infection_risk_g1","conceptId":"leuk_infection_risk","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Blasts are nonfunctional and crowd out normal hematopoiesis, lowering effective immunity despite a high total WBC.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement best explains the paradox of leukocytosis with high infection risk in acute leukemia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The leukemic cells are nonfunctional blasts that crowd out normal cells"},{"id":"o1","text":"The cells are normal but too numerous"},{"id":"o2","text":"The patient has too many functional neutrophils"},{"id":"o3","text":"The high count reflects a strong immune response"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"leuk_infection_risk_g2","conceptId":"leuk_infection_risk","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> What matters is the count of functional neutrophils (ANC), which can be low even when the total WBC (mostly blasts) is high.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse teaches a leukemia patient about why they remain neutropenic despite a high WBC. Which concept is key?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The absolute neutrophil count of functional cells is low even when total WBC is high"},{"id":"o1","text":"Total WBC is the only measure of immunity"},{"id":"o2","text":"Platelets determine infection risk"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hemoglobin determines infection risk"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"leuk_infection_risk_g3","conceptId":"leuk_infection_risk","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A count dominated by immature blasts means few functional neutrophils and the highest infection risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which patient with leukemia is at greatest infection risk?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"One whose elevated WBC is composed almost entirely of immature blasts"},{"id":"o1","text":"One with a normal differential"},{"id":"o2","text":"One with a mild reactive leukocytosis from a cold"},{"id":"o3","text":"One with mature, functional neutrophils"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"leuk_infection_risk_g4","conceptId":"leuk_infection_risk","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The elevated WBC consists of dysfunctional leukemic cells; it does not confer protection and infection precautions remain essential.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A leukemia patient's family asks how to interpret the high white count. Best nurse response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"The high number is mostly abnormal cells that don't protect against infection.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"The high number means infection is impossible.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It means chemotherapy is no longer needed.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It means the immune system is stronger than normal.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenia_priority_g0","conceptId":"neutropenia_priority","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Infection prevention (hand hygiene, neutropenic precautions) is the priority; raw produce and flowers harbor organisms and are avoided.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A neutropenic AML patient is admitted. Which nursing intervention is the priority?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Strict hand hygiene and neutropenic precautions"},{"id":"o1","text":"Serving fresh raw fruit and salads"},{"id":"o2","text":"Placing fresh flowers in the room"},{"id":"o3","text":"Allowing all visitors regardless of illness"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenia_priority_g1","conceptId":"neutropenia_priority","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Limiting exposure (screening contacts, hand hygiene, private room) is the core of neutropenic precautions.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which action best protects a neutropenic patient from infection?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Screening visitors and staff for illness and enforcing hand hygiene"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encouraging a roommate to share the room"},{"id":"o2","text":"Keeping fresh-cut flowers at the bedside"},{"id":"o3","text":"Allowing undercooked foods"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenia_priority_g2","conceptId":"neutropenia_priority","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Raw produce can carry bacteria; a low-microbial (neutropenic) diet is preferred. The order for raw produce should be questioned.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse plans care for a neutropenic patient. Which order should the nurse question?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A diet including raw vegetables and unpeeled fruit"},{"id":"o1","text":"A private room"},{"id":"o2","text":"Meticulous oral care"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hand hygiene before all contact"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenia_priority_g3","conceptId":"neutropenia_priority","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A private room and removal of flowers/standing water (which harbor organisms) reduce infection risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which environmental measure is appropriate for a hospitalized neutropenic patient?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Private room with no fresh flowers or standing water"},{"id":"o1","text":"Shared room to reduce isolation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fresh flowers to improve mood"},{"id":"o3","text":"Open visitation for all"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenia_priority_g4","conceptId":"neutropenia_priority","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Soil and plants are sources of fungal/bacterial organisms; neutropenic patients should avoid them.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A neutropenic patient wants to garden during a pass. What is the nurse's best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Avoid soil and plants for now, since they carry organisms that can infect you.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Gardening is encouraged for exercise.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Only garden without gloves.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"There is no infection risk while neutropenic.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenic_fever_g0","conceptId":"neutropenic_fever","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Neutropenic fever is an oncologic emergency; obtain cultures and start empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics promptly (typically within 1 hour).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A neutropenic leukemia patient develops a temperature of 100.9 F. Priority action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Treat as an emergency: obtain cultures and prepare broad-spectrum antibiotics"},{"id":"o1","text":"Document and recheck in 4 hours"},{"id":"o2","text":"Give acetaminophen and take no other action"},{"id":"o3","text":"Encourage oral fluids only"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenic_fever_g1","conceptId":"neutropenic_fever","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Without functional neutrophils, infection can become life-threatening quickly; empiric antibiotics are started immediately, not after cultures result.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is even a single fever in a neutropenic patient treated urgently?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"They cannot mount a normal inflammatory response, so infection can progress to sepsis rapidly"},{"id":"o1","text":"Fever is harmless in these patients"},{"id":"o2","text":"It indicates the leukemia is improving"},{"id":"o3","text":"Antibiotics should wait for culture results"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenic_fever_g2","conceptId":"neutropenic_fever","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Draw cultures and rapidly administer empiric antibiotics; delaying for results increases mortality in neutropenic fever.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A neutropenic patient spikes a fever. Which set of actions reflects correct priority sequencing?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Obtain blood cultures, then give empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics promptly"},{"id":"o1","text":"Give antibiotics only after cultures result in 48 hours"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer antipyretics and reassess next shift"},{"id":"o3","text":"Restrict fluids and monitor"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenic_fever_g3","conceptId":"neutropenic_fever","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Neutropenic fever is commonly a single temp >=38.3 C or >=38.0 C sustained ~1 hour, prompting emergent cultures and antibiotics.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which fever threshold typically defines neutropenic fever requiring emergent workup?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A single temperature of 38.3 C (101 F) or 38.0 C (100.4 F) sustained"},{"id":"o1","text":"Only temperatures above 40 C"},{"id":"o2","text":"Any temperature above 37 C"},{"id":"o3","text":"Fever is not defined in neutropenia"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"neutropenic_fever_g4","conceptId":"neutropenic_fever","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever plus hypotension in neutropenia suggests evolving sepsis; immediate cultures, antibiotics, and resuscitation are the priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse receives a neutropenic patient with fever and a BP trending down. What is the priority?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Initiate sepsis evaluation with cultures and rapid empiric antibiotics"},{"id":"o1","text":"Document and continue routine monitoring"},{"id":"o2","text":"Offer oral fluids and recheck in 4 hours"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer acetaminophen alone"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"chemo_monitor_g0","conceptId":"chemo_monitor","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chemo causes myelosuppression; WBC (infection risk) and platelets (bleeding risk) are the priority monitoring values.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An AML patient is receiving chemotherapy. Which labs are the priority to monitor?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"WBC count and platelet count"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hemoglobin and hematocrit only"},{"id":"o2","text":"BUN and creatinine only"},{"id":"o3","text":"Serum electrolytes only"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"chemo_monitor_g1","conceptId":"chemo_monitor","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A declining ANC (nadir) marks the period of greatest infection risk during chemotherapy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which laboratory trend during chemotherapy most directly signals increased infection risk?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A falling absolute neutrophil count"},{"id":"o1","text":"A rising platelet count"},{"id":"o2","text":"A rising albumin"},{"id":"o3","text":"A falling bilirubin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"chemo_monitor_g2","conceptId":"chemo_monitor","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Thrombocytopenia from chemo requires bleeding precautions; the other options increase bleeding risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse reviews chemo labs and notes platelets of 22,000/mm3. Which intervention is appropriate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Institute bleeding precautions"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage contact sports"},{"id":"o2","text":"Give IM injections"},{"id":"o3","text":"Encourage vigorous nose blowing"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"chemo_monitor_g3","conceptId":"chemo_monitor","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Myelosuppression chiefly threatens neutrophils (infection) and platelets (bleeding); these are monitored most closely.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which combination of values should the nurse monitor most closely to detect chemotherapy myelosuppression?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Neutrophils and platelets"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sodium and potassium"},{"id":"o2","text":"Calcium and magnesium"},{"id":"o3","text":"Glucose and A1c"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"chemo_monitor_g4","conceptId":"chemo_monitor","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> An ANC <500/mm3 is severe neutropenia; strict infection precautions and prompt response to fever are required.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A chemotherapy patient's ANC falls to 400/mm3. How should the nurse interpret this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Severe neutropenia with high infection risk requiring precautions"},{"id":"o1","text":"Normal finding needing no action"},{"id":"o2","text":"Improved immune function"},{"id":"o3","text":"An indication to stop all precautions"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"thrombocytopenia_g0","conceptId":"thrombocytopenia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Severe thrombocytopenia requires bleeding precautions; activities and procedures that risk trauma or bleeding are avoided.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A leukemia patient has a platelet count of 16,000/mm3. Which intervention is most appropriate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Bleeding precautions: soft toothbrush, no invasive procedures, no rectal temps"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage contact sports"},{"id":"o2","text":"Give IM injections for comfort"},{"id":"o3","text":"Encourage vigorous nose blowing"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"thrombocytopenia_g1","conceptId":"thrombocytopenia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Petechiae, mucosal bleeding, and headache may signal serious or intracranial bleeding and warrant immediate notification.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment finding in a thrombocytopenic patient requires immediate provider notification?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"New petechiae with bleeding gums and a headache"},{"id":"o1","text":"A single bruise on the shin"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild fatigue"},{"id":"o3","text":"A formed stool"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"thrombocytopenia_g2","conceptId":"thrombocytopenia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Electric razor, soft toothbrush, and avoiding antiplatelet drugs (aspirin/NSAIDs) reduce bleeding risk in thrombocytopenia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse provides teaching to a patient with chemo-induced thrombocytopenia. Which instruction is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Use an electric razor and a soft toothbrush, and avoid aspirin or NSAIDs.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Floss vigorously twice daily.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Take aspirin for aches.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Blow your nose forcefully to keep airways clear.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"thrombocytopenia_g3","conceptId":"thrombocytopenia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> IM injections risk hematoma/bleeding in severe thrombocytopenia and should be questioned; transfusion may be appropriate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which order should the nurse question for a patient with a platelet count of 14,000/mm3?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"An intramuscular injection"},{"id":"o1","text":"A soft mechanical diet"},{"id":"o2","text":"An oral medication"},{"id":"o3","text":"A platelet transfusion"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"thrombocytopenia_g4","conceptId":"thrombocytopenia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Valsalva/straining can provoke bleeding (including rectal/intracranial); softeners prevent straining. Rectal routes are avoided.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A thrombocytopenic patient asks why they must avoid straining with bowel movements. Best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Straining can raise pressure and cause bleeding; we'll use stool softeners to prevent it.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Straining improves your platelet count.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"There is no bleeding concern.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"You should use rectal suppositories instead.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"bmt_immunosuppress_g0","conceptId":"bmt_immunosuppress","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Allogeneic transplant requires immunosuppression to prevent rejection and graft-versus-host disease (GVHD).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient undergoing allogeneic stem cell transplant asks why immunosuppressants are needed afterward. Best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"They help prevent your body from rejecting the donor cells and reduce graft-versus-host disease.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"They prevent infection during recovery.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"They increase red blood cell production.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"They prevent blood clots.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"bmt_immunosuppress_g1","conceptId":"bmt_immunosuppress","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In allogeneic transplant, donor immune cells can attack host tissue (GVHD); immunosuppression reduces this risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which complication is unique to allogeneic (not autologous) transplant and explains the need for immunosuppression?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Graft-versus-host disease"},{"id":"o1","text":"Tumor lysis syndrome"},{"id":"o2","text":"Neutropenia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Anemia"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"bmt_immunosuppress_g2","conceptId":"bmt_immunosuppress","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Immunosuppressants reduce immune activity to prevent rejection/GVHD and are continued as prescribed, not stopped at count recovery.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse teaches a post-allogeneic-transplant patient. Which statement indicates correct understanding of immunosuppression?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"These drugs lower my immune system to keep the donor cells from being rejected.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"These drugs boost my immune system.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"I can stop them once my counts recover.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"They are antibiotics.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"bmt_immunosuppress_g3","conceptId":"bmt_immunosuppress","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The immunosuppression that prevents GVHD/rejection also increases infection risk, so strict precautions are essential.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why are post-allogeneic-transplant patients counseled on strict infection precautions?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Immunosuppression to prevent GVHD also raises infection susceptibility"},{"id":"o1","text":"They no longer need precautions"},{"id":"o2","text":"Their immunity is stronger than normal"},{"id":"o3","text":"Antibiotics make precautions unnecessary"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"bmt_immunosuppress_g4","conceptId":"bmt_immunosuppress","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> GVHD classically affects skin (rash), gut (diarrhea), and liver (rising enzymes); these warrant prompt evaluation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding in a post-allogeneic-transplant patient suggests graft-versus-host disease?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Skin rash, diarrhea, and rising liver enzymes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Isolated mild ankle edema"},{"id":"o2","text":"A single episode of constipation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Stable counts with no symptoms"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_cd4_g0","conceptId":"hiv_cd4","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A CD4 <200 defines AIDS and indicates high opportunistic-infection risk; ART is never paused and the patient remains infectious.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with HIV has a CD4 count of 180 cells/mm3 with new fever and cough. Which conclusion is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The patient has progressed to AIDS and is at high risk for opportunistic infections"},{"id":"o1","text":"The CD4 is normal and the cough is unrelated"},{"id":"o2","text":"HIV is well controlled and ART can be paused"},{"id":"o3","text":"The low CD4 means the patient is no longer contagious"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_cd4_g1","conceptId":"hiv_cd4","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A CD4 count <200 cells/mm3 (or an AIDS-defining illness) establishes AIDS, with high opportunistic infection risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>At what CD4 threshold is a patient with HIV considered to have AIDS, with markedly increased opportunistic infection risk?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Below 200 cells/mm3"},{"id":"o1","text":"Below 800 cells/mm3"},{"id":"o2","text":"Below 1500 cells/mm3"},{"id":"o3","text":"Below 1000 cells/mm3"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_cd4_g2","conceptId":"hiv_cd4","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> At CD4 <200, PCP prophylaxis (e.g., trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole) is indicated due to high risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse interprets a CD4 of 150 cells/mm3 in an HIV patient. Which prophylaxis is commonly indicated at this level?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Prophylaxis against Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia"},{"id":"o1","text":"No prophylaxis is needed"},{"id":"o2","text":"Discontinuation of ART"},{"id":"o3","text":"Prophylactic anticoagulation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_cd4_g3","conceptId":"hiv_cd4","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> CD4 cells are central to cell-mediated immunity; the lower the count, the greater the opportunistic infection risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement about CD4 count and infection risk in HIV is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A lower CD4 count means greater susceptibility to opportunistic infections"},{"id":"o1","text":"A lower CD4 count means lower infection risk"},{"id":"o2","text":"CD4 count does not relate to immunity"},{"id":"o3","text":"A CD4 of 150 indicates strong immunity"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_cd4_g4","conceptId":"hiv_cd4","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A falling CD4 indicates progression and higher infection risk; adherence and regimen should be reassessed, not ART stopped.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An HIV patient's CD4 has dropped from 350 to 160 cells/mm3. How should the nurse interpret this trend?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Disease progression with increased opportunistic infection risk; reassess ART adherence"},{"id":"o1","text":"Improvement in immune function"},{"id":"o2","text":"No clinical significance"},{"id":"o3","text":"A reason to stop ART"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_pcp_g0","conceptId":"hiv_pcp","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, dry cough, and hypoxemia in advanced HIV strongly suggest PCP, the classic AIDS-defining pulmonary infection.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with advanced HIV has fever, nonproductive cough, and SpO2 88%. Which opportunistic infection should the nurse suspect first?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP)"},{"id":"o1","text":"CMV retinitis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Oral candidiasis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Cryptococcal meningitis"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_pcp_g1","conceptId":"hiv_pcp","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PCP typically causes insidious dyspnea, nonproductive cough, and hypoxemia disproportionate to exam findings.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which presentation in an AIDS patient is most consistent with Pneumocystis pneumonia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Gradual dyspnea, dry cough, and marked hypoxemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sudden vision loss"},{"id":"o2","text":"Headache with neck stiffness"},{"id":"o3","text":"White oral plaques only"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_pcp_g2","conceptId":"hiv_pcp","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> First-line PCP treatment/prophylaxis is trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (TMP-SMX).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse anticipates which treatment for suspected PCP in an AIDS patient?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole"},{"id":"o1","text":"Insulin"},{"id":"o2","text":"Warfarin"},{"id":"o3","text":"A loop diuretic"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_pcp_g3","conceptId":"hiv_pcp","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PCP characteristically causes diffuse infiltrates, a dry cough, and hypoxemia often out of proportion to findings, unlike classic lobar bacterial pneumonia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment finding most strongly differentiates PCP from typical bacterial pneumonia in an AIDS patient?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Profound hypoxemia with a relatively nonproductive cough and diffuse infiltrates"},{"id":"o1","text":"Lobar consolidation with purulent sputum"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sudden unilateral chest pain"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sawtooth ECG pattern"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"hiv_pcp_g4","conceptId":"hiv_pcp","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hypoxemia requires immediate oxygen and prompt provider notification; empiric PCP therapy is often started without waiting for confirmation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An AIDS patient with suspected PCP is hypoxemic. Which nursing action is the priority?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Apply oxygen and notify the provider for urgent evaluation and treatment"},{"id":"o1","text":"Encourage ambulation in the hall"},{"id":"o2","text":"Withhold oxygen to avoid CO2 retention"},{"id":"o3","text":"Delay treatment until sputum cultures finalize"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"art_adherence_g0","conceptId":"art_adherence","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Strict daily adherence maintains viral suppression and prevents resistance; ART is lifelong and is not a cure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient newly started on antiretroviral therapy asks about taking it. Which teaching is most important?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Take it consistently every day; missing doses can lead to drug resistance.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Stop once you feel better to avoid side effects.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It cures HIV in a few weeks.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Take it only when you have symptoms.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"art_adherence_g1","conceptId":"art_adherence","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Subtherapeutic levels from missed doses allow resistant strains to emerge, risking treatment failure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is consistent ART adherence emphasized for HIV patients?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Inconsistent dosing promotes viral resistance and treatment failure"},{"id":"o1","text":"Skipping doses improves long-term outcomes"},{"id":"o2","text":"Adherence only matters during symptoms"},{"id":"o3","text":"ART cures HIV, so adherence is optional after suppression"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"art_adherence_g2","conceptId":"art_adherence","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Viral suppression depends on continuous therapy; stopping leads to rebound and resistance. ART is continued lifelong.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient on ART reports feeling well and wants to stop the medication. Best nurse response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Feeling well means it's working; stopping it allows the virus to rebound and become resistant.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"You may stop now that you feel well.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Stop and restart only when symptoms return.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Take a drug holiday every few weeks.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"art_adherence_g3","conceptId":"art_adherence","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Effective ART suppresses viral load to undetectable and supports CD4 recovery.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which goal best reflects effective ART?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"An undetectable viral load with a rising CD4 count"},{"id":"o1","text":"A rising viral load"},{"id":"o2","text":"A falling CD4 count"},{"id":"o3","text":"Symptom-triggered dosing"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"art_adherence_g4","conceptId":"art_adherence","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Undetectable = untransmittable sexually (U=U) only with sustained suppression, which requires continued ART; it is not a cure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse counsels an HIV patient about an undetectable viral load. Which statement is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"An undetectable viral load greatly reduces transmission risk, but keep taking ART and using precautions.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"Undetectable means you are cured.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"You can stop ART once undetectable.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Undetectable means you can never transmit under any circumstance, so ART can stop.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"leuk_report_g0","conceptId":"leuk_report","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, bleeding/bruising, respiratory symptoms, and worsening anemia symptoms warrant immediate reporting. A minor cut that has stopped bleeding does not.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse teaches a leukemia patient which symptoms to report immediately. Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fever of 100.4 F (38 C) or higher"},{"id":"o1","text":"New bleeding gums or easy bruising"},{"id":"o2","text":"Shortness of breath or persistent cough"},{"id":"o3","text":"Worsening fatigue with pallor"},{"id":"o4","text":"A small papercut that has already stopped bleeding"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"leuk_report_g1","conceptId":"leuk_report","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, chills, new respiratory symptoms, and dysuria can signal infection in a neutropenic patient and must be reported. A healed bruise does not.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which findings should a patient with chemotherapy-induced neutropenia report immediately? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Temperature 100.5 F"},{"id":"o1","text":"Chills or rigors"},{"id":"o2","text":"A new productive cough"},{"id":"o3","text":"Burning with urination"},{"id":"o4","text":"A healed bruise from last week"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"leuk_report_g2","conceptId":"leuk_report","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hematuria, epistaxis, petechiae, and gum bleeding indicate bleeding risk from thrombocytopenia. A freckle is not a bleeding sign.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A leukemia patient on chemotherapy should report which signs of bleeding? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Blood in urine or stool"},{"id":"o1","text":"Nosebleeds that won't stop"},{"id":"o2","text":"New petechiae"},{"id":"o3","text":"Bleeding gums"},{"id":"o4","text":"A single freckle noticed today"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"leuk_report_g3","conceptId":"leuk_report","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever/chills, oral lesions, localized infection signs, and respiratory symptoms suggest infection. A minor resolving itch does not.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which symptoms indicate possible infection that a neutropenic patient must report? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Fever or chills"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sore throat or mouth sores"},{"id":"o2","text":"Redness or drainage at any site"},{"id":"o3","text":"New cough or shortness of breath"},{"id":"o4","text":"Mild seasonal itch that resolves with lotion"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"leuk_report_g4","conceptId":"leuk_report","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fever, uncontrolled bleeding, neuro changes, and dyspnea are urgent. A routine future appointment is not a warning sign.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse reviews warning signs with a leukemia patient. Which require urgent reporting? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Temperature >= 100.4 F"},{"id":"o1","text":"Uncontrolled bleeding"},{"id":"o2","text":"Severe headache or confusion"},{"id":"o3","text":"Shortness of breath"},{"id":"o4","text":"A scheduled clinic appointment next week"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"match_leukemia_g0","conceptId":"match_leukemia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> ALL = pediatric, acute; AML = adult, acute; CLL = older adults, indolent; CML = Philadelphia chromosome, TKI-treated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each leukemia type with its characteristic feature or population.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"ALL (acute lymphocytic leukemia)"},{"id":"l1","text":"AML (acute myeloid leukemia)"},{"id":"l2","text":"CLL (chronic lymphocytic leukemia)"},{"id":"l3","text":"CML (chronic myeloid leukemia)"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Most common in children; rapid onset"},{"id":"r1","text":"Common in adults; rapid onset, poor prognosis if untreated"},{"id":"r2","text":"Slow onset in older adults; often asymptomatic"},{"id":"r3","text":"Philadelphia chromosome; treated with tyrosine-kinase inhibitors"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_leukemia_g1","conceptId":"match_leukemia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Onset/age mapping: ALL acute/children; AML acute/adults; CLL chronic/older adults; CML chronic/adults with BCR-ABL (Philadelphia chromosome).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each leukemia to its typical onset and age group.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"ALL"},{"id":"l1","text":"AML"},{"id":"l2","text":"CLL"},{"id":"l3","text":"CML"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Acute; peak incidence in young children"},{"id":"r1","text":"Acute; primarily adults"},{"id":"r2","text":"Chronic; older adults, frequently incidental"},{"id":"r3","text":"Chronic; adults, associated with BCR-ABL"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_leukemia_g2","conceptId":"match_leukemia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> ALL = CNS prophylaxis; AML = Auer rods; CLL = smudge cells; CML = TKI therapy targeting BCR-ABL.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each leukemia with a key clinical or treatment association.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"ALL"},{"id":"l1","text":"AML"},{"id":"l2","text":"CLL"},{"id":"l3","text":"CML"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"CNS prophylaxis often part of therapy"},{"id":"r1","text":"Auer rods on blood smear"},{"id":"r2","text":"Smudge cells on peripheral smear"},{"id":"r3","text":"Tyrosine-kinase inhibitor therapy (e.g., imatinib)"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_leukemia_g3","conceptId":"match_leukemia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Descriptions map to ALL, AML, CLL, and CML respectively based on lineage, acuity, and cytogenetics.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each description to the correct leukemia.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Rapidly progressive lymphoblast proliferation in a child"},{"id":"l1","text":"Rapidly progressive myeloblast proliferation with Auer rods"},{"id":"l2","text":"Indolent mature lymphocyte accumulation in an elder"},{"id":"l3","text":"Philadelphia-chromosome myeloproliferation"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"ALL"},{"id":"r1","text":"AML"},{"id":"r2","text":"CLL"},{"id":"r3","text":"CML"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_leukemia_g4","conceptId":"match_leukemia","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hallmarks: ALL childhood lymphoid; AML Auer rods; CLL smudge cells; CML BCR-ABL.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each leukemia to its hallmark.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"ALL"},{"id":"l1","text":"AML"},{"id":"l2","text":"CLL"},{"id":"l3","text":"CML"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Childhood acute lymphoid; good response to chemo"},{"id":"r1","text":"Adult acute myeloid; Auer rods"},{"id":"r2","text":"Older-adult chronic lymphoid; smudge cells"},{"id":"r3","text":"Chronic myeloid; BCR-ABL/Philadelphia chromosome"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_hiv_oi_g0","conceptId":"match_hiv_oi","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> PCP = hypoxemic dry cough; CMV = retinitis/vision change; cryptococcus = meningitis; candida = oral thrush.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each HIV-related opportunistic infection to its primary clinical feature.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP)"},{"id":"l1","text":"CMV retinitis"},{"id":"l2","text":"Cryptococcal meningitis"},{"id":"l3","text":"Oral candidiasis (thrush)"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Fever, nonproductive cough, dyspnea/hypoxemia"},{"id":"r1","text":"Painless vision changes/loss"},{"id":"r2","text":"Headache, fever, altered mental status"},{"id":"r3","text":"White plaques in the mouth"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_hiv_oi_g1","conceptId":"match_hiv_oi","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hallmarks map PCP to lung, CMV to eye, cryptococcus to meninges, candida to oropharynx.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each opportunistic infection in advanced HIV to its hallmark.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"PCP"},{"id":"l1","text":"CMV"},{"id":"l2","text":"Cryptococcus neoformans"},{"id":"l3","text":"Candida albicans"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Diffuse infiltrates with hypoxemia"},{"id":"r1","text":"Retinal changes and vision loss"},{"id":"r2","text":"Meningeal signs and increased intracranial pressure"},{"id":"r3","text":"Oropharyngeal white patches"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_hiv_oi_g2","conceptId":"match_hiv_oi","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Findings localize to lung (PCP), eye (CMV), CNS (cryptococcus), and oropharynx/esophagus (candida).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match the assessment finding to the likely opportunistic infection in AIDS.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"SpO2 86% with dry cough"},{"id":"l1","text":"Floaters and decreasing visual acuity"},{"id":"l2","text":"Severe headache, photophobia, confusion"},{"id":"l3","text":"Difficulty swallowing with white oral plaques"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"PCP"},{"id":"r1","text":"CMV retinitis"},{"id":"r2","text":"Cryptococcal meningitis"},{"id":"r3","text":"Esophageal/oral candidiasis"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_hiv_oi_g3","conceptId":"match_hiv_oi","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> TMP-SMX targets PCP; ganciclovir targets CMV; amphotericin/flucytosine treat cryptococcus; azoles/nystatin treat candida.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each prophylaxis or treatment to its target opportunistic infection.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"TMP-SMX"},{"id":"l1","text":"Ganciclovir/valganciclovir"},{"id":"l2","text":"Amphotericin B plus flucytosine"},{"id":"l3","text":"Fluconazole/nystatin"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"PCP"},{"id":"r1","text":"CMV"},{"id":"r2","text":"Cryptococcal meningitis"},{"id":"r3","text":"Candidiasis"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_hiv_oi_g4","conceptId":"match_hiv_oi","domain":"Hematologic","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Lower CD4 thresholds correspond to PCP (<200), CMV/cryptococcus (<50-100), with candidiasis common across low CD4 levels.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match the CD4-associated risk to the opportunistic infection.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"CD4 < 200: dry cough and hypoxemia"},{"id":"l1","text":"CD4 < 50: vision changes"},{"id":"l2","text":"CD4 < 100: meningitis"},{"id":"l3","text":"Any low CD4: oral white plaques"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"PCP"},{"id":"r1","text":"CMV retinitis"},{"id":"r2","text":"Cryptococcal meningitis"},{"id":"r3","text":"Candidiasis"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"dmards_g0","conceptId":"dmards","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> DMARDs (e.g., methotrexate) modify the disease course and prevent joint destruction; NSAIDs/steroids relieve symptoms but don't halt progression.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which medication class is prescribed specifically to slow rheumatoid arthritis progression and prevent joint destruction?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs)"},{"id":"o1","text":"NSAIDs"},{"id":"o2","text":"Corticosteroids"},{"id":"o3","text":"Opioid analgesics"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"dmards_g1","conceptId":"dmards","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> DMARDs are the disease-altering agents; other listed drugs are symptomatic only.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with RA asks which of their medications actually changes the course of the disease. Best response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"The DMARD, such as methotrexate, slows the disease and protects your joints.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"The NSAID changes the disease course.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"The opioid prevents joint damage.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"None of your medications affect the disease.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"dmards_g2","conceptId":"dmards","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Early DMARD initiation limits joint damage; they have a delayed onset (weeks) and modify disease rather than just relieving pain.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement about DMARD therapy in RA is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"DMARDs are started early to limit irreversible joint damage"},{"id":"o1","text":"DMARDs are reserved for end-stage disease only"},{"id":"o2","text":"DMARDs work immediately within hours"},{"id":"o3","text":"DMARDs only relieve pain without altering disease"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"dmards_g3","conceptId":"dmards","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> NSAIDs are symptomatic; DMARDs are required to slow progression and prevent joint destruction.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse explains why NSAIDs alone are insufficient for RA management. Which rationale is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"NSAIDs reduce inflammation/pain but don't prevent joint destruction; DMARDs are needed"},{"id":"o1","text":"NSAIDs cure RA"},{"id":"o2","text":"NSAIDs replace DMARDs"},{"id":"o3","text":"NSAIDs slow disease progression better than DMARDs"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"dmards_g4","conceptId":"dmards","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Methotrexate is a common first-line DMARD; the others are symptomatic analgesics/anti-inflammatories.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which is an example of a DMARD used as first-line therapy in RA?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Methotrexate"},{"id":"o1","text":"Ibuprofen"},{"id":"o2","text":"Morphine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Acetaminophen"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"mtx_teach_g0","conceptId":"mtx_teach","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Early DMARD therapy limits irreversible joint destruction; this is the key teaching to address the refusal.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An RA patient refuses methotrexate, saying their arthritis 'isn't that bad yet.' Which information is most important?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Starting methotrexate early helps decrease the extent of permanent joint damage.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"It is cheaper than newer drugs.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It takes 4-6 weeks to work.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It has fewer side effects than other drugs.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"mtx_teach_g1","conceptId":"mtx_teach","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Emphasizing joint protection plus monitoring addresses the concern while reinforcing the value of early therapy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient newly prescribed methotrexate for RA expresses fear of side effects. Which response best supports adherence?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Early treatment protects your joints from permanent damage; we'll monitor labs to manage side effects.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"You can wait until your joints are badly damaged.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"Side effects are guaranteed and untreatable.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"Methotrexate cures RA in a week.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"mtx_teach_g2","conceptId":"mtx_teach","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Methotrexate is dosed weekly, folic acid mitigates side effects, alcohol is avoided (hepatotoxicity), and it is teratogenic/contraindicated in pregnancy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which teaching point about methotrexate for RA is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Folic acid is often prescribed to reduce side effects, and alcohol should be avoided"},{"id":"o1","text":"Methotrexate should be taken daily in high doses"},{"id":"o2","text":"Alcohol intake is unrestricted"},{"id":"o3","text":"Pregnancy is safe on methotrexate"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"mtx_teach_g3","conceptId":"mtx_teach","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Methotrexate can cause myelosuppression and mucositis; infection, stomatitis, or bruising should be reported promptly.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient on methotrexate should be taught to report which symptom promptly?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Signs of infection, mouth sores, or unusual bruising"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild improvement in joint pain"},{"id":"o2","text":"Normal weekly dosing"},{"id":"o3","text":"Taking prescribed folic acid"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"mtx_teach_g4","conceptId":"mtx_teach","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> RA methotrexate is a weekly low-dose regimen; accidental daily dosing causes serious toxicity (a known fatal error).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is methotrexate for RA dosed weekly rather than daily?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Daily dosing markedly increases toxicity; weekly dosing provides efficacy with lower risk"},{"id":"o1","text":"Weekly dosing is less effective but cheaper"},{"id":"o2","text":"Daily dosing is the standard for RA"},{"id":"o3","text":"Dosing frequency does not affect toxicity"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ra_septic_joint_g0","conceptId":"ra_septic_joint","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A single acutely hot, red, swollen joint (especially with fever) suggests septic arthritis, a joint emergency requiring immediate evaluation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse assesses a patient with RA. Which finding is most concerning and requires immediate intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A single hot, red, swollen knee with limited range of motion and fever"},{"id":"o1","text":"Symmetric morning stiffness in the hands"},{"id":"o2","text":"Low-grade fatigue"},{"id":"o3","text":"Symmetric joint pain that eases with movement"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ra_septic_joint_g1","conceptId":"ra_septic_joint","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Septic arthritis typically presents as an acutely inflamed single joint with fever; immunosuppressed RA patients are at higher risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which presentation in an RA patient should prompt urgent evaluation for septic arthritis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Acute monoarticular swelling, warmth, and severe pain with fever"},{"id":"o1","text":"Bilateral symmetric stiffness"},{"id":"o2","text":"Chronic nodules over the elbows"},{"id":"o3","text":"Gradual fatigue"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ra_septic_joint_g2","conceptId":"ra_septic_joint","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> This may be septic arthritis; urgent notification and arthrocentesis (aspiration for culture) are needed. Delay risks joint destruction/sepsis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An RA patient on immunosuppressants reports one knee that is suddenly hot, swollen, and exquisitely painful. Priority action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Notify the provider urgently and anticipate joint aspiration"},{"id":"o1","text":"Apply heat and reassess next shift"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage range-of-motion exercises of that knee"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer a scheduled DMARD and continue monitoring"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ra_septic_joint_g3","conceptId":"ra_septic_joint","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Damaged joints and immunosuppression (from DMARDs/steroids) raise septic arthritis risk in RA patients.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why are RA patients at increased risk for septic arthritis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Chronic joint damage plus immunosuppressive therapy increases infection susceptibility"},{"id":"o1","text":"RA protects joints from infection"},{"id":"o2","text":"DMARDs eliminate infection risk"},{"id":"o3","text":"Septic arthritis cannot occur in RA"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ra_septic_joint_g4","conceptId":"ra_septic_joint","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Monoarticular acute inflammation with fever/systemic signs points to infection rather than the symmetric pattern of an RA flare.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding best distinguishes a likely septic joint from a typical RA flare?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A single acutely inflamed joint with fever and systemic signs"},{"id":"o1","text":"Symmetric small-joint involvement"},{"id":"o2","text":"Morning stiffness lasting an hour"},{"id":"o3","text":"Improvement with usual RA medications"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ana_g0","conceptId":"ana","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> ANA is sensitive but not specific; a positive result supports but does not confirm SLE, and can occur in other conditions and healthy people.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with suspected SLE has a positive ANA and asks what it means. Most accurate response?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"It supports the diagnosis but isn't specific to lupus; other tests are needed to confirm.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"It confirms you definitely have lupus.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"It measures kidney function.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"It means your lupus is in remission.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ana_g1","conceptId":"ana","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> ANA is a sensitive screening test; specificity is low, so confirmation requires additional, more specific antibodies (e.g., anti-dsDNA, anti-Smith).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement about the ANA test is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A positive ANA is sensitive for SLE but can be positive in other autoimmune conditions and some healthy people"},{"id":"o1","text":"A positive ANA is specific and confirms SLE"},{"id":"o2","text":"A negative ANA confirms SLE"},{"id":"o3","text":"ANA measures disease activity directly"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ana_g2","conceptId":"ana","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Anti-dsDNA and anti-Smith antibodies are highly specific for SLE and help confirm the diagnosis after a positive ANA.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse explains follow-up testing after a positive ANA in suspected lupus. Which tests are more specific for SLE?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Anti-double-stranded DNA and anti-Smith antibodies"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hemoglobin and hematocrit"},{"id":"o2","text":"Basic metabolic panel"},{"id":"o3","text":"Lipid panel"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ana_g3","conceptId":"ana","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Because ANA lacks specificity, diagnosis integrates clinical criteria and more specific antibodies, not the ANA alone.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which patient teaching about a positive ANA is appropriate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"\"Many people with a positive ANA do not have lupus; we'll use your symptoms and other labs to diagnose.\""},{"id":"o1","text":"\"A positive ANA always means lupus.\""},{"id":"o2","text":"\"You can ignore the result entirely.\""},{"id":"o3","text":"\"A positive ANA rules out all other autoimmune disease.\""}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"ana_g4","conceptId":"ana","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Anti-dsDNA is specific for SLE and rising titers can correlate with activity, particularly lupus nephritis.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Anti-dsDNA antibodies in a patient with SLE are useful because they:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Are specific for SLE and may correlate with disease activity, especially nephritis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Rule out SLE when positive"},{"id":"o2","text":"Measure liver function"},{"id":"o3","text":"Are nonspecific like ANA"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lupus_nephritis_g0","conceptId":"lupus_nephritis","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> New edema in SLE suggests renal involvement (lupus nephritis) with proteinuria; it is a major cause of morbidity and warrants evaluation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An SLE patient presents with joint pain, fatigue, and new bilateral leg edema. Which complication is the nurse most concerned about?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Lupus nephritis"},{"id":"o1","text":"Osteoarthritis"},{"id":"o2","text":"Deep vein thrombosis"},{"id":"o3","text":"Peripheral neuropathy"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lupus_nephritis_g1","conceptId":"lupus_nephritis","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Lupus nephritis presents with edema, hypertension, proteinuria, and declining renal function.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment findings in an SLE patient suggest lupus nephritis?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"New edema, hypertension, proteinuria, and rising creatinine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Improved energy and weight loss"},{"id":"o2","text":"Isolated dry cough"},{"id":"o3","text":"Unilateral calf pain only"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lupus_nephritis_g2","conceptId":"lupus_nephritis","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Proteinuria and creatinine track renal involvement (lupus nephritis), the priority complication to detect early.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse monitors an SLE patient for renal involvement. Which laboratory/finding is the priority to track?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Urine protein and serum creatinine"},{"id":"o1","text":"Serum amylase"},{"id":"o2","text":"Visual acuity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Bone density"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lupus_nephritis_g3","conceptId":"lupus_nephritis","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Lupus nephritis can lead to irreversible kidney damage; early detection and immunosuppressive treatment preserve renal function.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is early detection of lupus nephritis important?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Untreated nephritis can progress to chronic kidney disease or renal failure"},{"id":"o1","text":"It resolves without treatment"},{"id":"o2","text":"It only affects the joints"},{"id":"o3","text":"It is unrelated to lupus activity"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"lupus_nephritis_g4","conceptId":"lupus_nephritis","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> New proteinuria with rising creatinine signals possible lupus nephritis; prompt provider notification and workup are the priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An SLE patient's labs show new proteinuria and a rising creatinine. Which action is the priority?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Notify the provider and anticipate further renal workup and treatment"},{"id":"o1","text":"Reassure the patient that this is expected and no action is needed"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage a high-sodium diet"},{"id":"o3","text":"Withhold all fluids"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crp_prednisone_g0","conceptId":"crp_prednisone","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> CRP is an inflammatory marker; a falling CRP indicates the anti-inflammatory effect of prednisone is working.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which laboratory result would the nurse monitor to determine whether prednisone is effective for an acute RA exacerbation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"C-reactive protein (CRP)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Blood glucose"},{"id":"o2","text":"Serum sodium"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hemoglobin A1c"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crp_prednisone_g1","conceptId":"crp_prednisone","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Declining inflammatory markers (CRP, ESR) reflect reduced inflammation from effective steroid therapy. Rising glucose is a side effect, not an efficacy measure.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse evaluates the effectiveness of corticosteroid therapy for inflammation. Which trend indicates improvement?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Decreasing CRP and ESR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Increasing CRP and ESR"},{"id":"o2","text":"Rising blood glucose"},{"id":"o3","text":"Falling hemoglobin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crp_prednisone_g2","conceptId":"crp_prednisone","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Corticosteroids commonly raise blood glucose; this is monitored as a side effect, distinct from CRP used to gauge efficacy.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which laboratory value should the nurse also monitor as a side effect of prednisone therapy?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Blood glucose, which can rise with corticosteroids"},{"id":"o1","text":"CRP, which measures the side effect"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hemoglobin, which steroids lower"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sodium, which steroids deplete"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crp_prednisone_g3","conceptId":"crp_prednisone","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Inflammatory markers (CRP/ESR) gauge therapeutic effect; glucose monitors a key steroid side effect.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with an RA flare is on prednisone. Which combination best reflects monitoring efficacy AND safety?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"CRP/ESR for efficacy and blood glucose for safety"},{"id":"o1","text":"Glucose for efficacy and CRP for safety"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sodium for both"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hemoglobin for both"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"crp_prednisone_g4","conceptId":"crp_prednisone","domain":"Autoimmune","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A substantial fall in CRP indicates reduced inflammation and an effective therapeutic response to prednisone.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>After several days of prednisone for an RA flare, the patient's CRP has dropped substantially. How should the nurse interpret this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The anti-inflammatory therapy is working"},{"id":"o1","text":"The therapy is failing"},{"id":"o2","text":"The patient has a new infection"},{"id":"o3","text":"The steroid dose must be increased"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"post_op_shock_g0","conceptId":"post_op_shock","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Tachycardia, hypotension, poor perfusion, and oliguria indicate shock (likely hemorrhage post-op); prompt notification and resuscitation are the priority.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A post-op patient has HR 122, BP 86/52, cool clammy skin, and urine output 15 mL over 2 hours. Which is the priority nursing action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Notify the provider and begin fluid resuscitation for likely hypovolemic/hemorrhagic shock"},{"id":"o1","text":"Document and reassess in 1 hour"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage the patient to ambulate"},{"id":"o3","text":"Administer the scheduled opioid"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"post_op_shock_g1","conceptId":"post_op_shock","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Progressive tachycardia, hypotension, and oliguria reflect decompensating hypovolemic shock requiring urgent action.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which assessment trend in a post-op patient most strongly indicates evolving hypovolemic shock?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rising heart rate with falling blood pressure and decreasing urine output"},{"id":"o1","text":"Stable vitals with good urine output"},{"id":"o2","text":"Bradycardia with hypertension"},{"id":"o3","text":"Warm, well-perfused skin with normal output"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"post_op_shock_g2","conceptId":"post_op_shock","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Active external hemorrhage with shock vitals requires immediate direct pressure and escalation while resuscitation begins.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A post-op patient's dressing is saturated with blood and vitals show HR 128, BP 84/50. What is the nurse's first action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Apply direct pressure to the site and notify the provider/rapid response"},{"id":"o1","text":"Change the dressing and document"},{"id":"o2","text":"Offer oral fluids and recheck later"},{"id":"o3","text":"Ambulate the patient to assess tolerance"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"post_op_shock_g3","conceptId":"post_op_shock","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hypotension refractory to fluids with rising lactate and altered mentation signals decompensated shock requiring rapid escalation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding indicates a post-op patient is decompensating and needs rapid escalation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Worsening hypotension despite fluids, with rising lactate and confusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild incisional pain relieved by analgesics"},{"id":"o2","text":"Stable vitals and clear mentation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Normal urine output"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"post_op_shock_g4","conceptId":"post_op_shock","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Early compensated shock shows tachycardia and narrowing pulse pressure before systolic BP falls; recognizing it allows early intervention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse recognizes early (compensated) shock in a post-op patient by which finding?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Tachycardia and narrowing pulse pressure with a still-normal systolic BP"},{"id":"o1","text":"Bradycardia and hypertension"},{"id":"o2","text":"Flushed, warm skin with bounding pulses"},{"id":"o3","text":"Increased urine output"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"gi_bleed_escalate_g0","conceptId":"gi_bleed_escalate","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Continued hypotension despite resuscitation is the clearest evidence of ongoing hemorrhage/decompensation requiring immediate escalation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a GI bleed has received 1 L crystalloid. Which finding most clearly indicates the need for immediate escalation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A repeat BP that keeps falling (e.g., 88/52 to 80/48) despite resuscitation"},{"id":"o1","text":"An isolated heart rate of 100/min"},{"id":"o2","text":"Capillary refill of 3 seconds"},{"id":"o3","text":"One episode of dark stool"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"gi_bleed_escalate_g1","conceptId":"gi_bleed_escalate","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Persistent hypotension/tachycardia after adequate fluids indicates ongoing bleeding and the need to escalate (blood products, endoscopy, surgery).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which trend in a GI-bleed patient indicates failure to respond to initial resuscitation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Persistent or worsening hypotension and tachycardia after fluids"},{"id":"o1","text":"Improving blood pressure and slowing heart rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"Increasing urine output"},{"id":"o3","text":"Resolving lightheadedness"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"gi_bleed_escalate_g2","conceptId":"gi_bleed_escalate","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Decompensation with altered mentation and refractory shock requires immediate transfusion and urgent definitive intervention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with upper GI bleeding develops new confusion, BP 82/46, and HR 130 after fluids. Priority action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Activate rapid escalation: transfuse, notify GI/surgery, prepare for urgent endoscopy"},{"id":"o1","text":"Document and recheck in 30 minutes"},{"id":"o2","text":"Provide a meal to maintain strength"},{"id":"o3","text":"Encourage ambulation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"gi_bleed_escalate_g3","conceptId":"gi_bleed_escalate","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Serial BP trending down despite treatment confirms decompensation; single or stale values can mislead during active bleeding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which parameter best confirms a GI-bleed patient is decompensating rather than stabilizing?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A downward blood pressure trend across serial readings despite treatment"},{"id":"o1","text":"A single normal blood pressure reading"},{"id":"o2","text":"A stable hemoglobin from hours ago"},{"id":"o3","text":"Subjective report of feeling better"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"gi_bleed_escalate_g4","conceptId":"gi_bleed_escalate","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Rising lactate with oliguria signals worsening hypoperfusion from ongoing hemorrhage, requiring blood products and escalation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A GI-bleed patient's lactate is rising and urine output is falling despite fluids. How should the nurse interpret this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Worsening hypoperfusion indicating the need for blood products and escalation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Adequate resuscitation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Improving perfusion"},{"id":"o3","text":"No clinical significance"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"rrt_criteria_g0","conceptId":"rrt_criteria","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acute hemodynamic deterioration with new altered mentation meets RRT activation criteria for early intervention before arrest.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which change in a ward patient most clearly meets criteria to activate the rapid response team?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Acute drop in BP with rising heart rate and new altered mental status"},{"id":"o1","text":"Mild incisional pain"},{"id":"o2","text":"A single blood pressure at baseline"},{"id":"o3","text":"Stable vitals with normal mentation"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"rrt_criteria_g1","conceptId":"rrt_criteria","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Acute respiratory deterioration (hypoxia despite oxygen, tachypnea) warrants rapid response activation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse notes a patient's SpO2 has dropped to 86% on increasing oxygen with RR 30. What is the appropriate action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Activate the rapid response team"},{"id":"o1","text":"Wait for the next routine assessment"},{"id":"o2","text":"Discontinue oxygen"},{"id":"o3","text":"Document and reassess in 2 hours"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"rrt_criteria_g2","conceptId":"rrt_criteria","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Clustered acute deterioration (shock signs plus altered mentation) signals a deteriorating patient needing rapid response.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which set of findings should prompt rapid response activation rather than routine monitoring?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"New tachycardia, hypotension, decreased urine output, and confusion"},{"id":"o1","text":"Stable vitals and clear mentation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild fatigue relieved by rest"},{"id":"o3","text":"A healed surgical incision"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"rrt_criteria_g3","conceptId":"rrt_criteria","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> RRTs exist to intervene early in deterioration, reducing progression to arrest and improving survival.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is early rapid response activation emphasized for a deteriorating patient?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Early intervention can prevent progression to cardiac arrest and improve outcomes"},{"id":"o1","text":"It delays definitive care"},{"id":"o2","text":"It is only used after arrest"},{"id":"o3","text":"It replaces provider notification permanently"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"rrt_criteria_g4","conceptId":"rrt_criteria","domain":"Clinical Judgment","section":"S2","verified":false,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Nurse concern ('failure to rescue' prevention) is a valid RRT trigger; subtle deterioration plus restlessness warrants early escalation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse is unsure but senses a patient is 'not right,' with subtle vital changes and new restlessness. Best action?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Trust the clinical concern and activate rapid response/escalate"},{"id":"o1","text":"Wait until vitals clearly meet thresholds"},{"id":"o2","text":"Ignore the subjective impression"},{"id":"o3","text":"Delay until the next shift"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"normal_intervals_g0","conceptId":"normal_intervals","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A normal QRS is <0.12 seconds; 0.16 s is widened and warrants investigation (e.g., bundle branch block, ventricular origin). The PR (0.12-0.20), RR (rate ~60), and QT (0.36-0.44) values shown are normal.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which ECG finding requires further investigation by the nurse?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"QRS interval of 0.16 second"},{"id":"o1","text":"PR interval of 0.16 second"},{"id":"o2","text":"RR interval of 1 second"},{"id":"o3","text":"QT interval of 0.38 second"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"normal_intervals_g1","conceptId":"normal_intervals","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A normal PR interval is 0.12-0.20 seconds; 0.26 s is prolonged (first-degree AV block). The QRS (0.08) and PR (0.16) values are normal.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which interval value is outside normal limits and should be reported?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"PR interval of 0.26 second"},{"id":"o1","text":"PR interval of 0.16 second"},{"id":"o2","text":"QRS interval of 0.08 second"},{"id":"o3","text":"RR interval of 0.8 second"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"normal_intervals_g2","conceptId":"normal_intervals","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Abnormal: QRS >0.12 (0.14), PR >0.20 (0.24), and a prolonged QT (0.50). Normal values are PR 0.18 and QRS 0.08.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which ECG interval findings are abnormal and warrant further assessment? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"QRS of 0.14 second"},{"id":"o1","text":"PR of 0.24 second"},{"id":"o2","text":"QT of 0.50 second"},{"id":"o3","text":"PR of 0.18 second"},{"id":"o4","text":"QRS of 0.08 second"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2"]},{"id":"normal_intervals_g3","conceptId":"normal_intervals","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A QRS of 0.12 second or greater is widened, reflecting delayed ventricular (intraventricular) conduction such as a bundle branch block, and should be evaluated.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse measures a QRS duration of 0.13 second. This finding indicates:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Delayed ventricular conduction that should be investigated"},{"id":"o1","text":"A normal QRS"},{"id":"o2","text":"An atrial conduction problem"},{"id":"o3","text":"A normal variant requiring no action"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"normal_intervals_g4","conceptId":"normal_intervals","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Normal PR is 0.12-0.20 s and normal QRS is <0.12 s. Values beyond these (long PR, wide QRS, prolonged QT) indicate conduction abnormalities.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement about normal ECG interval values is correct?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Normal PR is 0.12-0.20 s and normal QRS is less than 0.12 s"},{"id":"o1","text":"Normal PR is greater than 0.24 s"},{"id":"o2","text":"Normal QRS is 0.16-0.20 s"},{"id":"o3","text":"Normal QT is always greater than 0.50 s"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"digoxin_tox_g0","conceptId":"digoxin_tox","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Classic digoxin toxicity includes GI upset (anorexia, nausea, vomiting), visual changes such as yellow-green halos, and dysrhythmias including bradycardia. Hypokalemia potentiates toxicity.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A nurse caring for a patient on digoxin should recognize which findings as possible digoxin toxicity?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Nausea, visual disturbances (yellow-green halos), and bradycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypertension and tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Constipation and dry mouth alone"},{"id":"o3","text":"Increased appetite and weight gain"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"digoxin_tox_g1","conceptId":"digoxin_tox","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Low potassium increases digoxin binding to cardiac cells and potentiates toxicity, so potassium is monitored closely in patients on digoxin, especially with diuretics.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which electrolyte abnormality increases the risk of digoxin toxicity?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypokalemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypernatremia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hyperchloremia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Hypercalcemia (mild)"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"digoxin_tox_g2","conceptId":"digoxin_tox","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Digoxin toxicity manifests as GI symptoms, visual disturbances, conduction abnormalities, and confusion (especially in older adults). A normal potassium (4.2) is not a toxicity cue.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which findings would alert the nurse to possible digoxin toxicity? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Anorexia, nausea, vomiting"},{"id":"o1","text":"Yellow-green visual halos"},{"id":"o2","text":"New bradycardia or heart block"},{"id":"o3","text":"Confusion in an older adult"},{"id":"o4","text":"A serum potassium of 4.2 mEq/L"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"digoxin_tox_g3","conceptId":"digoxin_tox","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> These are signs of digoxin toxicity, worsened by diuretic-induced hypokalemia. The nurse should withhold the dose and obtain a digoxin level and potassium before further administration.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient on digoxin and furosemide reports nausea and 'yellow vision.' The nurse's priority is to:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hold the digoxin and check the digoxin level and potassium"},{"id":"o1","text":"Administer an extra digoxin dose"},{"id":"o2","text":"Encourage more fluids and recheck in the morning"},{"id":"o3","text":"Give an antiemetic and continue the digoxin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"digoxin_tox_g4","conceptId":"digoxin_tox","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The nurse assesses the apical pulse for a full minute before giving digoxin and withholds it for significant bradycardia. Toxicity typically produces bradycardia, and potassium status strongly affects toxicity risk.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which statement about digoxin therapy is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Apical pulse should be assessed before administration and the dose held for significant bradycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Digoxin should be given regardless of heart rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"A fast heart rate is a sign of toxicity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Potassium levels do not affect digoxin"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pvc_k_g0","conceptId":"pvc_k","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Hypokalemia (2.9) increases ventricular irritability and the risk of dangerous dysrhythmias; it is the priority to report and correct in a patient with multifocal PVCs. The other values are normal.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient has frequent multifocal PVCs. Which laboratory value is most important to report to the provider?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Serum potassium of 2.9 mEq/L"},{"id":"o1","text":"Serum sodium of 138 mEq/L"},{"id":"o2","text":"Serum chloride of 100 mEq/L"},{"id":"o3","text":"Magnesium of 2.0 mg/dL"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pvc_k_g1","conceptId":"pvc_k","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Low potassium destabilizes the ventricular myocardium, increasing the risk that frequent multifocal PVCs progress to ventricular tachycardia or fibrillation; prompt correction is important.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Why is hypokalemia particularly concerning in a patient with multifocal PVCs?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It increases ventricular irritability and can precipitate VT or VF"},{"id":"o1","text":"It slows the sinus node only"},{"id":"o2","text":"It has no effect on ventricular rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"It prevents PVCs"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pvc_k_g2","conceptId":"pvc_k","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Both hypokalemia (2.8) and hypomagnesemia (1.2) increase ventricular irritability and warrant prompt reporting/correction. Sodium 140, calcium 9.0, and potassium 4.0 are normal.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with multifocal PVCs has these labs. Which should the nurse prioritize reporting? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Potassium 2.8 mEq/L"},{"id":"o1","text":"Magnesium 1.2 mg/dL"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sodium 140 mEq/L"},{"id":"o3","text":"Calcium 9.0 mg/dL"},{"id":"o4","text":"Potassium 4.0 mEq/L"}],"correct":["o0","o1"]},{"id":"pvc_k_g3","conceptId":"pvc_k","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Correcting the hypokalemia reduces ventricular irritability and the PVC burden. Cardioversion is not used for PVCs, and the electrolyte abnormality requires active correction.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with frequent PVCs has a potassium of 3.0 mEq/L. After notifying the provider, the nurse anticipates:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"An order to replace potassium and recheck the level"},{"id":"o1","text":"An order to restrict all fluids"},{"id":"o2","text":"No intervention since PVCs are benign"},{"id":"o3","text":"An order for synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pvc_k_g4","conceptId":"pvc_k","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Multifocal PVCs plus hypokalemia reflect significant ventricular irritability and carry the highest risk of progression to VT/VF, unlike occasional unifocal PVCs with normal labs.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which patient with PVCs is at highest risk for deterioration to a lethal rhythm?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A patient with multifocal PVCs and a potassium of 2.8 mEq/L"},{"id":"o1","text":"A patient with rare unifocal PVCs and normal electrolytes"},{"id":"o2","text":"An athlete with occasional PVCs at rest"},{"id":"o3","text":"A patient with PVCs that resolve with activity"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_asym_brady_g0","conceptId":"tx_asym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asymptomatic sinus bradycardia is an expected, benign finding in trained athletes due to increased vagal tone. With no symptoms and a normal BP, no treatment is needed.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A 20-year-old athlete has a pre-participation ECG showing sinus bradycardia at 52/min and BP 116/68. The athlete denies dizziness, chest pain, or syncope. Which action would the nurse take?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Document the finding; the athlete may participate"},{"id":"o1","text":"Refer urgently to cardiology for a pacemaker"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer atropine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Restrict the athlete from all activity"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_asym_brady_g1","conceptId":"tx_asym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Bradycardia is treated based on symptoms of inadequate perfusion. A slow but asymptomatic rate — common in athletes — requires only monitoring, not medication or pacing.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which principle guides management of asymptomatic sinus bradycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Treat the patient, not the number — intervene only if symptoms of poor perfusion appear"},{"id":"o1","text":"Always give atropine for any rate under 60"},{"id":"o2","text":"Every bradycardia requires a pacemaker"},{"id":"o3","text":"Asymptomatic bradycardia is always dangerous"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_asym_brady_g2","conceptId":"tx_asym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Appropriate care is documentation, reassurance, symptom education, and monitoring. Atropine is reserved for symptomatic bradycardia, not a normal athletic finding.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An asymptomatic athlete has a resting heart rate of 50/min. Which nursing actions are appropriate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Document the rhythm and rate"},{"id":"o1","text":"Reassure the patient this can be normal for athletes"},{"id":"o2","text":"Educate the patient to report dizziness or syncope"},{"id":"o3","text":"Continue routine monitoring"},{"id":"o4","text":"Administer atropine prophylactically"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"tx_asym_brady_g3","conceptId":"tx_asym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Symptoms of decreased perfusion (syncope, dizziness, hypotension) convert benign bradycardia into a treatable problem. The rate alone, with a normal BP and no symptoms, does not warrant intervention.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which finding would change an asymptomatic athlete's sinus bradycardia into a situation requiring intervention?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Development of syncope, dizziness, or hypotension"},{"id":"o1","text":"A resting rate of 50/min"},{"id":"o2","text":"A normal blood pressure"},{"id":"o3","text":"A regular rhythm with normal P waves"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"tx_asym_brady_g4","conceptId":"tx_asym_brady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Patient/family teaching should convey that athletic bradycardia reflects cardiovascular conditioning and, when asymptomatic, does not preclude participation or require treatment.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A coach asks why a star runner with a heart rate of 48 is being cleared to compete. The nurse's best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'A low resting heart rate is common and expected in well-trained athletes when they have no symptoms.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'We will start medication to raise the heart rate first.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'The athlete needs a pacemaker before competing.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'This is an emergency that prevents participation.'"},{"id":"o4","text":"'The heart rate must be above 60 to play.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pacemaker_teach_g0","conceptId":"pacemaker_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Limiting arm movement on the incision side prevents lead dislodgement during early healing. Microwaves are safe, light activity resumes sooner than 'several weeks,' and airline notification is not required (though carrying a device ID is wise).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient is being discharged after permanent pacemaker placement. Which statement indicates that teaching was effective?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'I won't lift the arm on the incision side above my shoulder until the provider says it is okay.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'I should avoid using a microwave oven.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'I will need several weeks before I can return to my usual light activities.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'I must notify the airline that I have a pacemaker when I book a flight.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pacemaker_teach_g1","conceptId":"pacemaker_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Pacemaker teaching includes arm-movement restriction, carrying an ID card, pulse monitoring, and simple cell-phone precautions. Microwave ovens are safe to use.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which instructions should be included when teaching a patient with a new permanent pacemaker? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Avoid raising the arm on the incision side above the shoulder until cleared"},{"id":"o1","text":"Carry a pacemaker identification card"},{"id":"o2","text":"Take your pulse as instructed and report a rate below the set rate"},{"id":"o3","text":"Keep cell phones a short distance from the device and use the opposite ear"},{"id":"o4","text":"Avoid all microwave ovens"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"pacemaker_teach_g2","conceptId":"pacemaker_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Modern pacemakers are shielded; everyday appliances including microwaves are safe. Patients are taught to avoid strong magnetic fields (e.g., MRI without clearance) and not to linger in anti-theft gates.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a new pacemaker asks about household appliances. The nurse's best response is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'Common appliances such as microwaves are safe; avoid strong magnetic fields and lingering near security/anti-theft systems.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'You must avoid all electrical appliances.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'Microwaves will stop your pacemaker.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'You can never use a cell phone again.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pacemaker_teach_g3","conceptId":"pacemaker_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Vigorous overhead movement on the incision side risks dislodging the leads during early healing and indicates incorrect understanding. The other statements reflect correct teaching.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which patient statement after pacemaker insertion indicates a need for further teaching?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"'I can do vigorous overhead arm exercises on the incision side right away.'"},{"id":"o1","text":"'I will carry an identification card about my pacemaker.'"},{"id":"o2","text":"'I will check my pulse daily and report a slow rate.'"},{"id":"o3","text":"'I will keep my follow-up appointments for device checks.'"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"pacemaker_teach_g4","conceptId":"pacemaker_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A rate below the programmed setting or recurrent dizziness/syncope may signal device malfunction and must be reported. A pulse at the set rate and resolving bruising are expected.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A pacemaker patient should be taught to notify the provider if which finding occurs?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A pulse rate consistently below the pacemaker's set rate, or dizziness/syncope"},{"id":"o1","text":"A pulse equal to the set rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"Mild incisional bruising that is improving"},{"id":"o3","text":"Normal energy with their usual activities"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"icd_teach_g0","conceptId":"icd_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Vigorous arm ROM on the operative side immediately after ICD insertion can dislodge the leads and indicates a need for further teaching. The other actions are appropriate post-ICD care.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A new nurse is caring for a patient after ICD insertion. Which action indicates a need for further teaching by the charge nurse?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Encourages vigorous active range-of-motion of the affected arm immediately"},{"id":"o1","text":"Helps the patient apply for a Medic Alert device"},{"id":"o2","text":"Teaches that sexual activity may resume once the incision heals"},{"id":"o3","text":"Reviews how to keep a log of any shocks delivered"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"icd_teach_g1","conceptId":"icd_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Patients are taught to sit/lie down when shocked, log the event, and seek emergency care for multiple shocks or symptoms. The device should never be removed by the patient.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a new ICD asks what to do if the device delivers a shock. The nurse teaches:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sit or lie down, note how you feel, and report shocks; call emergency services if you receive repeated shocks or feel unwell"},{"id":"o1","text":"Ignore all shocks"},{"id":"o2","text":"Remove the device immediately"},{"id":"o3","text":"Drive yourself to the clinic during a shock"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"icd_teach_g2","conceptId":"icd_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> ICD teaching includes arm precautions, carrying an ID card, logging/reporting shocks, and follow-up. Patients should pass through (not linger near) security gates to avoid interference.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Which teaching points are appropriate for a patient with a newly implanted ICD? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Avoid raising the affected arm overhead until cleared"},{"id":"o1","text":"Carry an ICD identification card"},{"id":"o2","text":"Keep a record of any shocks and report them"},{"id":"o3","text":"Maintain follow-up device interrogation appointments"},{"id":"o4","text":"Stand near anti-theft security gates for long periods"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"]},{"id":"icd_teach_g3","conceptId":"icd_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> An ICD monitors for and treats lethal ventricular dysrhythmias with antitachycardia pacing or a shock, whereas a pacemaker's primary role is to prevent excessive bradycardia.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An ICD differs from a permanent pacemaker primarily in that an ICD:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Detects and terminates life-threatening ventricular dysrhythmias by delivering a shock"},{"id":"o1","text":"Only paces a slow heart rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"Cannot deliver any therapy"},{"id":"o3","text":"Replaces the need for all cardiac medications"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"icd_teach_g4","conceptId":"icd_teach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Antiarrhythmic therapy such as amiodarone is commonly combined with an ICD to decrease the number of dysrhythmic episodes and therefore the number of shocks the patient receives.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with an ICD is prescribed amiodarone. The nurse understands this is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Appropriate, because antiarrhythmics can reduce the frequency of shocks"},{"id":"o1","text":"An error, because medication and an ICD cannot be combined"},{"id":"o2","text":"A reason to remove the ICD"},{"id":"o3","text":"Only used if the ICD fails"}],"correct":["o0"]},{"id":"cloze_rhythm_action_g0","conceptId":"cloze_rhythm_action","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A wide, regular, rapid, pulseless rhythm is pulseless VT — a shockable arrest treated with CPR and defibrillation, not vagal maneuvers or synchronized cardioversion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>The nurse interprets a strip for an unresponsive, pulseless patient showing a wide, regular, rapid waveform at 180/min with no P waves. The nurse identifies this as [b0] and prepares for [b1].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"pulseless ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"supraventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"sinus tachycardia"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"CPR and defibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"vagal maneuvers"},{"id":"o2","text":"synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":"o0"}],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cloze_rhythm_action_g1","conceptId":"cloze_rhythm_action","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Stable SVT that fails vagal maneuvers is treated with adenosine; pulseless VF requires immediate defibrillation. Atropine treats bradycardia, and cardioversion is not used for VF.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A stable patient with SVT unresponsive to vagal maneuvers may receive [b0]. In contrast, a patient in pulseless ventricular fibrillation requires immediate [b1].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"adenosine"},{"id":"o1","text":"atropine"},{"id":"o2","text":"epinephrine"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"defibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"synchronized cardioversion"},{"id":"o2","text":"adenosine"}],"correct":"o0"}],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cloze_rhythm_action_g2","conceptId":"cloze_rhythm_action","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Symptomatic bradycardia is treated with atropine first; if atropine fails, transcutaneous pacing (or a chronotropic infusion) is next. Adenosine and beta-blockers slow the rate.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient in symptomatic bradycardia at 38/min first receives [b0]; if ineffective, the team prepares for [b1].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"atropine"},{"id":"o1","text":"adenosine"},{"id":"o2","text":"a beta-blocker"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"transcutaneous pacing"},{"id":"o1","text":"defibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"vagal maneuvers"}],"correct":"o0"}],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cloze_rhythm_action_g3","conceptId":"cloze_rhythm_action","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Torsades with a pulse is treated with IV magnesium; pulseless torsades is a shockable arrest treated with CPR and defibrillation. Adenosine and CCBs are not used.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>A patient with a prolonged QT develops torsades de pointes with a pulse. The nurse anticipates [b0]; if the patient becomes pulseless, the team will [b1].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"IV magnesium sulfate"},{"id":"o1","text":"IV adenosine"},{"id":"o2","text":"IV diltiazem"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"begin CPR and defibrillate"},{"id":"o1","text":"perform vagal maneuvers"},{"id":"o2","text":"give oral metoprolol"}],"correct":"o0"}],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"cloze_rhythm_action_g4","conceptId":"cloze_rhythm_action","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S2","verified":true,"points":2,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> An organized rhythm without a pulse is PEA — a non-shockable arrest. Treatment is CPR plus identification and correction of reversible causes, not defibrillation or cardioversion.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>An unresponsive, pulseless patient shows an organized rhythm at 70/min. This is [b0], and the priority is [b1].</div>","type":"cloze","blanks":[{"key":"b0","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"pulseless electrical activity (PEA)"},{"id":"o1","text":"ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"asystole"}],"correct":"o0"},{"key":"b1","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"CPR and treating reversible causes"},{"id":"o1","text":"immediate defibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":"o0"}],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_afib_g0","conceptId":"id_afib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Irregularly irregular ventricular response with absent P waves and a fibrillatory baseline is the defining signature of atrial fibrillation. Atrial flutter shows sawtooth flutter waves; MAT shows ≥3 distinct P-wave morphologies.</p>","imageRhythm":"afib","stem":"<div>A 78-year-old reports palpitations. The rhythm is irregularly irregular with no discernible P waves and a fibrillatory baseline. Which rhythm does the nurse document?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sinus arrhythmia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Multifocal atrial tachycardia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Atrial flutter with variable block"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_afib_g1","conceptId":"id_afib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The pairing of absent organized P waves with irregular irregularity is what distinguishes afib. PR interval cannot be measured when P waves are absent, and QRS is typically narrow in afib.</p>","imageRhythm":"afib","stem":"<div>The monitor shows no organized P waves, an undulating baseline, and R-R intervals that vary beat to beat. Which feature most specifically identifies this as atrial fibrillation rather than another irregular rhythm?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Absent P waves with an irregularly irregular ventricular response"},{"id":"o1","text":"A consistently prolonged PR interval"},{"id":"o2","text":"A rate below 60/min"},{"id":"o3","text":"Wide, bizarre QRS complexes"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_afib_g2","conceptId":"id_afib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Afib is defined by irregular irregularity, absent P waves, and a fibrillatory baseline. Sawtooth waves indicate flutter; a measurable fixed PR requires conducted P waves, which afib lacks.</p>","imageRhythm":"afib","stem":"<div>Which findings on a rhythm strip are consistent with atrial fibrillation? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Irregularly irregular R-R intervals"},{"id":"o1","text":"Absent or indiscernible P waves"},{"id":"o2","text":"Fibrillatory (chaotic) baseline"},{"id":"o3","text":"A regular sawtooth flutter pattern"},{"id":"o4","text":"A fixed, measurable PR interval"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_afib_g3","conceptId":"id_afib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Afib with a ventricular rate under ~100/min is termed controlled. 'Rapid ventricular response' applies when the rate exceeds ~100/min. The rhythm itself is still atrial fibrillation.</p>","imageRhythm":"afib","stem":"<div>A patient's strip shows a ventricular rate of about 90/min that is irregularly irregular with no P waves. The nurse correctly identifies this as atrial fibrillation. This rate would be described as:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Controlled (rate-controlled) atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response"},{"id":"o2","text":"Coarse ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus rhythm with PACs"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_afib_g4","conceptId":"id_afib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In afib the atria depolarize chaotically, so no discrete organized P waves are produced. The other options describe junctional rhythm, normal conduction, and Wenckebach respectively.</p>","imageRhythm":"afib","stem":"<div>Which statement about the P waves in atrial fibrillation is accurate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"There are no identifiable, organized P waves"},{"id":"o1","text":"P waves are present but inverted"},{"id":"o2","text":"Every P wave is followed by a QRS"},{"id":"o3","text":"P waves progressively lengthen the PR interval"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vfib_g0","conceptId":"id_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Chaotic deflections of varying amplitude with no organized QRS in a pulseless patient is ventricular fibrillation. Afib has organized QRS complexes; asystole is a flat line.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>A patient collapses; the monitor shows chaotic, irregular deflections of varying amplitude with no identifiable QRS complexes. The patient is pulseless. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Coarse ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Asystole"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vfib_g1","conceptId":"id_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> VT produces wide but discrete, countable QRS complexes; VF produces no organized QRS at all, only chaotic undulations. Neither shows usable P waves or PR intervals.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>Which single feature most distinguishes ventricular fibrillation from ventricular tachycardia on the monitor?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"VF has no organized, identifiable QRS complexes; VT has wide but discrete QRS complexes"},{"id":"o1","text":"VF is always slower than VT"},{"id":"o2","text":"VF has visible P waves"},{"id":"o3","text":"VF has a measurable PR interval"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vfib_g2","conceptId":"id_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Coarse, disorganized, patternless activity without a pulse is VF. Torsades shows a recognizable polymorphic twisting pattern; third-degree block and sinus tach have organized complexes.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>A rhythm shows coarse, totally disorganized electrical activity with no discernible pattern in a pulseless, apneic patient. The nurse identifies this as:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"o1","text":"Torsades de pointes"},{"id":"o2","text":"Third-degree AV block"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus tachycardia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vfib_g3","conceptId":"id_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> VF has no organized QRS, a chaotic varying-amplitude baseline, and never produces a pulse. It has no measurable rate and no flutter/sawtooth waves.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>Which characteristics describe ventricular fibrillation? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"No identifiable QRS complexes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Chaotic baseline with varying amplitude"},{"id":"o2","text":"Always pulseless — a cardiac arrest rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"Regular sawtooth waves"},{"id":"o4","text":"A consistent, measurable rate"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vfib_g4","conceptId":"id_vfib","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Fine (low-amplitude) VF generally reflects a longer arrest interval and worse prognosis than coarse VF, but both are pulseless shockable rhythms requiring CPR and defibrillation.</p>","imageRhythm":"vfib","stem":"<div>The nurse sees fine, low-amplitude chaotic activity with no QRS complexes in an unresponsive, pulseless patient. Compared with coarse VF, fine VF most likely indicates:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A longer downtime / more prolonged arrest"},{"id":"o1","text":"A more stable, perfusing rhythm"},{"id":"o2","text":"Successful return of spontaneous circulation"},{"id":"o3","text":"A supraventricular origin"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vtach_g0","conceptId":"id_vtach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A regular wide-complex (QRS ≥0.12 s) tachycardia without P waves is monomorphic VT. Sinus tach has normal narrow QRS with P waves; afib is irregular.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>The monitor shows a regular, wide-complex tachycardia at 180/min with no visible P waves. The patient has a pulse and is alert. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Monomorphic ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sinus tachycardia"},{"id":"o3","text":"First-degree AV block"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vtach_g1","conceptId":"id_vtach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Monomorphic VT shows wide, uniform QRS complexes at a regular rapid rate of 150-250/min. The other options describe afib, asystole, and Mobitz I respectively.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>Which set of features identifies monomorphic ventricular tachycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Wide QRS, regular rhythm, rate 150-250/min, uniform QRS shape"},{"id":"o1","text":"Narrow QRS, irregular rhythm, no P waves"},{"id":"o2","text":"Flat line with no electrical activity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Progressive PR lengthening with dropped beats"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vtach_g2","conceptId":"id_vtach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Identical (uniform) QRS morphology defines monomorphic VT. Polymorphic VT (e.g., torsades) shows continuously changing QRS shape; idioventricular rhythm is slow, not tachycardic.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>A wide-complex tachycardia is regular with QRS complexes that all look identical. This uniformity tells the nurse the VT is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Monomorphic"},{"id":"o1","text":"Polymorphic"},{"id":"o2","text":"Supraventricular"},{"id":"o3","text":"Idioventricular"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vtach_g3","conceptId":"id_vtach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Monomorphic VT is wide, regular, rapid, and uniform. P waves are usually absent or dissociated, not clearly visible before each QRS.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>Which findings are consistent with monomorphic ventricular tachycardia? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Wide QRS (≥0.12 s)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Regular ventricular rhythm"},{"id":"o2","text":"Rate typically 150-250/min"},{"id":"o3","text":"Uniform QRS morphology"},{"id":"o4","text":"Clearly visible P waves before each QRS"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_vtach_g4","conceptId":"id_vtach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> AV dissociation strongly favors VT over SVT with aberrancy. When uncertain, a wide-complex tachycardia is treated as VT until proven otherwise.</p>","imageRhythm":"vtach","stem":"<div>The nurse must distinguish VT from SVT with aberrancy on a wide-complex tachycardia. Which finding favors ventricular tachycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"AV dissociation (P waves marching independently of QRS)"},{"id":"o1","text":"A narrow QRS"},{"id":"o2","text":"An irregularly irregular rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"A clearly conducted P wave before every QRS"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_3avb_g0","conceptId":"id_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Complete AV dissociation — P waves and QRS each regular but independent — defines third-degree block. First-degree block conducts every P with a long PR; sinus brady conducts normally.</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>The strip shows regular P waves and regular QRS complexes, but the P waves bear no consistent relationship to the QRS and the ventricular rate is 35/min. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Third-degree (complete) AV block"},{"id":"o1","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sinus bradycardia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Atrial fibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_3avb_g1","conceptId":"id_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Complete block means no atrial impulses reach the ventricles; an escape pacemaker drives the ventricles independently. The other options describe first-degree block, Wenckebach, and afib.</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>In third-degree AV block, what is the relationship between atrial and ventricular activity?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"The atria and ventricles beat independently with no conduction between them"},{"id":"o1","text":"Every P wave conducts with a prolonged PR interval"},{"id":"o2","text":"The PR lengthens until a beat drops"},{"id":"o3","text":"There are no P waves at all"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_3avb_g2","conceptId":"id_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Complete block shows regular P waves and a regular but independent ventricular escape rhythm with full AV dissociation. If every P conducted a QRS, it would not be complete block.</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>Which findings identify third-degree (complete) heart block? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"P waves present and regular"},{"id":"o1","text":"QRS complexes regular but at their own slower rate"},{"id":"o2","text":"No consistent PR relationship"},{"id":"o3","text":"P waves and QRS are completely dissociated"},{"id":"o4","text":"Every P wave is followed by a QRS"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_3avb_g3","conceptId":"id_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> In complete block the AV node does not conduct, so a junctional or ventricular escape focus maintains the slow ventricular rate independent of the atria.</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>A monitored patient has an atrial rate of 80/min and a ventricular rate of 30/min with no relationship between the two. The nurse recognizes the ventricular rhythm is being maintained by:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A ventricular escape pacemaker"},{"id":"o1","text":"The SA node"},{"id":"o2","text":"Retrograde atrial conduction"},{"id":"o3","text":"Normal AV nodal conduction"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_3avb_g4","conceptId":"id_3avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Complete AV dissociation — atria and ventricles independent — is the hallmark of third-degree block. The other rhythms retain some P-QRS relationship.</p>","imageRhythm":"third_degree","stem":"<div>Which block is most accurately described as 'P waves and QRS complexes that march to their own separate drummers'?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Third-degree (complete) AV block"},{"id":"o1","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"o2","text":"Second-degree Mobitz I"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus rhythm"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_asystole_g0","conceptId":"id_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A true flat line with no electrical deflections is asystole. Fine VF still shows chaotic low-amplitude activity; PEA shows an organized rhythm without a pulse.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>A patient is unresponsive, apneic, and pulseless. The monitor shows a flat line with no electrical activity. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Asystole"},{"id":"o1","text":"Fine ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"o2","text":"Pulseless electrical activity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus arrest with junctional escape"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_asystole_g1","conceptId":"id_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asystole should be confirmed in two leads to rule out fine VF or a disconnected/displaced lead masquerading as a flat line. Asystole is never shocked.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>Before treating an apparent flat line as asystole, the nurse should first:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Confirm the flat line in more than one lead and check lead placement"},{"id":"o1","text":"Immediately defibrillate"},{"id":"o2","text":"Administer adenosine"},{"id":"o3","text":"Apply synchronized cardioversion"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_asystole_g2","conceptId":"id_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asystole is the absence of electrical activity (flat line), non-shockable, and confirmed in two leads. Defibrillation is useless because there is no electrical activity to reorganize.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>Which statements about asystole are accurate? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"There is no organized electrical activity"},{"id":"o1","text":"It appears as a flat line on the monitor"},{"id":"o2","text":"It is a non-shockable rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"It should be confirmed in two leads"},{"id":"o4","text":"Defibrillation is the first-line treatment"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_asystole_g3","conceptId":"id_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The distinction is the presence (fine VF) versus complete absence (asystole) of electrical deflections. This distinction matters because VF is shockable and asystole is not.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>Which finding best distinguishes asystole from fine ventricular fibrillation?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Asystole shows a flat line with no deflections; fine VF shows low-amplitude chaotic activity"},{"id":"o1","text":"Asystole shows wide QRS complexes"},{"id":"o2","text":"Asystole has visible P waves"},{"id":"o3","text":"Asystole has a measurable rate"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_asystole_g4","conceptId":"id_asystole","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A flat line in an awake, perfusing patient indicates an artifact such as a disconnected lead, not asystole. Always correlate the monitor with the patient before acting.</p>","imageRhythm":"asystole","stem":"<div>The monitor displays a flat line. The nurse notes the patient is awake and talking. The most likely explanation is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A lead has become disconnected or displaced"},{"id":"o1","text":"The patient is in true asystole"},{"id":"o2","text":"The patient is in ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"The patient has third-degree block"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_sbrady_g0","conceptId":"id_sbrady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A regular sinus rhythm under 60/min with normal P waves and a normal PR is sinus bradycardia. First-degree block has a prolonged PR; junctional rhythm lacks normal upright P waves.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>A strip shows a regular rhythm at 48/min with a normal upright P wave before every QRS and a normal PR interval. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sinus bradycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"o2","text":"Junctional rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus arrest"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_sbrady_g1","conceptId":"id_sbrady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus bradycardia is a normally conducted sinus rhythm with a rate below 60/min. The distractors describe sinus tach, afib, and an idioventricular/escape rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>Which set of criteria defines sinus bradycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rate <60/min, regular, normal P wave before each QRS, normal PR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Rate >100/min with normal P waves"},{"id":"o2","text":"Irregularly irregular with no P waves"},{"id":"o3","text":"Wide QRS at 40/min with AV dissociation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_sbrady_g2","conceptId":"id_sbrady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus bradycardia retains normal sinus conduction — a P wave before each QRS, normal PR — simply at a slow rate. Absent P waves would indicate a non-sinus rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>Which findings are consistent with sinus bradycardia? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Heart rate below 60/min"},{"id":"o1","text":"Regular R-R intervals"},{"id":"o2","text":"One normal P wave before each QRS"},{"id":"o3","text":"Normal PR interval (0.12-0.20 s)"},{"id":"o4","text":"Absent P waves"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_sbrady_g3","conceptId":"id_sbrady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus bradycardia is an expected finding in trained athletes due to high vagal tone. Identification is the same regardless of cause; significance depends on symptoms.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>A conditioned 22-year-old athlete has a regular rhythm at 50/min with normal P waves and normal PR. The nurse identifies the rhythm and recognizes that in this patient it is most likely:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sinus bradycardia that is a normal finding for a trained athlete"},{"id":"o1","text":"A dangerous conduction defect requiring a pacemaker"},{"id":"o2","text":"Junctional escape rhythm"},{"id":"o3","text":"Second-degree AV block"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_sbrady_g4","conceptId":"id_sbrady","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The presence of a normal upright (sinus) P wave before each QRS identifies the rhythm as sinus in origin rather than junctional, which shows absent, inverted, or retrograde P waves.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_brady","stem":"<div>Which feature differentiates sinus bradycardia from a junctional rhythm at the same slow rate?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sinus bradycardia has a normal upright P wave before each QRS"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sinus bradycardia has a wide QRS"},{"id":"o2","text":"Sinus bradycardia has no QRS complexes"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus bradycardia is irregular"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_svt_g0","conceptId":"id_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A regular narrow-complex tachycardia too fast to show discrete P waves (typically >150/min) is SVT. Sinus tach usually shows P waves and is rate-appropriate to a stressor; VT is wide; afib is irregular.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>The monitor shows a regular narrow-complex tachycardia at 190/min with no discernible P waves. The patient reports palpitations. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Supraventricular tachycardia (SVT)"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sinus tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Atrial fibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_svt_g1","conceptId":"id_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> SVT typically exceeds 150/min, hides the P waves, and starts/stops abruptly, whereas sinus tach has visible P waves and gradual onset tied to a physiologic cause.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>Which feature best distinguishes SVT from sinus tachycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"In SVT the rate is usually >150/min with no discernible P waves and abrupt onset"},{"id":"o1","text":"SVT always has a wide QRS"},{"id":"o2","text":"SVT is irregularly irregular"},{"id":"o3","text":"SVT shows a sawtooth baseline"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_svt_g2","conceptId":"id_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> SVT is narrow, regular, rapid, and frequently buries the P wave in the prior T wave. Wide bizarre QRS complexes would suggest VT instead.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>Which findings are consistent with supraventricular tachycardia? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Narrow QRS complexes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Regular rhythm"},{"id":"o2","text":"Rate often 150-250/min"},{"id":"o3","text":"P waves often hidden in the preceding T wave"},{"id":"o4","text":"Wide, bizarre QRS complexes"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_svt_g3","conceptId":"id_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Paroxysmal SVT classically starts and stops suddenly because of a reentrant circuit. Sinus tachycardia speeds up and slows gradually with the underlying stimulus.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>A regular narrow-complex tachycardia at 200/min begins and ends abruptly. This abrupt 'on-off' behavior is characteristic of:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Sinus tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus arrhythmia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_svt_g4","conceptId":"id_svt","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Most SVT is due to AV nodal reentry or an accessory-pathway reentrant circuit, which is why AV-nodal-blocking maneuvers (vagal, adenosine) terminate it.</p>","imageRhythm":"svt","stem":"<div>The nurse sees a narrow-complex regular tachycardia and cannot find P waves. Which underlying mechanism most commonly produces this rhythm?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A reentrant circuit at or near the AV node"},{"id":"o1","text":"A ventricular escape focus"},{"id":"o2","text":"Chaotic atrial fibrillatory activity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Complete failure of the SA node"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_stach_g0","conceptId":"id_stach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A regular rhythm of 100-150/min with a normal P wave before each QRS is sinus tachycardia, typically a compensatory response (here, to fever). SVT is faster and hides P waves.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>A febrile postoperative patient has a regular rhythm at 124/min with a normal P wave before every QRS and a normal PR interval. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sinus tachycardia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Supraventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Atrial flutter"},{"id":"o3","text":"Ventricular tachycardia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_stach_g1","conceptId":"id_stach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tachycardia is normal sinus conduction at 100-150/min. The distractors describe SVT, afib, and VT.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>Which set of criteria identifies sinus tachycardia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rate 100-150/min, regular, normal P before each QRS, normal PR"},{"id":"o1","text":"Rate >180/min with no P waves"},{"id":"o2","text":"Irregular with fibrillatory baseline"},{"id":"o3","text":"Wide QRS with AV dissociation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_stach_g2","conceptId":"id_stach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tach is regular, rate-appropriate, retains normal P waves, and arises gradually from a physiologic stressor. Absent P waves with irregularity describes afib.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>Which findings are consistent with sinus tachycardia? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Rate 100-150/min"},{"id":"o1","text":"Regular rhythm"},{"id":"o2","text":"Upright P wave before each QRS"},{"id":"o3","text":"Gradual onset linked to a stimulus (fever, pain, hypovolemia)"},{"id":"o4","text":"Absent P waves with an irregular rhythm"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_stach_g3","conceptId":"id_stach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Discernible normal P waves before each QRS at this rate point to sinus tachycardia. SVT typically exceeds 150/min and obscures the P waves.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>The nurse notes a regular narrow rhythm at 130/min with visible P waves in a patient who is anxious and in pain. The presence of visible, normal P waves before each QRS tells the nurse this is:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Sinus tachycardia rather than SVT"},{"id":"o1","text":"Ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Third-degree block"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_stach_g4","conceptId":"id_stach","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tachycardia is the heart's normal response to a physiologic demand; management targets the underlying cause rather than the rhythm itself.</p>","imageRhythm":"sinus_tach","stem":"<div>Why is sinus tachycardia generally considered a sign rather than a primary dysrhythmia?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"It is usually a compensatory response to an underlying cause such as fever, pain, or hypovolemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"It originates in the ventricles"},{"id":"o2","text":"It reflects failure of the SA node"},{"id":"o3","text":"It is always pathologic and life-threatening"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_1avb_g0","conceptId":"id_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A consistently prolonged PR interval (>0.20 s) in which every P still conducts a QRS defines first-degree AV block. Mobitz I shows progressive PR lengthening with dropped beats.</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>A strip shows a regular rhythm at 68/min in which every P wave is followed by a QRS, but the PR interval is consistently 0.28 seconds. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"o1","text":"Second-degree AV block Mobitz I"},{"id":"o2","text":"Third-degree AV block"},{"id":"o3","text":"Normal sinus rhythm"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_1avb_g1","conceptId":"id_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> First-degree block is a fixed, prolonged PR with 1:1 conduction. The distractors describe Mobitz I, complete block, and afib respectively.</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>Which feature defines first-degree AV block?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A consistently prolonged PR interval (>0.20 s) with every P conducting"},{"id":"o1","text":"A PR that lengthens until a QRS drops"},{"id":"o2","text":"Complete dissociation of P waves and QRS"},{"id":"o3","text":"Absent P waves"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_1avb_g2","conceptId":"id_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> First-degree block is a fixed prolonged PR with consistent 1:1 conduction and a regular rhythm. If some P waves failed to conduct, it would be a higher-degree block.</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>Which findings identify first-degree AV block? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"PR interval greater than 0.20 seconds"},{"id":"o1","text":"PR interval is the same on every beat"},{"id":"o2","text":"Every P wave is followed by a QRS"},{"id":"o3","text":"Rhythm is usually regular"},{"id":"o4","text":"Some P waves fail to conduct"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_1avb_g3","conceptId":"id_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The absence of any dropped QRS distinguishes first-degree block (every P conducts) from second-degree block (intermittent non-conduction).</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>The nurse measures a PR interval of 0.32 seconds that is identical on every beat, with a QRS after each P wave. This consistency (no dropped beats) distinguishes first-degree block from:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Second-degree AV block"},{"id":"o1","text":"Normal PR interval"},{"id":"o2","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Sinus tachycardia"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_1avb_g4","conceptId":"id_1avb","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> First-degree block represents delayed conduction through the AV node while still conducting every impulse, producing a uniformly long PR interval.</p>","imageRhythm":"first_degree","stem":"<div>A prolonged but fixed PR interval with 1:1 AV conduction most often reflects:</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Slowed conduction through the AV node"},{"id":"o1","text":"A ventricular escape rhythm"},{"id":"o2","text":"Chaotic atrial activity"},{"id":"o3","text":"Failure of the SA node to fire"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_torsades_g0","conceptId":"id_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A polymorphic VT whose QRS axis twists around the isoelectric line in the setting of a prolonged QT is torsades de pointes. Monomorphic VT has uniform QRS; VF has no organized QRS.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>A patient with a long QT interval develops a wide-complex tachycardia in which the QRS amplitude appears to twist around the baseline. Which rhythm is this?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Torsades de pointes"},{"id":"o1","text":"Monomorphic ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"o3","text":"Ventricular fibrillation"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_torsades_g1","conceptId":"id_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Torsades is polymorphic with a continuously changing, twisting QRS and is associated with QT prolongation; monomorphic VT has uniform QRS complexes.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>Which feature distinguishes torsades de pointes from monomorphic VT?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Torsades shows a polymorphic, twisting QRS pattern, often with a prolonged QT"},{"id":"o1","text":"Torsades has a flat baseline"},{"id":"o2","text":"Torsades is narrow-complex"},{"id":"o3","text":"Torsades has visible normal P waves"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_torsades_g2","conceptId":"id_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Torsades is polymorphic, twists around the baseline, and is driven by QT prolongation (often from hypomagnesemia/hypokalemia or QT-prolonging drugs). Uniform QRS would be monomorphic VT.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>Which findings are characteristic of torsades de pointes? Select all that apply.</div>","type":"sata","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Polymorphic (changing) QRS morphology"},{"id":"o1","text":"A twisting appearance around the baseline"},{"id":"o2","text":"Association with a prolonged QT interval"},{"id":"o3","text":"Often related to low magnesium or low potassium"},{"id":"o4","text":"Uniform, identical QRS complexes"}],"correct":["o0","o1","o2","o3"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_torsades_g3","conceptId":"id_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> QT prolongation is the substrate for torsades. Recognizing a long QT on a baseline strip lets the nurse anticipate and help prevent this dangerous rhythm.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>A nurse reviewing a telemetry strip notes a polymorphic VT that twists around the isoelectric line. Before this rhythm developed, which finding most likely predisposed the patient to it?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"A prolonged QT interval"},{"id":"o1","text":"A short PR interval"},{"id":"o2","text":"A wide P wave"},{"id":"o3","text":"ST-segment depression"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"id_torsades_g4","conceptId":"id_torsades","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":true,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Low magnesium and low potassium prolong the QT and precipitate torsades, which is why magnesium repletion is both treatment and prevention.</p>","imageRhythm":"torsades","stem":"<div>Which laboratory abnormalities most commonly set the stage for torsades de pointes?</div>","type":"mc","options":[{"id":"o0","text":"Hypomagnesemia and hypokalemia"},{"id":"o1","text":"Hypernatremia and hyperchloremia"},{"id":"o2","text":"Hypercalcemia and hyperglycemia"},{"id":"o3","text":"Elevated BUN and creatinine"}],"correct":["o0"],"verifiedSource":"external_2025"},{"id":"match_rhythms_g0","conceptId":"match_rhythms","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Afib is irregular with no P waves; VT is wide and regular; sinus bradycardia is a normal slow sinus rhythm; asystole is a flat line.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each cardiac rhythm to its defining description.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"l1","text":"Ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"l2","text":"Sinus bradycardia"},{"id":"l3","text":"Asystole"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Irregularly irregular, no identifiable P waves, fibrillatory baseline"},{"id":"r1","text":"Wide, regular QRS complexes at 150-250/min"},{"id":"r2","text":"Regular rhythm under 60/min with a normal P wave before each QRS"},{"id":"r3","text":"No electrical activity; flat line"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_rhythms_g1","conceptId":"match_rhythms","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Sinus tach shows visible P waves; SVT is faster and hides P waves; torsades twists with a long QT; VF is chaotic and pulseless.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each rhythm to its key feature.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Sinus tachycardia"},{"id":"l1","text":"Supraventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"l2","text":"Torsades de pointes"},{"id":"l3","text":"Ventricular fibrillation"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Regular, 100-150/min, normal P before each QRS"},{"id":"r1","text":"Narrow, regular, 150-250/min, P waves not discernible"},{"id":"r2","text":"Polymorphic VT that twists around the baseline with a long QT"},{"id":"r3","text":"Chaotic, no organized QRS, pulseless"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_rhythms_g2","conceptId":"match_rhythms","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> First-degree block has a fixed long PR; complete block has AV dissociation; afib is irregular without P waves; monomorphic VT is wide and uniform.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each rhythm to its hallmark.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"l1","text":"Third-degree AV block"},{"id":"l2","text":"Atrial fibrillation"},{"id":"l3","text":"Monomorphic VT"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Fixed prolonged PR (>0.20 s), every P conducts"},{"id":"r1","text":"P waves and QRS fully independent"},{"id":"r2","text":"Irregularly irregular, no P waves"},{"id":"r3","text":"Wide, uniform, regular, rapid QRS"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_rhythms_g3","conceptId":"match_rhythms","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Asystole is a flat line; PEA is an organized rhythm without a pulse; sinus bradycardia is slow and normal-looking; SVT is fast and narrow.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each rhythm to its description.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Asystole"},{"id":"l1","text":"Pulseless electrical activity"},{"id":"l2","text":"Sinus bradycardia"},{"id":"l3","text":"Supraventricular tachycardia"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Flat line, no electrical activity, pulseless"},{"id":"r1","text":"Organized rhythm on the monitor but no pulse"},{"id":"r2","text":"Slow regular sinus rhythm, normal P waves"},{"id":"r3","text":"Fast narrow-complex regular rhythm, hidden P waves"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_rhythms_g4","conceptId":"match_rhythms","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> VF has no organized QRS; VT is wide and regular; torsades twists with a long QT; afib is irregularly irregular without P waves.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each rhythm to its defining characteristic.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Ventricular fibrillation"},{"id":"l1","text":"Ventricular tachycardia"},{"id":"l2","text":"Torsades de pointes"},{"id":"l3","text":"Atrial fibrillation"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Chaotic undulations, no QRS, pulseless"},{"id":"r1","text":"Wide regular QRS at a rapid rate"},{"id":"r2","text":"Twisting polymorphic VT associated with a prolonged QT"},{"id":"r3","text":"Irregularly irregular ventricular response, no P waves"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_blocks_g0","conceptId":"match_blocks","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> First-degree: fixed long PR, all conduct. Mobitz I: progressive PR lengthening then dropped beat. Mobitz II: sudden dropped beats without PR change. Complete: full AV dissociation.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each AV heart block to its defining characteristic.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"l1","text":"Second-degree Mobitz I (Wenckebach)"},{"id":"l2","text":"Second-degree Mobitz II"},{"id":"l3","text":"Third-degree (complete) block"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"PR interval consistently prolonged (>0.20 s); all P waves conduct"},{"id":"r1","text":"PR progressively lengthens until a QRS is dropped, then repeats"},{"id":"r2","text":"P waves intermittently fail to conduct without PR lengthening"},{"id":"r3","text":"No relationship between P waves and QRS; atria and ventricles independent"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_blocks_g1","conceptId":"match_blocks","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> The discriminators are: fixed long PR (1°), lengthening PR with dropped beat (Mobitz I), fixed PR with sudden drops (Mobitz II), and total dissociation (3°).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each block to its key feature.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"l1","text":"Mobitz I (Wenckebach)"},{"id":"l2","text":"Mobitz II"},{"id":"l3","text":"Third-degree block"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Every P conducts with a uniformly prolonged PR"},{"id":"r1","text":"Cyclic PR lengthening ending in a dropped QRS"},{"id":"r2","text":"Constant PR with sudden non-conducted P waves; can progress to complete block"},{"id":"r3","text":"Independent atrial and ventricular rhythms"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_blocks_g2","conceptId":"match_blocks","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Strip appearance distinguishes them: constant long PR (1°), progressive PR then a gap (Mobitz I), sudden gaps with normal PR (Mobitz II), and independent regular P and QRS (3°).</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each block to how it appears on the strip.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"First-degree"},{"id":"l1","text":"Mobitz I"},{"id":"l2","text":"Mobitz II"},{"id":"l3","text":"Complete (third-degree)"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Long but constant PR; no dropped beats"},{"id":"r1","text":"PR gets longer and longer, then a beat is skipped"},{"id":"r2","text":"Normal PR, then a QRS suddenly missing"},{"id":"r3","text":"P-P and R-R each regular but unrelated"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_blocks_g3","conceptId":"match_blocks","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> Severity rises across the blocks: 1° benign, Mobitz I usually benign, Mobitz II concerning (pacing risk), and complete block requiring pacing when symptomatic.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each block to its clinical danger level/feature.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"l1","text":"Mobitz I"},{"id":"l2","text":"Mobitz II"},{"id":"l3","text":"Third-degree block"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"Usually benign; monitor only when asymptomatic"},{"id":"r1","text":"Often transient and well tolerated"},{"id":"r2","text":"More dangerous; can progress to complete block, may need pacing"},{"id":"r3","text":"Requires pacing when symptomatic; escape rhythm unreliable"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]},{"id":"match_blocks_g4","conceptId":"match_blocks","domain":"Dysrhythmias","section":"S1","verified":false,"points":1,"rationale":"<p><strong>Rationale:</strong> This reverses the match: the description on the left maps to the correct block name on the right, reinforcing recognition in both directions.</p>","imageRhythm":null,"stem":"<div>Match each AV block description to its name.</div>","type":"matching","leftPrompts":[{"id":"l0","text":"Uniformly prolonged PR with 1:1 conduction"},{"id":"l1","text":"Progressive PR prolongation then a dropped QRS"},{"id":"l2","text":"Intermittent dropped QRS with a constant PR"},{"id":"l3","text":"Complete AV dissociation"}],"rightOptions":[{"id":"r0","text":"First-degree AV block"},{"id":"r1","text":"Mobitz I (Wenckebach)"},{"id":"r2","text":"Mobitz II"},{"id":"r3","text":"Third-degree block"}],"pairs":[["l0","r0"],["l1","r1"],["l2","r2"],["l3","r3"]]}]};
const ITEMS = DATA.items;
// STRIPS now imported from ./images.js (externalized PNGs)
const MASCOTS = {"pools":{"home":["home_present","home_wave","home_arms"],"question":["question_point"],"rationale":["rationale_open","rationale_heart","rationale_clip"],"correct":["correct_thumbs","correct_fist"],"incorrect":["incorrect_think"]}};
// MASCOT_IMGS now imported from ./images.js (externalized PNGs)
const MASCOT_POOLS = MASCOTS.pools;
function pickMascot(state){const p=MASCOT_POOLS[state]; if(!p||!p.length) return null; const k=p[Math.floor(Math.random()*p.length)]; return MASCOT_IMGS[k];}

const DOMAINS = ["Dysrhythmias","Liver","GI","Hematologic","Autoimmune","Clinical Judgment"];
const DOMAIN_SHORT = {
  "Dysrhythmias":"Dysrhythmias","Liver":"Liver","GI":"GI",
  "Hematologic":"Heme/Onc","Autoimmune":"Autoimmune","Clinical Judgment":"Clinical Judgment"
};

// ---------- scoring helpers ----------
function gradeItem(item, resp) {
  // returns {earned, max, correct(bool full), perElement:[]}
  if (item.type === "mc") {
    const ok = resp && resp.length === 1 && item.correct.includes(resp[0]);
    return { earned: ok ? item.points : 0, max: item.points, full: ok };
  }
  if (item.type === "sata") {
    const correct = new Set(item.correct);
    const chosen = new Set(resp || []);
    const total = item.options.length;
    let right = 0;
    item.options.forEach(o => {
      const inC = correct.has(o.id), inR = chosen.has(o.id);
      if (inC === inR) right++; // correct inclusion or correct exclusion
    });
    const frac = right / total;
    const earned = +(item.points * frac).toFixed(3);
    return { earned, max: item.points, full: right === total };
  }
  if (item.type === "cloze") {
    const total = item.blanks.length;
    let right = 0;
    item.blanks.forEach(b => { if (resp && resp[b.key] === b.correct) right++; });
    const earned = +(item.points * (right / total)).toFixed(3);
    return { earned, max: item.points, full: right === total };
  }
  if (item.type === "matching") {
    const total = item.pairs.length;
    let right = 0;
    item.pairs.forEach(([l, r]) => { if (resp && resp[l] === r) right++; });
    const earned = +(item.points * (right / total)).toFixed(3);
    return { earned, max: item.points, full: right === total };
  }
  return { earned: 0, max: item.points, full: false };
}

function shuffle(arr) {
  const a = arr.slice();
  for (let i = a.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
    const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
    [a[i], a[j]] = [a[j], a[i]];
  }
  return a;
}

// ---------- animated EKG signature trace ----------
function EkgTrace({ active }) {
  return (
    <svg className="ekg-trace" viewBox="0 0 600 60" preserveAspectRatio="none" aria-hidden="true">
      <path className={active ? "ekg-path pulse" : "ekg-path"}
        d="M0,30 L80,30 L92,30 L100,12 L108,48 L116,30 L130,30 L150,30 L156,22 L162,30 L240,30 L252,30 L260,12 L268,48 L276,30 L290,30 L320,30 L326,22 L332,30 L420,30 L432,30 L440,12 L448,48 L456,30 L470,30 L500,30 L506,22 L512,30 L600,30" />
    </svg>
  );
}

function Strip({ rhythm }) {
  const [zoom, setZoom] = useState(false);
  if (!rhythm || !STRIPS[rhythm]) return null;
  return (
    <div className={"strip " + (zoom ? "strip-zoom" : "")} onClick={() => setZoom(z => !z)}
         role="button" tabIndex={0}
         onKeyDown={e => { if (e.key === "Enter" || e.key === " ") { e.preventDefault(); setZoom(z=>!z);} }}
         aria-label={"Rhythm strip. " + (zoom ? "Tap to shrink." : "Tap to enlarge.")}>
      <img src={STRIPS[rhythm]} alt="Cardiac rhythm strip" draggable="false" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
      <span className="strip-hint">{zoom ? "tap to shrink" : "tap to zoom"}</span>
    </div>
  );
}

function VerifyTag() {
  return (
    <span className="tag-unverified" title="AI-generated — not clinician-verified">
      <svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="2.5"><path d="M12 9v4M12 17h.01M10.3 3.9 1.8 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.7 3h17a2 2 0 0 0 1.7-3L13.7 3.9a2 2 0 0 0-3.4 0Z"/></svg>
      AI wrote this — vibe-check before you trust it
    </span>
  );
}
function VerifiedTag() {
  return (
    <span className="tag-verified" title="Reviewed item from the course bank">
      <svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="2.5"><path d="M20 6 9 17l-5-5"/></svg>
      verified
    </span>
  );
}

// ---------- mascot (Professor Tecson) ----------
function Mascot({ state, side }) {
  // state: home|question|rationale|correct|incorrect ; side: left|right
  const src = React.useMemo(() => pickMascot(state), [state]);
  if (!src) return null;
  return (
    <img className={"mascot mascot-" + state + " mascot-" + (side || "right")}
         src={src} alt="Professor Tecson" draggable="false" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
  );
}

// ---------- question renderers ----------
function Html({ html, className }) {
  return <div className={className} dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: html }} />;
}

function QuestionCard({ item, response, setResponse, locked, comprehensive }) {
  const onMC = (id) => { if (!locked) setResponse([id]); };
  const onSATA = (id) => {
    if (locked) return;
    const cur = new Set(response || []);
    cur.has(id) ? cur.delete(id) : cur.add(id);
    setResponse([...cur]);
  };
  const onCloze = (key, oid) => {
    if (locked) return;
    setResponse({ ...(response || {}), [key]: oid });
  };
  const onMatch = (l, r) => {
    if (locked) return;
    setResponse({ ...(response || {}), [l]: r });
  };

  return (
    <div className="qcard">
      {!locked ? <Mascot state="question" side="right" /> : null}
      <div className="qtags">
        {item.verified ? <VerifiedTag/> : <VerifyTag/>}
        {/* In Comprehensive mode the domain stays hidden until the answer is
            locked (the rationale reveal), the way the real exam comes at you. */}
        <span className="qdomain">{(comprehensive && !locked) ? "???" : DOMAIN_SHORT[item.domain]}</span>
        <span className={"qtype qtype-" + item.type}>{labelType(item.type)}</span>
      </div>

      <Html className="qstem" html={item.stem} />
      {item.imageRhythm ? <Strip rhythm={item.imageRhythm} /> : null}

      {(item.type === "mc" || item.type === "sata") && (
        <div className="opts" role={item.type === "mc" ? "radiogroup" : "group"}>
          {item.options.map(o => {
            const chosen = (response || []).includes(o.id);
            const isCorrect = item.correct.includes(o.id);
            let cls = "opt";
            if (chosen) cls += " opt-chosen";
            if (locked && isCorrect) cls += " opt-correct";
            if (locked && chosen && !isCorrect) cls += " opt-wrong";
            return (
              <button key={o.id} type="button" className={cls}
                aria-pressed={chosen}
                onClick={() => item.type === "mc" ? onMC(o.id) : onSATA(o.id)}
                disabled={locked}>
                <span className="opt-mark" aria-hidden="true">
                  {item.type === "sata"
                    ? (chosen ? "■" : "□")
                    : (chosen ? "●" : "○")}
                </span>
                <span className="opt-text" dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: o.text }} />
                {locked && isCorrect ? <span className="opt-flag opt-flag-ok">✓</span> : null}
                {locked && chosen && !isCorrect ? <span className="opt-flag opt-flag-no">✕</span> : null}
              </button>
            );
          })}
          {item.type === "sata" && <p className="sata-hint">Select all that apply — partial credit per option.</p>}
        </div>
      )}

      {item.type === "cloze" && (
        <div className="cloze">
          {item.blanks.map((b, bi) => (
            <div className="cloze-row" key={b.key}>
              <span className="cloze-label">Blank {bi + 1}</span>
              <div className="cloze-opts">
                {b.options.map(o => {
                  const chosen = response && response[b.key] === o.id;
                  const isC = b.correct === o.id;
                  let cls = "chip";
                  if (chosen) cls += " chip-chosen";
                  if (locked && isC) cls += " chip-correct";
                  if (locked && chosen && !isC) cls += " chip-wrong";
                  return (
                    <button key={o.id} type="button" className={cls}
                      onClick={() => onCloze(b.key, o.id)} disabled={locked} aria-pressed={chosen}>
                      <span dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: o.text }} />
                      {locked && isC ? <span className="opt-flag opt-flag-ok">✓</span> : null}
                    </button>
                  );
                })}
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      )}

      {item.type === "matching" && (
        <div className="matching">
          {item.leftPrompts.map(lp => {
            const sel = response && response[lp.id];
            return (
              <div className="match-row" key={lp.id}>
                <div className="match-left" dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: lp.text }} />
                <div className="match-rights">
                  {item.rightOptions.map(ro => {
                    const chosen = sel === ro.id;
                    const correctPair = item.pairs.find(p => p[0] === lp.id);
                    const isC = correctPair && correctPair[1] === ro.id;
                    let cls = "mchip";
                    if (chosen) cls += " mchip-chosen";
                    if (locked && isC) cls += " mchip-correct";
                    if (locked && chosen && !isC) cls += " mchip-wrong";
                    return (
                      <button key={ro.id} type="button" className={cls}
                        onClick={() => onMatch(lp.id, ro.id)} disabled={locked} aria-pressed={chosen}
                        title={ro.text.replace(/<[^>]+>/g,'')}>
                        <span dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: ro.text }} />
                      </button>
                    );
                  })}
                </div>
              </div>
            );
          })}
          <p className="sata-hint">Pick the best match on each row — partial credit per row.</p>
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

function labelType(t){
  return t==="mc"?"Single":t==="sata"?"SATA":t==="cloze"?"Cloze":t==="matching"?"Matching":t;
}

function hasResponse(item, resp){
  if (item.type==="mc"||item.type==="sata") return resp && resp.length>0;
  if (item.type==="cloze") return resp && Object.keys(resp).length===item.blanks.length;
  if (item.type==="matching") return resp && Object.keys(resp).length===item.leftPrompts.length;
  return false;
}

// ---------- round engine ----------
function Round({ pool, title, subtitle, onExit, comprehensive }) {
  const [order] = useState(() => shuffle(pool));
  const [idx, setIdx] = useState(0);
  const [resp, setResp] = useState(null);
  const [locked, setLocked] = useState(false);
  const [score, setScore] = useState(0);
  const [maxScore, setMaxScore] = useState(0);
  const [streak, setStreak] = useState(0);
  const [bestStreak, setBestStreak] = useState(0);
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]); // {domain, earned, max, full}
  const [done, setDone] = useState(false);
  const liveRef = useRef(null);

  const item = order[idx];
  const grade = locked ? gradeItem(item, resp) : null;

  const submit = () => {
    if (locked || !hasResponse(item, resp)) return;
    const g = gradeItem(item, resp);
    setScore(s => +(s + g.earned).toFixed(3));
    setMaxScore(m => +(m + g.max).toFixed(3));
    setResults(r => [...r, { domain: item.domain, earned: g.earned, max: g.max, full: g.full }]);
    setStreak(prev => {
      const ns = g.full ? prev + 1 : 0;
      setBestStreak(b => Math.max(b, ns));
      return ns;
    });
    setLocked(true);
    if (liveRef.current) liveRef.current.textContent =
      g.full ? "Correct." : g.earned > 0 ? "Partially correct." : "Incorrect.";
  };

  const next = () => {
    if (idx + 1 >= order.length) { setDone(true); return; }
    setIdx(i => i + 1); setResp(null); setLocked(false);
  };

  if (done) {
    return <Summary results={results} score={score} maxScore={maxScore}
              bestStreak={bestStreak} comprehensive={comprehensive}
              onExit={onExit} total={order.length} />;
  }

  const pct = maxScore > 0 ? Math.round((score / maxScore) * 100) : 0;
  const progress = Math.round(((idx) / order.length) * 100);

  return (
    <div className="round">
      <div className="round-top">
        <button className="link-btn" onClick={() => onExit()}>← Menu</button>
        <div className="round-titles">
          <h2>{title}</h2>
          {subtitle ? <p>{subtitle}</p> : null}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div className="hud">
        <div className="hud-cell">
          <span className="hud-num">{score.toFixed(score % 1 ? 1 : 0)}<span className="hud-den">/{maxScore.toFixed(maxScore % 1 ? 1 : 0)}</span></span>
          <span className="hud-lbl">score</span>
        </div>
        <div className="hud-cell">
          <span className="hud-num">{pct}<span className="hud-den">%</span></span>
          <span className="hud-lbl">accuracy</span>
        </div>
        <div className={"hud-cell hud-streak" + (streak>=3?" hot":"")}>
          <span className="hud-num">{streak}{streak>=3?<span className="flame">▲</span>:null}</span>
          <span className="hud-lbl">streak</span>
        </div>
        <div className="hud-cell">
          <span className="hud-num">{idx + 1}<span className="hud-den">/{order.length}</span></span>
          <span className="hud-lbl">item</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div className="pbar"><div className="pbar-fill" style={{ width: progress + "%" }} /></div>

      <QuestionCard item={item} response={resp} setResponse={setResp} locked={locked} comprehensive={comprehensive} />

      <div className="sr-only" aria-live="polite" ref={liveRef} />

      {locked && (
        <div className={"feedback " + (grade.full ? "fb-full" : grade.earned > 0 ? "fb-part" : "fb-zero")}>
          <Mascot state={grade.full ? "correct" : "incorrect"} side="left" />
          <div className="fb-head">
            <span className="fb-verdict">
              {grade.full ? "Correct" : grade.earned > 0 ? "Partially correct" : "Incorrect"}
            </span>
            <span className="fb-pts">+{grade.earned.toFixed(grade.earned % 1 ? 1 : 0)} / {grade.max.toFixed(grade.max % 1 ? 1 : 0)}</span>
          </div>
          <Html className="fb-rationale" html={item.rationale} />
          {!item.verified && (
            <p className="fb-disclaimer">
              AI wrote this one. Vibe-check the answer against your notes, current AHA/ACLS guidance, and NCLEX standards before it counts.
            </p>
          )}
        </div>
      )}

      <div className="round-actions">
        {!locked
          ? <button className="btn-primary" onClick={submit} disabled={!hasResponse(item, resp)}>
              Check answer
            </button>
          : <button className="btn-primary" onClick={next}>
              {idx + 1 >= order.length ? "See results" : "Next item →"}
            </button>}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

// ---------- summary ----------
function Summary({ results, score, maxScore, bestStreak, comprehensive, onExit, total }) {
  const pct = maxScore > 0 ? Math.round((score / maxScore) * 100) : 0;
  const byDomain = {};
  results.forEach(r => {
    if (!byDomain[r.domain]) byDomain[r.domain] = { earned: 0, max: 0, full: 0, n: 0 };
    const d = byDomain[r.domain];
    d.earned += r.earned; d.max += r.max; d.n++; if (r.full) d.full++;
  });
  const domainRows = Object.entries(byDomain).map(([dom, d]) => ({
    dom, pct: d.max > 0 ? Math.round((d.earned / d.max) * 100) : 0, n: d.n, full: d.full
  })).sort((a, b) => a.pct - b.pct);
  const weakest = comprehensive && domainRows.length ? domainRows[0] : null;

  return (
    <div className="summary">
      <button className="link-btn" onClick={() => onExit()}>← Menu</button>
      <div className="sum-hero">
        <div className="sum-score-ring" style={{ "--p": pct }}>
          <span className="sum-score-num">{pct}%</span>
        </div>
        <div className="sum-hero-meta">
          <h2>Round complete</h2>
          <p>{score.toFixed(score % 1 ? 1 : 0)} of {maxScore.toFixed(maxScore % 1 ? 1 : 0)} points · {total} items · best streak {bestStreak}</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div className="sum-domains">
        <h3>By domain</h3>
        {domainRows.map(r => (
          <div className="sum-drow" key={r.dom}>
            <span className="sum-dname">{DOMAIN_SHORT[r.dom]}</span>
            <div className="sum-dbar"><div className="sum-dfill" style={{ width: r.pct + "%" }} /></div>
            <span className="sum-dpct">{r.pct}%</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      {weakest && (
        <div className="sum-weak">
          <p>Weakest area this round: <strong>{DOMAIN_SHORT[weakest.dom]}</strong> ({weakest.pct}%).</p>
          <button className="btn-primary" onClick={() => onExit(weakest.dom)}>
            Drill {DOMAIN_SHORT[weakest.dom]} →
          </button>
        </div>
      )}

      <button className="btn-ghost wide" onClick={() => onExit()}>Back to menu</button>
    </div>
  );
}

// ---------- menus ----------
function App() {
  const [view, setView] = useState({ name: "home" });

  // precompute pools
  const pools = useMemo(() => {
    const byDS = {}; // domain|section -> items
    DOMAINS.forEach(d => { byDS[d + "|S1"] = []; byDS[d + "|S2"] = []; });
    ITEMS.forEach(it => { byDS[it.domain + "|" + it.section].push(it); });
    return byDS;
  }, []);

  const counts = useMemo(() => {
    const c = { S1: {}, S2: {}, total: ITEMS.length,
                verified: ITEMS.filter(i=>i.verified).length,
                generated: ITEMS.filter(i=>!i.verified).length };
    DOMAINS.forEach(d => {
      c.S1[d] = pools[d + "|S1"].length;
      c.S2[d] = pools[d + "|S2"].length;
    });
    return c;
  }, [pools]);

  const startSection = (section, domain) => {
    const pool = pools[domain + "|" + section];
    const secName = section === "S1" ? "Memorization" : "Clinical Reasoning";
    setView({ name: "round", pool, title: DOMAIN_SHORT[domain],
      subtitle: secName + " · " + pool.length + " items", comprehensive: false });
  };

  const startComprehensive = (len) => {
    let pool = ITEMS.filter(i => i.section === "S2"); // reasoning pool, all domains
    pool = shuffle(pool);
    if (len !== "all") pool = pool.slice(0, len);
    setView({ name: "round", pool, title: "Comprehensive NGN",
      subtitle: pool.length + " mixed items · domain hidden", comprehensive: true });
  };

  const exitRound = (drillDomain) => {
    if (drillDomain) { startSection("S2", drillDomain); return; }
    setView({ name: "home" });
  };

  if (view.name === "round") {
    return (
      <Shell>
        <Round pool={view.pool} title={view.title} subtitle={view.subtitle}
          comprehensive={view.comprehensive} onExit={exitRound} />
      </Shell>
    );
  }
  if (view.name === "section") {
    return (
      <Shell>
        <SectionMenu section={view.section} counts={counts}
          onPick={(d) => startSection(view.section, d)}
          onBack={() => setView({ name: "home" })} />
      </Shell>
    );
  }
  if (view.name === "comp") {
    return (
      <Shell>
        <CompMenu onPick={startComprehensive} onBack={() => setView({ name: "home" })}
          poolSize={ITEMS.filter(i=>i.section==="S2").length} />
      </Shell>
    );
  }
  return (
    <Shell>
      <Home counts={counts}
        onSection={(s) => setView({ name: "section", section: s })}
        onComp={() => setView({ name: "comp" })} />
    </Shell>
  );
}

function Shell({ children }) {
  const reduce = typeof window !== "undefined" &&
    window.matchMedia && window.matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;
  return (
    <div className="app">
      <Style />
      <header className="masthead">
        <EkgTrace active={!reduce} />
        <div className="mast-inner">
          <div className="mast-brand">
            <span className="mast-kicker">N444 · EXAM 2</span>
            <h1>Cooked or Cooking</h1>
          </div>
          <span className="mast-tag">NGN review</span>
        </div>
      </header>
      <main className="main">{children}</main>
      <footer className="foot">
        Study tool · Verified items are from the course bank; generated items are practice and flagged for verification.
      </footer>
    </div>
  );
}

function Home({ counts, onSection, onComp }) {
  return (
    <div className="home">
      <div className="home-lede home-lede-mascot">
        <Mascot state="home" side="right" />
        <p>Three ways to lock in, bestie. Drill one domain till it lives in your head
        rent-free, speedrun clinical scenarios like the main character, or send it on a
        mixed set with the domain hidden — exactly how the exam tries to cook you. No cap.</p>
      </div>

      <div className="cards">
        <button className="mode-card" onClick={() => onSection("S1")}>
          <span className="mode-no">01</span>
          <h3>Memorization</h3>
          <p>Flashcard energy fr. Recognition, definitions, and reading strips till they're
          not even a thing anymore. One domain at a time — we lock in.</p>
          <span className="mode-meta">{sumVals(counts.S1)} items · 6 domains</span>
        </button>
        <button className="mode-card" onClick={() => onSection("S2")}>
          <span className="mode-no">02</span>
          <h3>Clinical Reasoning</h3>
          <p>Priority and "what happens next" brain. SATA, cloze, and bow-tie scenarios that
          will fully try to ratio you. Stay sigma, don't get cooked.</p>
          <span className="mode-meta">{sumVals(counts.S2)} items · 6 domains</span>
        </button>
        <button className="mode-card mode-card-accent" onClick={onComp}>
          <span className="mode-no">03</span>
          <h3>Comprehensive NGN</h3>
          <p>Everything, shuffled, zero labels — pure exam menace mode. Pick 10, 20, or the
          whole gauntlet. Reshuffles every round so you can't memorize the vibes.</p>
          <span className="mode-meta">mixed · domain hidden · no peeking</span>
        </button>
      </div>

      <div className="bankline">
        <span><strong>{counts.total}</strong> items</span>
        <span className="dot">·</span>
        <span className="bl-verified">{counts.verified} verified</span>
        <span className="dot">·</span>
        <span className="bl-gen">{counts.generated} generated</span>
        <span className="dot">·</span>
        <span>110 source questions → 89 concepts</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

function SectionMenu({ section, counts, onPick, onBack }) {
  const name = section === "S1" ? "Memorization" : "Clinical Reasoning";
  const c = section === "S1" ? counts.S1 : counts.S2;
  return (
    <div className="secmenu">
      <button className="link-btn" onClick={onBack}>← Menu</button>
      <h2 className="secmenu-h">{name}</h2>
      <p className="secmenu-sub">Pick a domain.</p>
      <div className="domgrid">
        {DOMAINS.map(d => (
          <button key={d} className="dom-card" onClick={() => onPick(d)} disabled={!c[d]}>
            <span className="dom-name">{DOMAIN_SHORT[d]}</span>
            <span className="dom-count">{c[d]} items</span>
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

function CompMenu({ onPick, onBack, poolSize }) {
  return (
    <div className="secmenu">
      <button className="link-btn" onClick={onBack}>← Menu</button>
      <h2 className="secmenu-h">Comprehensive NGN</h2>
      <p className="secmenu-sub">Mixed domains, hidden until the rationale. Round length:</p>
      <div className="lenrow">
        <button className="len-card" onClick={() => onPick(10)}><span className="len-n">10</span><span className="len-l">quick</span></button>
        <button className="len-card" onClick={() => onPick(20)}><span className="len-n">20</span><span className="len-l">standard</span></button>
        <button className="len-card" onClick={() => onPick("all")}><span className="len-n">{poolSize}</span><span className="len-l">full set</span></button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

function sumVals(o){ return Object.values(o).reduce((a,b)=>a+b,0); }

export default App;

// ---------- styles ----------
function Style() {
  return <style>{CSS}</style>;
}
const CSS = `
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Space+Grotesk:wght@400;500;600;700&family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@500;700&display=swap');

* { box-sizing: border-box; }
:root{
  --bg:#0B0F14; --bezel:#11171F; --panel:#161E28; --panel2:#1B2530;
  --line:#26323F; --line2:#33424F;
  --green:#3DF5A0; --green-dim:#1f7d57; --green-glow:rgba(61,245,160,.25);
  --amber:#FFB454; --red:#FF5C6C;
  --ink:#E8EDF2; --muted:#8094A6; --faint:#5B6B7A;
  --r:14px;
}
.app{
  min-height:100vh; background:
    radial-gradient(1200px 600px at 50% -10%, #121A24 0%, var(--bg) 55%) fixed;
  color:var(--ink);
  font-family:Inter,system-ui,sans-serif;
  -webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased;
}
.main{ max-width:760px; margin:0 auto; padding:22px 18px 60px; }

/* masthead + ekg signature */
.masthead{ position:relative; overflow:hidden; border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);
  background:linear-gradient(180deg,#0E141B, #0B0F14); }
.mast-inner{ position:relative; z-index:2; max-width:760px; margin:0 auto;
  padding:20px 18px 16px; display:flex; align-items:flex-end; justify-content:space-between; gap:12px; }
.mast-kicker{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:11px; letter-spacing:.22em;
  color:var(--green); opacity:.85; }
.mast-brand h1{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-weight:700; font-size:30px;
  margin:.12em 0 0; letter-spacing:-.01em; line-height:1; }
.mast-tag{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:11px; color:var(--muted);
  border:1px solid var(--line2); border-radius:999px; padding:5px 11px; white-space:nowrap; }
.ekg-trace{ position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; z-index:1; opacity:.5; }
.ekg-path{ fill:none; stroke:var(--green); stroke-width:1.6; opacity:.55;
  filter:drop-shadow(0 0 5px var(--green-glow)); stroke-dasharray:1200; stroke-dashoffset:0; }
.ekg-path.pulse{ animation:sweep 4.2s linear infinite; }
@keyframes sweep{ from{stroke-dashoffset:1200;} to{stroke-dashoffset:0;} }

/* home */
.home-lede p{ color:var(--muted); font-size:15.5px; line-height:1.6; margin:6px 2px 22px; }
.cards{ display:grid; gap:13px; }
.mode-card{ text-align:left; background:var(--panel); border:1px solid var(--line);
  border-radius:var(--r); padding:20px 20px 16px; cursor:pointer; color:var(--ink);
  position:relative; transition:border-color .18s, transform .18s, background .18s; }
.mode-card:hover{ border-color:var(--line2); background:var(--panel2); transform:translateY(-2px); }
.mode-no{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:12px; color:var(--faint); letter-spacing:.1em; }
.mode-card h3{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-size:20px; margin:4px 0 6px; font-weight:600; }
.mode-card p{ color:var(--muted); font-size:14px; line-height:1.55; margin:0 0 12px; }
.mode-meta{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:11.5px; color:var(--faint); }
.mode-card-accent{ border-color:var(--green-dim); background:linear-gradient(180deg,#13211B,#13191F); }
.mode-card-accent:hover{ border-color:var(--green); }
.mode-card-accent .mode-no{ color:var(--green); }

.bankline{ margin-top:22px; padding:13px 16px; border:1px solid var(--line);
  border-radius:10px; background:#0F151C; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px; align-items:center;
  font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:12px; color:var(--muted); }
.bankline strong{ color:var(--ink); }
.bl-verified{ color:var(--green); } .bl-gen{ color:var(--amber); }
.bankline .dot{ color:var(--faint); }

/* section + comp menus */
.link-btn{ background:none; border:none; color:var(--green); font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;
  font-size:13px; cursor:pointer; padding:6px 0; margin-bottom:8px; }
.link-btn:hover{ text-decoration:underline; }
.secmenu-h{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-size:24px; margin:6px 0 2px; }
.secmenu-sub{ color:var(--muted); font-size:14px; margin:0 0 18px; }
.domgrid{ display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(2,1fr); gap:11px; }
.dom-card{ text-align:left; background:var(--panel); border:1px solid var(--line);
  border-radius:12px; padding:16px; cursor:pointer; color:var(--ink); display:flex;
  flex-direction:column; gap:5px; transition:border-color .18s, background .18s; }
.dom-card:hover:not(:disabled){ border-color:var(--green-dim); background:var(--panel2); }
.dom-card:disabled{ opacity:.4; cursor:not-allowed; }
.dom-name{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-weight:600; font-size:16px; }
.dom-count{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:12px; color:var(--faint); }
.lenrow{ display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr); gap:11px; }
.len-card{ background:var(--panel); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:12px;
  padding:22px 12px; cursor:pointer; color:var(--ink); display:flex; flex-direction:column;
  align-items:center; gap:6px; transition:border-color .18s, background .18s; }
.len-card:hover{ border-color:var(--green); background:var(--panel2); }
.len-n{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-weight:700; font-size:26px; color:var(--green); }
.len-l{ font-size:12px; color:var(--muted); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.1em; }

/* round */
.round-top{ display:flex; align-items:flex-start; gap:14px; margin-bottom:14px; }
.round-titles h2{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-size:19px; margin:0; }
.round-titles p{ color:var(--muted); font-size:12.5px; margin:2px 0 0;
  font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; }

.hud{ display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(4,1fr); gap:8px; margin-bottom:12px; }
.hud-cell{ background:var(--bezel); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:10px;
  padding:9px 6px 7px; text-align:center; }
.hud-num{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-weight:700; font-size:21px; color:var(--ink);
  display:block; line-height:1; }
.hud-den{ font-size:12px; color:var(--faint); font-weight:500; }
.hud-lbl{ font-size:10px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.13em; color:var(--faint); }
.hud-streak.hot .hud-num{ color:var(--green); text-shadow:0 0 12px var(--green-glow); }
.flame{ font-size:13px; margin-left:2px; }

.pbar{ height:4px; background:var(--line); border-radius:99px; overflow:hidden; margin-bottom:18px; }
.pbar-fill{ height:100%; background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--green-dim),var(--green));
  transition:width .35s ease; }

/* question card */
.qcard{ background:var(--panel); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:var(--r);
  padding:18px 18px 20px; }
.qtags{ display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:7px; align-items:center; margin-bottom:13px; padding-right:84px; }
.tag-verified,.tag-unverified{ display:inline-flex; align-items:center; gap:4px;
  font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:10.5px; padding:3px 8px; border-radius:999px;
  letter-spacing:.02em; }
.tag-verified{ color:var(--green); background:rgba(61,245,160,.08); border:1px solid var(--green-dim); }
.tag-unverified{ color:var(--amber); background:rgba(255,180,84,.08); border:1px solid #6b5128; }
.qdomain{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:10.5px; color:var(--muted);
  margin-left:auto; }
.qtype{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:10px; padding:3px 7px; border-radius:6px;
  background:var(--panel2); color:var(--muted); border:1px solid var(--line); text-transform:uppercase;
  letter-spacing:.08em; }
.qstem{ font-size:16px; line-height:1.55; color:var(--ink); }
.qstem div{ margin:0; }
.qstem strong{ color:#fff; }

/* strip */
.strip{ margin:14px 0 4px; border:1px solid var(--line2); border-radius:10px; overflow:hidden;
  background:#060A0E; cursor:zoom-in; position:relative; }
.strip img{ width:100%; display:block; image-rendering:auto; }
.strip-zoom{ cursor:zoom-out; }
.strip-zoom img{ width:auto; min-width:100%; }
.strip-hint{ position:absolute; right:8px; bottom:7px; font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;
  font-size:10px; color:var(--green); background:rgba(0,0,0,.6); padding:2px 7px; border-radius:6px; }

/* options */
.opts{ margin-top:15px; display:grid; gap:9px; }
.opt{ display:flex; align-items:flex-start; gap:11px; text-align:left; width:100%;
  background:var(--panel2); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:11px; padding:13px 14px;
  color:var(--ink); cursor:pointer; font-size:14.5px; line-height:1.45;
  transition:border-color .15s, background .15s; }
.opt:hover:not(:disabled){ border-color:var(--line2); }
.opt-mark{ color:var(--faint); font-size:15px; line-height:1.4; flex-shrink:0; }
.opt-chosen{ border-color:var(--green); background:rgba(61,245,160,.07); }
.opt-chosen .opt-mark{ color:var(--green); }
.opt-correct{ border-color:var(--green); background:rgba(61,245,160,.12); }
.opt-wrong{ border-color:var(--red); background:rgba(255,92,108,.1); }
.opt-text{ flex:1; } .opt-text p{ margin:0; }
.opt-flag{ font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0; }
.opt-flag-ok{ color:var(--green); } .opt-flag-no{ color:var(--red); }
.opt:disabled{ cursor:default; }
.sata-hint{ font-size:12px; color:var(--faint); margin:9px 2px 0; font-style:italic; }

/* cloze */
.cloze{ margin-top:15px; display:grid; gap:13px; }
.cloze-row{ background:var(--panel2); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:11px; padding:12px; }
.cloze-label{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:11px; color:var(--green);
  display:block; margin-bottom:9px; letter-spacing:.05em; }
.cloze-opts{ display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:7px; }
.chip{ background:var(--bezel); border:1px solid var(--line2); border-radius:9px; padding:8px 12px;
  color:var(--ink); cursor:pointer; font-size:13.5px; transition:border-color .15s, background .15s; }
.chip:hover:not(:disabled){ border-color:var(--muted); }
.chip-chosen{ border-color:var(--green); background:rgba(61,245,160,.1); }
.chip-correct{ border-color:var(--green); background:rgba(61,245,160,.16); }
.chip-wrong{ border-color:var(--red); background:rgba(255,92,108,.12); }

/* matching */
.matching{ margin-top:15px; display:grid; gap:11px; }
.match-row{ background:var(--panel2); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:11px; padding:12px; }
.match-left{ font-size:14px; font-weight:500; margin-bottom:9px; color:#fff; }
.match-left p{ margin:0; }
.match-rights{ display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:6px; }
.mchip{ background:var(--bezel); border:1px solid var(--line2); border-radius:8px; padding:7px 11px;
  color:var(--muted); cursor:pointer; font-size:12.5px; max-width:100%; transition:border-color .15s,color .15s,background .15s; }
.mchip:hover:not(:disabled){ border-color:var(--muted); color:var(--ink); }
.mchip-chosen{ border-color:var(--green); color:var(--ink); background:rgba(61,245,160,.08); }
.mchip-correct{ border-color:var(--green); color:var(--green); background:rgba(61,245,160,.12); }
.mchip-wrong{ border-color:var(--red); color:#ffb3bb; background:rgba(255,92,108,.1); }
.mchip span p{ margin:0; display:inline; }

/* feedback */
.feedback{ margin-top:16px; border-radius:12px; padding:15px 16px; border:1px solid var(--line); }
.fb-full{ border-color:var(--green-dim); background:rgba(61,245,160,.06); }
.fb-part{ border-color:#6b5128; background:rgba(255,180,84,.06); }
.fb-zero{ border-color:#5e2730; background:rgba(255,92,108,.06); }
.fb-head{ display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:9px; }
.fb-verdict{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-weight:600; font-size:15px; }
.fb-full .fb-verdict{ color:var(--green); }
.fb-part .fb-verdict{ color:var(--amber); }
.fb-zero .fb-verdict{ color:var(--red); }
.fb-pts{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:13px; color:var(--muted); }
.fb-rationale{ font-size:14px; line-height:1.55; color:var(--ink); }
.fb-rationale p{ margin:0; } .fb-rationale strong{ color:#fff; }
.fb-disclaimer{ margin:11px 0 0; font-size:12px; line-height:1.5; color:var(--amber);
  border-top:1px solid #4a3a1d; padding-top:9px; }

/* actions */
.round-actions{ margin-top:18px; }
.btn-primary{ width:100%; background:var(--green); color:#06120C; border:none; border-radius:12px;
  padding:15px; font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-weight:600; font-size:16px; cursor:pointer;
  transition:filter .15s, transform .1s; }
.btn-primary:hover:not(:disabled){ filter:brightness(1.08); }
.btn-primary:active:not(:disabled){ transform:scale(.99); }
.btn-primary:disabled{ background:var(--line2); color:var(--faint); cursor:not-allowed; }
.btn-ghost{ background:var(--panel); color:var(--ink); border:1px solid var(--line2);
  border-radius:12px; padding:13px; font-size:14px; cursor:pointer; font-family:Inter,sans-serif; }
.btn-ghost:hover{ border-color:var(--muted); }
.btn-ghost.wide{ width:100%; margin-top:18px; }

/* summary */
.sum-hero{ display:flex; align-items:center; gap:20px; margin:8px 0 24px; }
.sum-score-ring{ --p:0; width:104px; height:104px; border-radius:50%; flex-shrink:0;
  background:conic-gradient(var(--green) calc(var(--p)*1%), var(--line) 0);
  display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content:center; position:relative; }
.sum-score-ring::after{ content:""; position:absolute; inset:9px; border-radius:50%; background:var(--bg); }
.sum-score-num{ position:relative; z-index:1; font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-weight:700;
  font-size:26px; color:var(--green); }
.sum-hero-meta h2{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-size:22px; margin:0 0 4px; }
.sum-hero-meta p{ color:var(--muted); font-size:13px; margin:0; font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; }
.sum-domains h3{ font-family:'Space Grotesk',sans-serif; font-size:15px; margin:0 0 12px; color:var(--muted);
  text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.1em; }
.sum-drow{ display:flex; align-items:center; gap:12px; margin-bottom:10px; }
.sum-dname{ width:110px; font-size:13.5px; flex-shrink:0; }
.sum-dbar{ flex:1; height:8px; background:var(--line); border-radius:99px; overflow:hidden; }
.sum-dfill{ height:100%; background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--green-dim),var(--green)); border-radius:99px; }
.sum-dpct{ font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace; font-size:13px; color:var(--muted); width:38px; text-align:right; }
.sum-weak{ margin-top:22px; padding:16px; border:1px solid var(--green-dim); border-radius:12px;
  background:rgba(61,245,160,.05); }
.sum-weak p{ margin:0 0 12px; font-size:14.5px; }
.sum-weak strong{ color:var(--green); }

/* foot */
.foot{ max-width:760px; margin:0 auto; padding:18px; text-align:center; font-size:11.5px;
  color:var(--faint); line-height:1.5; border-top:1px solid var(--line); }

/* a11y */
.sr-only{ position:absolute; width:1px; height:1px; padding:0; margin:-1px; overflow:hidden;
  clip:rect(0,0,0,0); white-space:nowrap; border:0; }
button:focus-visible,[role=button]:focus-visible{ outline:2px solid var(--green); outline-offset:2px; }

@media (max-width:560px){
  .mast-brand h1{ font-size:25px; }
  .cards{ gap:11px; }
  .hud-num{ font-size:18px; }
  .domgrid{ grid-template-columns:1fr; }
  .sum-dname{ width:84px; font-size:12.5px; }
  .qstem{ font-size:15px; }
}
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){
  .ekg-path.pulse{ animation:none; }
  *{ transition:none !important; }
}
/* mascot */
.mascot{ height:118px; width:auto; object-fit:contain; pointer-events:none;
  filter:drop-shadow(0 6px 14px rgba(0,0,0,.45)); }
.home-lede-mascot{ display:flex; align-items:center; gap:16px; }
.home-lede-mascot p{ margin:0; flex:1; }
.home-lede-mascot .mascot{ height:150px; flex-shrink:0; }
.qcard{ position:relative; }
.mascot-question{ position:absolute; top:-6px; right:10px; height:92px; opacity:.96; }
.feedback{ display:flex; align-items:flex-start; gap:14px; flex-wrap:wrap; }
.feedback .mascot{ height:104px; flex-shrink:0; }
.feedback .fb-head{ flex:1; min-width:60%; }
.fb-rationale, .fb-disclaimer{ flex-basis:100%; }
@media (max-width:560px){
  .home-lede-mascot{ flex-direction:column; text-align:center; }
  .home-lede-mascot .mascot{ height:128px; }
  .mascot-question{ height:64px; top:-2px; right:4px; }
  .qtags{ padding-right:58px; }
  .feedback .mascot{ height:80px; }
}

`;
